<1ST_LINE>r p PM-WashingtonSenate Bjt   10-24 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington Senate, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorton, Lowry Change Styles In Hopes of Capturing Senate Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Altering images is the tack both Slade
Gorton and Mike Lowry are following in their quest for the U.S.
Senate with the former Republican senator hoping to revive his
political career and the Democratic congressman looking to move up
to a six-year job.
   Lowry, a five-term representative, has calmed his bombastic
rhetoric and trademark arm-flailing, shaven his Yasser Arafat-style
beard, pressed his usually rumpled suits and sworn off beer for the
campaign.
   Gorton has been apologetic about his failure to listen and a
number of his earlier Senate votes, and is warming an icy, detached
image that he blames in large part for his loss to Democrat Brock
Adams two years ago.
   That defeat also stems from Gorton's infamous vote swap. In May
1986, the White House agreed to nominate liberal Democrat William
L. Dwyer _ a Gorton recommendation _ to the federal bench only
after Gorton, then a freshman senator, agreed to provide the last
vote needed to confirm conservative lawyer Daniel Manion as a
federal appeals judge.
   For all the style changes, the liberal Democrat and
moderate-to-conservative Republican remain neck-and-neck in
Washington's first Senate race in 44 years without an incumbent.
   Republican Sen. Dan Evans surprised the political establishment
when he decided to step down after serving the remaining five years
of the late Sen. Henry M. ``Scoop'' Jackson's term.
   Polls conducted earlier this month found Gorton holding a slight
lead over Lowry, but based on the margin of error in the surveys
the contest is a dead heat.
   Yet on issues ranging from defense and taxation to the war on
drugs and abortion, the candidates remain far apart.
   Lowry wants to cut military spending, especially on defense
systems such as Star Wars and the MX missile, and use the money for
education, health, transportation, public works and housing.
   Gorton, a former Air Force officer, insists the nation is more
secure because of the military build-up over the last eight years
and warns that ``we shouldn't abandon any deterrent system'' before
gaining concessions in arms talks with the Soviets.
   Gorton favors construction of a Navy homeport for the U.S.
Nimitz carrier task force at Everett on Puget Sound. Lowry calls it
an environmentally hazardous ``home pork.''
   When the House passed a controversial anti-drug law to impose
the death penalty on drug murderers and slap heavy fines on users,
Lowry was one of only 30 votes against it. He opposed a number of
the bill's provisos as unconstitutional.
   Gorton cited Lowry's vote as another sign he is out of step with
the state of Washington, where drugs and gangs emigrating north
from California have become more common.
   Gorton says no to federal tax hikes; Lowry has not ruled them
out.
   The Senate hopefuls both are fighting to be seen as the
candidate of the broad middle of the electorate, particularly the
Reagan Democrats and independents who will swing the election.
   Lowry says his progressive brand of politics fits
Democratic-leaning Washington. Gorton says his own more
conservative approach is in the mainstream and that Lowry is a
liberal maverick who's out of step.
   This diversity has failed to move either candidate into a clear
lead with the Nov. 8 election looming.
   ``Mike Lowry is a tough competitor, no question about that,''
concedes Gorton. ``He has done a good job of moderating his image
from the way he presents himself in Congress to the middle of the
road out here.
   ``I am an awful lot closer to the views of the vast majority of
people. I am in fact, both in philosophy and in voting record, a
moderate conservative. That is what the vast majority of the people
feel comfortable with. Mike is a dedicated and articulate liberal
in Congress.''
   Lowry disagrees with Gorton's assessment of the voters, if not
Lowry's record.
   ``We have an excellent chance of winning because the people of
the state of Washington agree with us on the issues,'' he said.
``When you compare Slade's record in six years in the Senate and my
10 in the House, the choice is clear.''
</TEXT>
