<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ClubofRome Bjt   10-24 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Club of Rome, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Age 20, International Think Tank Turns To Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Club of Rome, best known for its first report
warning of the dangers unlimited growth pose to the planet, is
bringing together thinkers and world leaders this week to celebrate
its 20th anniversary.
   And in addition to fostering discussion on what it calls `a new
global society,'' the club plans internal changes that will for the
first time seek to turn its ideas into action.
   Club members come from 51 countries _ rich and poor, capitalist,
socialist and communist.
   ``I think we are at a turning point in the life of the club
after 20 years,'' Secretary-General Bertrand Schneider said in an
interview in his Paris office.
   The Club of Rome _ which despite its name has been based in
Paris since 1984 _ was founded by Italian industrialist Aurelio
Peccei and Scottish scientist Alexander King in 1968 as a sort of
floating international think tank.
   The club committed itself to approaching issues from a global
perspective, with a sense that problems like pollution,
overpopulation, hunger or the impact of developing technologies are
interdependent.
   ``Governments and international organizations are stuck in the
day-to-day management of problems. They usually have no time for
long-term thinking. We have a special mission. We have no
responsibility to anybody except ourselves,'' Schneider said.
   At this week's conference, such international figures as Prince
Sadruddin Aga Khan, former President Belisario Betancur of
Colombia, Crown Prince Hassan of Jordan and International Monetary
Fund Director Michel Camdessus are meeting to discuss ``Reasons to
Live and to Hope in a New Global Society.''
   A highlight will be a session Friday night at the Sorbonne
intended to be an exchange between the club's luminaries and youth
of the world.
   ``In a world that has become so young, we need their help to
understand the world,'' Schneider said. ``It's important for us,
and for them, to exchange our experiences.''
   The club's first report, ``Limits to Growth,'' was the spark for
a worldwide reassessment of the environmental, economic and social
dangers of untrammeled expansion.
   Published as a book, the report has sold 10 million copies in 27
languages.
   ``It provoked a very passionate debate all around the world, and
it's not finished,'' Schneider said. ``The idea of Zero Growth has
been falsely attributed to the Club of Rome. Some industrialists
did not like the idea at all, of course.''
   The club's commitment to act, as well as talk, is about to have
its first major test in a development project scheduled to start
next year in eight countries of the drought-prone Sahel in Africa.
   The project will coordinate U.N. forces, local government and
aid organizations to promote development and reclaim land from the
spreading desert.
   Schneider said the club is to be the ``catalyst'' rather than
the planner or organizer of the project.
   ``The peaceful U.N. force is to assure logistics of stopping the
desertification and starting development, building camps and
greenhouses, digging wells, planting trees, ensuring communications
and transport,'' he said.
   It is intended to last at least five years, but the hope is to
make rapid progress ``in order that the population can see the
immediate improvement in their daily lives.''
   In its private sessions this week, the club intends to overhaul
its organization, establishing a collective presidency, increasing
its visibility and setting up a budget, for the first time.
   ``We started by saying that we were a non-organization. Now we
all accept the fact that we are a small, modest organization, but
an organization,'' Schneider said.
   ``We think that in a world which is very often blocked by
ideologies, bureaucracies and economic short-term interests, we
offer the flexibility, the informality and the possibility for very
quick decision and intervention, which may be useful for the whole
world community.''
</TEXT>
