<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     10-24 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Democrats Will `Grasp At Any Straw'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Quayle's event at 9:35 a.m. EDT; Top planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle is accusing the Democrats
of trying to polarize the electorate and predicts that presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis will ``grasp at any straw'' in the final
two weeks of the campaign.
   ``We can't take anything for ganted,'' the vice presidential
nominee said in exhorting a Louisville riverboat audience to work
hard for the GOP ticket headed by Quayle's running mate, George
Bush.
   Later at a rally in Lexington, Quayle outlasted a sizable group
of pro-Dukakis demonstrators who disrupted his indoor rally with
repeated chanting.
   ``What they don't want to hear is the truth,'' an unruffled
Quayle said as the demonstrators waved Dukakis signs and placards
linking Bush to Panamanian ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Quayle was campaigning today in Lexington before traveling to
Stone Mountain and Augusta, Ga., and later Florida. Both Southern
states are considered likely wins for Bush, but Quayle is making
the trip to help GOP candidates, in particular senate contender
Connie Mack III of Florida.
   On Monday, at the riverboat fund-raising event on the Ohio
River, Quayle talked about the intensity and negativism heading
into the home stretch of the campaign.
   ``Boy is it getting nasty out there ... they'll grasp at any
straw. They're going to try and polarize the American electorate.
They'll say anything that comes to their mind whether it's true or
not,'' he said.
   Later, Quayle's rowdy indoor rally was disrupted by a loud group
of Dukakis supporters chanting, ``No more lies'' and
``Bush-Noriega.''
   Quayle interrupted his remarks to respond to the protesters.
Gesturing in their direction, he said, ``If I had to support
Michael Dukakis, I'd yell too. I would shout and scream and yell
because he ain't gonna make it.''
   The demonstrators, however, continued chanting, nearly drowning
out the candidate in the outer corridor of Rupp Arena.
   But Quayle prevailed, proceeding to attack Dukakis to the
delight of the Bush-Quayle supporters who burst into chants of
``Good Night, Mike.''
   Earlier Monday, Quayle branded it a diversionary tactic for
former Democratic candidate Jesse Jackson and Quayle's vice
presidential opponent, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, to accuse the
Bush campaign of racists appeals.
   ``It's totally absurd. I think it shows just how desperate they
really are to start fanning the fires of racism in this country,''
Quayle told reporters aboard his campaign plane en route to
Missouri.
   Jackson alleged the Bush campaign was sending a racial signal by
hammering Dukakis over the case of convicted murderer Willie
Horton, Jr. Horton, a black man on a weekend furlough from a
Massachusetts prison, brutalized a Maryland couple.
   In Missouri, Quayle used a stop at East Central College in Union
to toss a baseball around and take a shot at Dukakis.
   Reporters noted after Quayle hit a couple of grounders that
Dukakis also likes to play baseball now and then on the campaign
trail and asked Quayle how he thought he would do against the
Massachusetts governor.
   Quayle laughed and said, ``I never served with Michael Dukakis
and I don't know him but he's no baseball player.''
   The remark was a paraphrase of a Bentsen putdown of Quayle when
the Republican compared himself with President John Kennedy during
the vice presidential debate.
</TEXT>
