<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SovietCredit     10-24 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Credit,0838</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West European Bankers Making Major Deals With Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West European bankers are
offering the Soviets huge amounts of credit to use in modernizing
their consumer economy, but Japan's relations with Moscow are cool
and its bankers are holding back.
   State Department sources in Washington emphasize that the deals
do not involve direct loans, but lines of credit, which become
loans only as the available credit is used.
   They said the credit lines appear designed to finance specific
trade arrangements and cannot be classed as ``untied loans'' _
money to be spent however the borrower chooses.
   The Unites States does not oppose lending at market rates for
non-strategic purposes but is against government subsidies of
loans, the sources said on condition of anonymity.
   Peter Pietsch, a finance and trade expert with West Germany's
Commerzbank, told The Associated Press: ``Credit not only from West
Germany but from all of Western Europe will be increasing and
expanding in coming years.''
   ``This has to do with the Soviet Union's goal of opening up
politically and economically, which also includes an increase in
trade activities,'' said Pietsch, whose institution is the
third-largest private bank in the country.
   ``The Soviets can only accomplish more activity in trade if they
have enough loans from Western countries. By helping the Soviet
Union modernize now, we can create the climate and conditions for
an even larger trade market in the future.''
   Commerzbank is part of a consortium of West German banks _ led
by Deutsche Bank, the country's largest _ that arranged a credit of
$1.6 billion.
   It was established to finance West German exports to the Soviet
Union, particularly in the food, leather, textile and clothing
industries.
   Officials signed the agreement Oct. 17, a week before Chancellor
Helmut Kohl began a visit to Moscow that is expected to produce
major benefits for West German businesses eager to expand trade.
   Other bankers in Western Europe are either following the German
lead or preparing to do so.
   On Oct. 14, Italy set up an export credit worth $775 million it
said was intended to help the Soviets modernize, with the money to
be used only to buy machinery in Italy for the production of
consumer goods. A group of banks led by the state-owned
Mediocredito Centrale organized the deal.
   London bankers involved in trade talks between Britain and the
Soviet Union confirmed Thursday they were willing to provide a
credit of $1.74 billion.
   Sir Michael Palliser, deputy chairman of Midland Bank PLC, told
a news conference the banks had agreed on a package of proposals
and a representative of the group would make a formal proposal next
week in Moscow.
   Bankers said 85 percent of the credit line would be backed by
the British government's Export Credits Guarantee Department.
   Other banks involved are the London-based Moscow Narodny Bank
Ltd., Barclays, Lloyd's Bank, National Westminster, Bank of
Scotland and Morgan Grenfell Group.
   Alan Clarke and Konstantin Katushev, the British and Soviet
trade ministers, also announced an agreement Thursday for
manufacturing of light commercial vehicles in the Soviet Union,
worth up to $297 million, and a small joint venture in photocopying.
   Katushev said the British credit line and those from West
Germany and Italy would be used primarily to modernize light
industry.
   ``We have enterprises with equipment that doesn't meet modern
requirements, and we have enterprises that don't have enough
capacity,'' he said.
   In France, the respected newspaper Le Monde reported last week
that a French consortium was proposing a credit to the Soviet Union
worth about $2 billion. It said the group of banks was led by
Credit Lyonnais, France's second-largest.
   Francois Riche, spokesman for Credit Lyonnais, would not comment
on the Le Monde report but confirmed that Jean-Yves Haberer, the
bank president, would travel to the Soviet Union on Nov. 10.
   Riche said Credit Lyonnais has had frequent dealings with the
Soviets over many years.
   Japanese bankers are taking a much more cautious approach. An
analyst with the Long-Term Credit Bank in Tokyo said similar large
credits from his and other private Japanese institutions are
unlikely, mainly because of cool Soviet-Japanese relations
resulting from a territorial dispute.
   ``The government attitude toward the Soviets is not really
clear, so it is rather difficult for commercial banks to get
together and form a loan credit as they are currently doing in
Europe,'' he said on condition of anonymity.
   An analyst with the Industrial Bank of Japan added that
consortiums are not necessary in his country because Japanese banks
nearly alway negotiate individually. ``The Soviet Union has not
asked us for the loan credit,'' he said.
   Japan and the Kremlin still have not signed a World War II peace
treaty, and Japan demands the return of islands off Hokkaido taken
by the Soviets.
</TEXT>
