<1ST_LINE>r p PM-JacksonSupporters     10-24 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson Supporters,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Supporters Gradually Enter Dukakis Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson supporters who felt overlooked
by Michael Dukakis have gained strategic positions in the
Democratic presidential campaign, although Jackson's former manager
said it may be ``too little too late.''
   ``The kind of campaign we have going on in Michigan, the kind of
campaign we have going on in Ohio, is the kind of campaign we
should have had going on since Labor Day,'' said former Jackson
campaign manager Gerald Austin.
   In Michigan, where Dukakis lost to Jackson in a caucus landslide
in March, Joel Ferguson had been complaining that once the
Massachusetts governor secured the Democratic presidential
nomination, he sent in a bunch of out-of-towners to run his general
election campaign.
   Ferguson, who had managed Jackson's campaign in the state, said
a month ago that Jackson people virtually were being ignored and
that it could cost Dukakis the election in Michigan.
   This week, as Dukakis barnstormed the state to revive his
sagging candidacy, Ferguson was flying on the candidate's plane
with him.
   ``They listened to him, and I think you have a better campaign
in Michigan because Joel is involved,'' Austin said in a telephone
interview.
   In the first weeks after the Democratic National Convention last
July, the Dukakis campaign did hire former Jackson supporters, but
few had ``meaningful'' positions, Austin said.
   But Ron Brown, who was Jackson's convention manager and now is
an unpaid senior political adviser to the Dukakis campaign, said he
was unaware of anyone being brought into the Dukakis campaign
strictly for appearance's sake.
   Brown said the Dukakis campaign started bringing in Jackson
people right after the national convention, although he
acknowledged the process was slow at the campaign's Boston
headquarters and spotty in the state organizations.
   ``I'm not saying it was a perfectly smooth transition in every
state,'' Brown said. ``It wasn't.''
   Black voters did not appear to have been impressed by those
early efforts. A Gallup poll of 643 black voters taken in August
for the Joint Center for Political Studies found that 42 percent
thought Jackson had been mistreated at the national convention and
a third of that group said they were less likely to vote because of
it.
   Nationwide, the Dukakis campaign began moving former Jackson
operatives into responsible jobs in late September and early
October, Austin said.
   ``It could be too little too late,'' Austin said. ``I hope not.''
   Brown himself was brought into the Dukakis campaign in an
official capacity three weeks ago. His volunteer status is by his
own choice, he said.
   Austin said things began changing in September, after the return
of John Sasso, who resigned from the Dukakis campaign last year
following his admission of torpedoing Sen. Joseph Biden's candidacy
for the Democratic presidential nomination. One of Sasso's first
actions after rejoining the campaign was to meet with Jackson.
   ``I think now Jackson speaks to Dukakis two or three times a
week,'' Austin said. ``I think he talks to Sasso even more.''
   Jackson also is traveling around the country to rally support
for the Democratic ticket and has made radio commercials urging
people to vote.
   Dukakis attended a Sunday breakfast in Boston with Jackson and
eight other black political leaders who pledged to support the
Massachusetts governor's campaign in the remaining two weeks before
election.
   In Mississippi and Louisiana, among the dozen states and
territories Jackson won during the primaries, the Dukakis campaign
had little choice but to include Jackson supporters because they
control the state party.
   In Alabama, another Jackson state, the problem hasn't been
getting Dukakis to pay attention to the Jackson people but getting
him to pay attention to Alabama, said state Sen. Michael Figures, a
Jackson campaign leader in the state. Dukakis has been there only
once, and vice presidential running mate Lloyd Bentsen has not
campaigned there at all.
   Similar disappointment was expressed by former Jackson delegates
in New Jersey, which has 16 electoral votes.
   ``He goes to Union but not Newark,'' said Newark Mayor Sharpe
James. ``He goes to a college campus but not Camden or Trenton.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
