<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     10-24 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Tech Dream Often Just That</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many rural communities searching for economic
revival hope to attract high-tech industry, but an Agriculture
Department researcher says they should think twice before investing
much time or money in the effort.
   A new factory to design or build gadgets for space robots might
seem the opportunity of the century, with hundreds of new jobs and
a fat monthly payroll.
   But James P. Miller of the department's Economic Research
Service says that dream is hard to make come true.
   In some cases, he says, computer and other high-tech companies
do locate research and development operations in the countryside.
But usually this is done only when local resources, such as
research facilities, match their needs.
   More often, rural communities wind up with ``the most routine
assembly tasks'' of the high-tech companies because of the
lower-skilled work involved and lower wages, Miller says.
Consequently, local development leaders shouldn't be overly
optimistic.
   ``High-tech firms may not be as footloose as many have been led
to believe, particularly when they are in their most innovative
state of development,'' Miller writes in a forthcoming issue of
Farmline magazine.
   But communities keep trying, and he says it is easy to see why
they do. Jobs and incomes have been lost in agriculture, mining,
forestry and low-wage, low-technology manufacturing.
   ``Some planners believe that rural areas should attempt to
encourage investment in the fast-growing high-technology industries
because these industries are clean and are perceived to pay high
wages,'' Miller said.
   The high-tech industries most often include communications,
electronics, defense systems, computers and software. Some of the
sophisticated products are guided missile components and
engineering, and medical instruments.
   Miller said states and local communities are committing an
increasing share of their scarce economic development resources to
high-tech development programs. One recent report, he said, cited
38 such programs in 22 states.
   But so far, Miller said, studies show that the clear tendency is
for new high-tech facilities to locate in urban areas.
   ``Computer manufacturing and software industries showed the
strongest tendencies among high-level R&D industries to concentrate
in metro areas,'' he said. ``New computer manufacturing
establishments tended to locate in urban areas, primarily in the
Northeast and West. But they were poorly represented in rural areas
of every part of the country except New England, where many rural
areas are highly integrated with urban areas.''
   On the other hand, rural areas can attract ``low-tech industries
involved in non-innovative, routine production activities,'' Miller
said. And there are always exceptions in which rural areas appeal
to certain kinds of high-tech companies _ sometimes because those
operations are unwelcome in big cities.
   ``Rural areas in most parts of the country tend to have a
comparative advantage in the production of chemical products, and
to a lesser extent, petroleum refining, ordnance, radio and TV
manufacturing, and the assembly of electrical apparatus,'' he said.
   It is also clear that high-tech companies don't usually move
themselves lock, stock and barrel into the countryside.
   ``Locally owned, independent firms account for only about 11
percent of all jobs created by new high-tech firms in rural
America,'' Miller said. ``Corporate affiliates are the dominant
form of new, high-tech business activity in rural areas, comprising
nearly 90 percent of the jobs in such industries.''
   Miller said high-tech firms, particularly those in innovative
and development phases, are attracted to cities by the availability
of professional and skilled workers, investment capital and close
contact with customers, suppliers and other high-tech companies.
   In contrast, high-tech facilities that are located in rural
areas are likely to be affiliates of urban-based corporations that
have opened remote assembly plants in order to avoid high costs of
labor, land and other production items.
   ``Large corporations based in cities tend to expand research
facilities in good times and reduce or eliminate them in bad times,
with those located farthest from urban centers being most likely to
experience large changes in employment,'' Miller said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
