<DOCNO> AP881024-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StarWars     10-24 1074</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Star Wars,1050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electronics Advances Central to Cheaper Star Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers in the Star Wars program say
progress in miniaturized electronics is central to the Pentagon's
recent estimate that the first phase of an anti-missile defense
system would cost $69 billion rather than a previously forecast
$115 billion.
   To illustrate the point, John P. Peller of Rockwell
International removes his tie clip and shows visitors that it is
actually an ``accelerometer,'' a measuring and computing device
that 20 years ago would have filled a small room.
   ``We feel that we will have achieved success when we can bring
all the hardware in the program in our tie tacks,'' said Peller, a
Rockwell vice president in charge of the company's program to
develop space-based weapons designed to smash enemy missiles.
   Dozens of engineers and scientists involved in Star Wars,
formally known as the Strategic Defense Initiative, made similar
points, showing off tiny devices that are a fraction of cost, size
and weight of earlier generations of technology.
   Mass producing them in the quantities needed for Star Wars would
drastically cut costs, the same way it has cut the prices of
consumer electronic devices such as computers and stereo systems.
   Among the cost and size reductions cited by Peller were an
inertial measurement unit, down from 40 pounds and $70,000 to six
ounces and $8,000, and a rocket thruster down from 19 pounds and
$150,000 in the 1960s to one-tenth of a pound and $20,000 today.
   Reduced weight means that a system is easier and cheaper to
launch and keep in orbit.
   And in an era of tight budgets, a $69 billion program may be
easier to sell than one costing twice that.
   But the drop in the estimated price has not calmed Capitol Hill
fears that Star Wars will not work.
   Rep. John M. Spratt, D-S.C., of the House Armed Services
Committee said he was unsure that ``costs can be cut by half
without eroding performance.''
   ``This system might actually be more fragile'' than the earlier,
costlier system, Spratt said during an Oct. 6 hearing at which SDI
officials explained the change.
   Furthermore, deployment of space-based defenses would break the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, and unless it is part of a
detailed arms control framework, would unleash a new round in the
arms race as the superpowers hurried to deploy defensive as well as
offensive weapons.
   Reagan administration officials say SDI research, funded at $4.1
billion for fiscal 1989, will allow a decision in the mid-1990s on
whether to develop an anti-missile defense, with deployment in the
late 1990s or early 21st century.
   Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has acknowledged that the
Soviets are working on a parallel program. Pentagon analysts say
that the Soviets are spending billion of rubles annually on
anti-missile defenses, and are ahead in such areas as laser
development.
   After President Reagan launched SDI in March 1983, public debate
centered on whether exotic defenses such as lasers could form a
defensive umbrella to protect the continental United States from
Soviet missiles.
   The $69 billion system outlined by scientists and engineers is
considerably less ambitious, and has the goal of knocking down
about 30 percent of the Soviets' more than 10,000 warheads, denying
them the certainty of being able to destroy the U.S. nuclear
arsenal in a ``bolt from the blue'' attack.
   Scientists and engineers at the national weapons laboratories,
Rockwell and other defense contractors are hard at work developing
a two-tier system which would include one layer of anti-missile
missiles based on the ground and another parked aboard satellites
in low orbit, less than 180 miles high.
   Edward Teller, the atomic physicist credited with planting the
seed of SDI in Reagan's mind, was initially skeptical of the
so-called ``kinetic kill vehicles'' which destroy warheads by
running into them. He had originally called for a space-based
defense using more exotic technology, in particular the X-ray
laser, powered by nuclear weapons exploded in space.
   But now Teller is leaning toward a kinetic, or collision, system
which would rely neither on nuclear weapons nor on nuclear reactors
in space.
   ``Progress in miniaturization, in the development of good
sensors, and in the realm of advanced computation, this made it
possible to make the kinetic energy component small and less
expensive,'' said Teller, 80, known as the father of the hydrogen
bomb.
   The Pentagon's current plans for a Phase One deployment, Teller
said in an interview, would be an important ``gateway'' to a more
complete and advanced system later.
   The first elements of the system to go into orbit will be about
10 Boost Surveillance and Tracking Systems (BSTS), Air Force
satellites costing about $400 million apiece. Starting in the
mid-1990s, these satellites are expected to perform a variety of
reconnaissance and communications missions not immediately linked
to Star Wars, said Mel R. Brashears, head of the BSTS program at
the Lockheed missiles and space company in Sunnyvale, Calif.
   If Congress and the administration agree to deploy an
anti-missile system, more BSTS satellites can be added to give
early warning of Soviet rocket launches, said Brashears.
   The current Pentagon vision of an anti-missile defense involves
two more satellite complexes. The Space Surveillance and Tracking
System (SSTS), orbiting several thousand miles above the earth,
would relay more detailed information on enemy boosters to another
lower complex, 147 satellites each weighing about 6,600 pounds and
carrying about 10 Space-Based Interceptors.
   The SSTS would send the space-interceptor platform ``what we
call a wake-up call,'' said Peller, of Rockwell.
   Under the new lower cost plan, the weapons platforms would
surrender much of their tracking capability to the SSTS satellites
and to the interceptors themselves.
   But that worries some critics who note that because there are
fewer SSTS, they will make an easier target for Soviet weapons.
   In addition to the space-based interceptors and sensors, the
United States would also build an undisclosed number of facilities
to launch ground-based anti-missile missiles. These would hit
warheads above 300,000 feet in altitude, as the bombs begin their
final descent.
   Lockheed officials hope to fly a prototype in 1990 and to drop
the cost for each of the estimated 3,000 missiles to $1 million a
copy, down from the current projected cost of $10 million apiece,
said Rex Hahn, an engineer at the corporation's sprawling facility
in Sunnyvale.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bryan Brumley writes on national security issues
for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
