<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MexicanHeroin 2ndLd-Writethru a0402 10-24 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexican Heroin, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0402,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Mexican Police Charged In Planning Heroin Shipments To New
York</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `A surveillance...', to CORRECT spelling to
Villagrana sted Illagrana.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Mexican police officers were arrested after
they offered to ship 110 pounds of heroin _ worth up to $50 million
_ to the United States each month, a Drug Enforcement
Administration spokesman said Sunday.
   ``These two defendants were using their positions in the
Acapulco region (of Mexico) to safely transport the heroin to the
United States,'' said DEA spokesman Robert Strang.
   The heroin would have been manufactured in Mexico and sent to
New York by plane, he said. A kilogram of heroin, which equals 2.2
pounds, has a street value up to $1 million.
   Agents posing as organized crime figures spoke with the men in
Mexico by telephone, and the pair flew to New York City on Friday
to complete the deal, Strang said.
   After dining with the Mexican officers Saturday night, two
undercover agents went to the mens' hotel and gave them $15,000
cash as partial payment in the proposed drug deal, Strang said.
   A surveillance team then moved in and arrested Pedro Guillen,
39, and Margaritan Villagrana, 42, he said. They are state police
officers from Guerrero, Mexico, which includes Acapulco, he said.
   They were charged with conspiracy to distribute heroin, a felony
that carries a penalty of 25 years to life in prison, Strang said.
They are scheduled to appear in state Supreme Court on Monday.
</TEXT>
