<DOCNO> AP881024-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--RatControl     10-24 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Rat Control,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rat Control Study Begins Before Major Highway Rebuilding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of specialists has begun a two-month,
$25,000 study on how to control rats displaced by the $3.5 billion
construction project on Boston's Central Artery.
   ``It's really the first time a major project of this sort has
asked the question ahead of time: `What can we do to reduce our
pest control problem and minimize the impact?''' said William
Jackson, head of the four-member team.
   ``Usually you have rats in the mayor's office or some such
political crisis instead of looking at the problem long-range.''
   The artery, the city's major highway through downtown, is
scheduled for reconstruction underground. A third tunnel under
Boston Harbor leading to Logan International Airport also is
planned.
   ``Rat poison's not the solution to everyone's problems,''
Jackson said. ``The recommendations have to be tailored to the
environment.''
   Jackson's team intends to develop what it calls an integrated
pest management report by December.
</TEXT>
