<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-24 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH LEWISBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmer Bob Corbett wants Chief to
make it big, so to speak, so he feeds his 1,230-pound hog 10 cans
of beer and 30 pounds of grain a day.
   The formula is working.
   Judges at the recent Indiana State Fair told Corbett that Chief
was the biggest hog they could recall ever seeing. The hog is
represented by a lawyer from Urbana, gets as much as $700 for
appearances at county fairs and has been on ``Late Night with David
Letterman.''
   Corbett, 65, quit his job as a prison guard to devote full time
to Chief, who was born one of a litter of 11 six years ago.
   ``He had a big neck, a lot of bone and a rear end as rough as a
washboard. Plenty of loose skin to grow into,'' Corbett said. ``I
knew right then I had me a good one.''
   At six months, he weighed 300 pounds _ 75 pounds more than any
of his siblings. By the time he was 4, he had won the Buckeye Big
Boar title at the state fair.
   Corbett credits some body-builder magazines he read three years
ago and an old veterinary book that said a hog's digestive system
is similar to man's.
   ``All you need is a diet with plenty of protein and
carbohydrates, a little exercise and a hog could put weight on just
like one of them body builders,'' he said.
   Chief's menu includes corn, steamed barley, oats, rolled oats,
alfalfa meal, soybean meal, commercially prepared meat scraps and
molasses, all washed down by beer to thin his blood and prevent
kidney stones. On the rare occasions when Chief doesn't have an
appetite, Corbett will mix in a bottle of Pepto-Bismol.
   Corbett takes Chief on two half-mile hikes every day during the
summer and has him X-rayed regularly to make sure fat isn't
building up around his heart.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100,000 people lined the banks of
the Charles River for the world's largest one-day rowing regatta,
but all of them didn't have their eyes on the boats.
   Stephanie Forte of New Jersey, a student at Bentley College in
Waltham, spoke for many when she listed her top priority: ``I'm
enthusiastic about the guys around here.''
   Kathi-Ann O'Leary, another Bentley student, conceded that she
knew nothing about rowing. ``It's more important to be here and
meet lots of people,'' she said.
   Despite a heavy presence of police and alcohol, spectators at
Sunday's annual Head-of-the-Charles Regatta got along well with
officers.
   ``Does anyone want to claim ownership of this bag?'' Officer
Frank O'Brien asked spectators while holding up a jug.
   As O'Brien dumped the tomato-red liquid into a trash can, a
group of spectators began chanting, ``Sha Na Na Na, Hey Hey, bye
bye.''
   O'Brien returned to the group, grinned, held up the empty bottle
and said, ``You're the nicest people we've taken alcohol from all
day.''
   The spectators included a group of campers from Newton who
brought an 8-foot-long hoagie, a sandwich that put the camp in the
spirit of the day by resembling a heavyweight shell.
   Regarded as the nation's premier rowing event, the
Head-of-the-Charles drew more than 3,500 competitors from across
the country as well as England, France, Switzerland, Mexico, Peru,
Hong Kong and East and West Germany. The races cover a three-mile
course from Boston to Cambridge.
</TEXT>
