<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RailcarWastes     10-24 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Railcar Wastes,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romer Denies Request to Expand Waste Storage at Nuclear Weapons
Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Roy Romer on Sunday denied a
Department of Energy request to expand low-level radioactive waste
storage at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant.
   Romer made his decision as a railcar, loaded with Rocky Flats
wastes and turned back from a temporary storage site in Idaho on
order of Idaho Gov. Cecil D. Andrus, was returning to the nuclear
weapons plant 16 miles northwest of Denver.
   Andrus has banned furthur shipments of such wastes to the
storage site in his state.
   ``I met with DOE and they said, `Would you expand the
authorization to store (at Rocky Flats)?' And my answer was `No!,'
'' Romer said. ``That's about as clear as you can get.
   ``I also asked them not to unload that car but to leave it
loaded and to leave it on the track so we can work to find another
destination for it,'' he said.
   ``I said, `You an keep the authorization for storage you now
have. But I will not enlarge the storage.'''
   An interim agreement allows storage of about 1,600 cubic yards
of material at Rocky Flats. Rocky Flats has about 650 yards of
low-level waste, leaving about 950 cubic yards to go, Romer said.
   The Energy Department had planned to transfer the waste from
Idaho to New Mexico when the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a
permanent nuclear waste site near Carlsbad, N.M., opens. That site
was to have been in operation this month, but the date has been
pushed back at least until early next year.
   Romer said he did not want to authorize an increase in nuclear
waste storage because he did ``not want Colorado to be the escape
valve for everybody's failure to provide a permanent site.''
   ``I said I want to confer with other western governors so that
we can find a way to get the WIPP site in New Mexico available as
soon as possible,'' the governor said.
   Dennis Hurtt, manager of external affairs for Rockwell
International that operates Rocky Flats, expected the railcar to be
moved to the weapons plant sometime Monday.
   ``We have a spur off of the line that we ship rail materials in
and out on, and it will be moved off the line and on the Rocky
Flats spur and stored on site there until a decision is made as to
how they want to handle this whole waste storage problem.'' Hurtt
said.
   Rocky Flats makes plutonium for nuclear warheads. The plutonium
processing was recently recently after three workers were exposed
radiation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
