<DOCNO> AP881024-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-B-1Bomber     10-24 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-B-1 Bomber,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says B-1 Bomber Has More Maintenance Problems Than
Predecessor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force's B-1 bombers are grounded with
maintenance problems far more than the aging planes they are
supposed to replace, says a congressional study.
   The General Accounting Office study said the time that B-1s
weren't available at Dyess Air Force Base in Texas due to
maintenance problems ranged from 47 percent to 66 percent.
   For systems that have been flying longer, such as the FB-111 and
the B-52, the Air Force expects that the total of ``not mission
capable'' rates won't exceed 25 percent of the available hours.
   The Air Force responded to the figures by saying it won't have
enough experience with the B-1 until 1994 to consider the plane
``mature,'' as the FB-111 and B-52 are now considered.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, disagreed. ``When the GAO suggested standards by which
to judge the reasonableness of breakdowns, they were told the plane
isn't mature yet. But its maturity is being pushed back further by
breakdowns,'' he said.
   The GAO study, released Sunday, concludes that ``the B-1B has
not been mission capable because of maintenance a significant
percentage of the time.''
   In Air Force parlance, ``mission capable'' means the ability to
carry out an assigned job. In the case of the B-1 _ which includes
the first four prototype B-1As, which are no longer flying, and the
next generation of 100 B-1Bs _ that would mean a nuclear strike on
the Soviet Union.
   ``The Air Force says the B-1B has been ready to go to war for
two years, but when it comes to pinning the service down on some of
the plane's problems, the answer is the plane is still just a
kid,'' said Aspin, one of the plane's chief critics.
   In response, Capt. Jay DeFrank, a spokesman for the Air Force,
said, ``This weapon system is not fully mature so it is not valid
to compare it to those that are.'' He added that ``all but a few of
the B-1Bs could be launched if a wartime crisis were to occur.''
   DeFrank also said the service wanted to fly the plane more but
had been restricted by the Democratic-controlled Congress.
   ``In fiscal year 1988, Congress specifically cut the B-1 flying
hours by 30 percent,'' DeFrank said. ``The Air Force flew all
19,000 flying hours allotted and could have flown more if they had
been available.''
   The B-1 program, killed by President Carter 11 years ago after
the first four planes were built, was resurrected in 1981 by
President Reagan, who said 100 of the swing-wing planes were needed
as replacement for the aging B-52s in America's fleet of atomic
bombers. Reagan pledged that all 100 planes would be purchased by
1988 at a cost of $26 billion.
   The 100th plane was delivered last spring, but Aspin and other
critics have pointed out what they say are serious flaws in the
plane's electronic countermeasure system, the complex mix of
computers and other weapons designed to outwit Soviet defenses.
   The Air Force defends the plane as the world's most
sophisticated atomic bomber and says the countermeasure problem can
be fixed.
   Part of the plane's problem, according to the GAO, is that the
maintenance system depends, in part, on an on-board diagnostic
system that has not worked as designed. That has delayed Air Force
plans to have service personnel take over some maintenance jobs
from private contractors.
   The Air Force is also working on a better ground-based system to
figure out B-1 problems, but that program won't be ready until at
least next year, the GAO said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881024-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-LtGov     10-24 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Lt Gov,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Lieutenant Governor's Rise Tied to Dukakis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Perhaps no politician has more riding on Michael
Dukakis' White House hopes than Evelyn Murphy.
   The Massachusetts lieutenant governor would take over the Corner
Office here if Dukakis moves to the Oval Office in Washington.
   Murphy's political career has been inextricably linked to the
fortunes of Dukakis, beginning as a volunteer cutting newspaper
clippings for his first gubernatorial campaign.
   After weathering and riding that association for 14 years, the
48-year-old lieutenant governor now says she would enjoy taking
over if Dukakis wins the White House in November.
   ``Sure,'' she said. ``You don't sit here twice around as a
Cabinet secretary and as a lieutenant governor, and you don't run
for the lieutenant governor's office, unless you look at it and
think some day that it will be possible to get there.''
   For Murphy, who has always pointed to her business, academic and
later governmental credentials for her next job, there appears to
be a persistent problem with the way her motives, intentions or
actions have been interpreted in Massachusetts' charged political
atmosphere, particularly in relation to Dukakis.
   Talking to reporters in July in Atlanta when Dukakis claimed the
Democratic Party's presidential nomination, she mentioned she was
leaving the convention one day early _ the day Dukakis gave his
acceptance speech _ to ``pick up the pieces'' back in Massachusetts.
   ``It wasn't off-handed,'' she said later of the remark, ``but it
got sort of stretched out to a kind of inference about the budget''
and an uncertain revenue situation she could inherit from Dukakis.
   Murphy had virtually no political experience before business
acquaintance Howard Smith, later to become economic affairs
secretary in Dukakis' first administration, asked her to help out
with Dukakis' first gubernatorial campaign.
   ``It was literally no more than cutting newspaper articles,''
she recalled. But it got her recognized and remembered after
Dukakis won in 1974.
   Murphy, helping Dukakis fulfill a campaign promise of bringing
women into his new administration, joined his cabinet as
environmental affairs secretary even though she thought her
qualifications were better suited for secretary of economic affairs.
   Murphy holds a doctorate in economics from Duke University and
founded her own consulting firm specializing in education, health
care and municipal development.
   But when Dukakis was turned out of office by Edward King in
1978, Murphy was out of a job, too. She became a visiting lecturer
on environmental issues at the Kennedy Institute of Politics at
Harvard University, a consultant to Polaroid Corp., and the founder
of a non-profit corporation involved in hazardous waste issues.
   Then, in 1982, she made her first run for lieutenant governor.
She won the state Democratic convention endorsement, but lost the
primary to John Kerry. Political detractors would later criticize
her for remaining neutral in the Dukakis-King rematch that year.
But when Dukakis won back the governor's office he didn't hesitate
to bring her back into his administration _ this time as economic
affairs secretary.
   Murphy quit the Cabinet in late 1985 to run again for lieutenant
governor. This time she won the election, but along the way
suffered what she considers her most painful political defeat _
narrowly losing the Democratic convention endorsement to former
state Sen. Gerard D'Amico.
   Various factors have been given for the loss. Organized labor
worked against her. D'Amico was helped by his former Senate
colleagues. Murphy's initial campaign tactic emphasizing history _
that she was bidding to become the first woman to hold statewide
office in Massachusetts _ over her personal qualifications was
ill-conceived.
   But the final straw for many Dukakis supporters may have been a
Boston Herald column the day before the convention. Under a
headline of ``Question of Loyalty,'' the column quoted unnamed
members of former Gov. King's transition team as saying she asked
King if she could participate in his administration after King
defeated Dukakis in 1978.
   Murphy said the allegation, which continues to haunt her, ``is
one that's always made me furious because it's basically wrong.''
   Murphy is unmarried, lives in Brookline _ like Dukakis _ and is
known for the long hours she gives to her work.
   ``As a kid I was very shy growing up,'' said Murphy. ``I got
through that by achieving.''
</TEXT>
