<DOCNO> AP881024-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Buckleys'Vendetta     10-24 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Buckleys' Vendetta,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Buckley Family Raises Money To Help Democrat Defeat
Weicker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Buckley family, a leading voice of
conservatives nationwide, has moved beyond rhetoric in its
longstanding feud with fellow Connecticut Republican Lowell P.
Weicker Jr.
   The Buckleys, who drew a few laughs at the Republican National
Convention this summer in New Orleans when they announced their
endorsement of Democrat Joseph Lieberman in the race for Weicker's
Senate seat, have launched a political action committee and raised
nearly $4,000 to help Lieberman, federal records show.
   A report filed last week with the Federal Election Commission by
BuckPac, the newly created fund-raising arm of ``Buckleys for
Lieberman,'' reported $3,737.50 in campaign contributions.
   Priscilla L. Buckley of Sharon, Conn., the committee treasurer
and sister of National Review editor William F. Buckley Jr. and
former Sen. James Buckley, said $1,000 has gone to Lieberman and
another $200 was split up among four Republican congressional
candidates in Connecticut.
   The family plans on spending the remaining $2,500 on local
newspaper ads attacking Weicker, she said.
   Buckley said the family did not solicit contributions, but said
small donations were received from ``people around the country who
have been offended by Lowell Weicker.''
   She said contributions have slowed to a trickle, adding that the
family expected to receive about $1,000 and ``were rather
astonished to get three times that amount.''
   The feud between Weicker, a leader of the liberal wing of the
party, and the Buckleys, who represent the conservative branch of
the GOP, began long before the 1988 Senate race.
   The Buckleys accuse Weicker of being a far-out liberal who
should not be a Republican.
   Weicker counters that the Buckleys represent an
ultra-conservative extremism that is dangerous to the GOP.
   ``The conservatives of that ilk don't want a Republican Party
with a broad base,'' Weicker said in an interview earlier this
month. ``They want a narrow party such as their Conservative Party.
   ``They obviously look at Lowell Weicker as frustrating that end,
and believe me, they get out there and do their hatchet job as best
they can because they don't care about the Republican Party,''
Weicker said. ``They care about their ultra-conservative
principles, be damned with the party.''
   Weicker points to the 1970 Senate race in New York in which
James Buckley defeated the Republican nominee in a three-way race
with 39 percent. Buckley lost a re-election bid in 1976 to Democrat
Daniel Patrick Moynihan and four years later lost a Senate bid in
Connecticut against Democrat Christopher J. Dodd.
   In 1985, Weicker and Dodd opposed his nomination as a federal
appeals court judge, but Buckley won Senate confirmation.
   Weicker has often been the subject of criticism in William
Buckley's National Review.
   Lieberman spokesman Marla Romash said ``anybody who knows Joe
Lieberman'' realizes that the Buckleys, specifically William
Buckley, raised money for the Democrat ``not because he likes Joe
Lieberman but because he hates Lowell Weicker.''
   Priscilla Buckley, in a telephone interview Friday, said Rep.
John G. Rowland, R-Conn., one of the four GOP congressional
candidates to receive $50 each from BuckPac, returned his
contribution.
   Rowland, whom many expected to challenge Weicker in a primary
but decided against it, returned the money ``because he didn't feel
he should take it from a fund that was against a Republican,'' she
acknowledged.
</TEXT>
