<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BiasIncident 1stLd-Writethru a0413 10-24 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bias Incident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0413,0811</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Howard Beach, Staten Islanders Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3, `Police indicated ... ' and 12, `Police
reportedly ...' to CLARIFY attribution on police investigation to
Lamberti; Also moved for AMs.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of a black teen-ager on a Staten
Island street has forced residents of a working-class neighborhood
in New York's whitest borough to proclaim they are not racists.
   When Derrick Antonio Tyus, 17, was killed by a car shortly after
a racial encounter with whites, New Yorkers recalled their most
infamous racial incident of recent years, the death of a black man
who was run over as he fled a gang of whites in Howard Beach, a
neighborhood in the borough of Queens.
   Police indicated Tyus' death Oct. 7 was not directly caused by a
racist incident, according to Staten Island's borough president,
who said the investigation found that Tyus was hit by a car 20
minutes after the exchange of racial slurs when he accidentally
jumped in the street while horsing around with friends
   That explanation has not satisfied everyone. State Sen. David A.
Paterson has called for a special prosecutor to investigate.
   At the urging of Paterson and other civil rights leaders, U.S.
Attorney Andrew Maloney agreed last week to conduct a preliminary
investigation into the death. The FBI will gather information to
determine whether a grand jury investigation into possible civil
rights violations is warranted.
   Meanwhile, residents and political leaders rushed to defend
Staten Island and the neighborhood of Rosebank from comparisons to
Howard Beach.
   ``We are not unique from any other community throughout this
country,'' said Staten Island Borough President Ralph Lamberti.
``Do we have racial problems? The answer is yes.''
   ``But that should not characterize our borough as a racist
borough,'' he said.
   The blacks involved in the incident come from the Park Hill
Housing Projects, a nondescript row of brick buildings about a mile
from Rosebank and its narrow streets of neat houses.
   Tyus and nine other youths were walking past JJ's Bar and Grill
when a smaller group of young whites came outside and the two
groups exchanged racial slurs, police said.
   The blacks told police that several white men got into two cars
and followed them for several blocks. At one point, a white man
allegedly jumped out of a car and pushed an 11-year-old black to
the ground. They then fled in their cars.
   Police reportedly said some of those who were with Tyus have
changed their accounts several times.
   ``There were some verbal slurs that were made,'' Lamberti said
after a closed-door briefing from police. ``But there was no
incident, at least supported by the Police Department
investigation, where youngsters were chased through the streets
because of fear of physical harm and ran into an oncoming car. That
is not the case here.''
   ``To make the parallel to the Howard Beach case is totally
unfair to this community,'' he said.
   Even so, racial incidents are not new to Staten Island, which
has the smallest minority population among the city's five
boroughs. Of an estimated 420,000 residents, about 52,000 are
members of minority groups, most of them living on the island's
North Shore near the terminal for the Staten Island Ferry.
   Last summer a black man on his way home from work was chased by
a group of bat-wielding whites but escaped serious injury when
several whites from a pizzeria came to his aid.
   Several years ago, a black youth was beaten to death with a bat
at a playground by a group of white youths because he was dating a
white girl. And a white was fatally stabbed for no apparent reason
by blacks at a playground behind a black church.
   But some leaders said Rosebank is less racially polarized than
many Staten Island neighborhoods.
   ``I keep hearing that Rosebank is a racist community. To that, I
say nonsense,'' said the Rev. John Servodidio of St. Joseph's
Church, whose parish is a block from where Tyus was killed.
   ``After the accident, people from the community rushed outside
and placed a coat beneath the dying boy's head and covered him
until the ambulance came,'' he said. People in the crowd also
suggested the quickest way to get to a hospital, he said.
   ``Does that sound like a racist community?''
   Servodidio believes something positive can come out of the
incident.
   ``It's an opportunity for us to teach,'' he said, which he
boldly did from the pulpit last week when he told his congregation
he knew who the ``hypocrites and racists'' were among them and he
would ``pray for their conversion.''
   ``The people I was referring to, their heads went down,'' the
priest said.
</TEXT>
