<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     10-24 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Scandal,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Scandal Hits Turning Point With First Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An insider trading scandal is revealing plenty of
intrigue: top politicians' aides buy stock, a hidden camera
captures an apparent attempt to bribe a lawmaker, and a key man
says he would rather die than talk.
   The politically sensitive Recruit Scandal is named after the
Recruit Co., a high-flying conglomerate whose offices in Tokyo's
glittering Ginza district were raided Wednesday.
   The raid, filmed for television as prosecutors carted away about
1,500 boxes of confiscated documents, was followed by the first
arrest since the scandal went national in July.
   Hiroshi Matsubara, 47, a former top aide to the head of
Recruit-Cosmos Co., a real-estate subsidiary, was charged Thursday
with offering a bribe to Yonosuke Narazaki, member of Parliament
for the opposition United Socialist Democratic Party. Narazaki is a
persistent driver of Parliament's probe of the scandal.
   With that arrest the probe is moving on two fronts, with
investigations by prosecutors and the Diet, Japan's parliament,
backed by aggressive reporting from some news media.
   ``At long last, the scandal has come under criminal
investigation, at least in part,'' the Asahi Shimbun, which made
the first revelations of the scandal's political bearing in June,
said in an editorial.
   But the liberal-leaning newspaper, while praising the display of
independence by the Tokyo District Prosecutor's Office, expressed
worry that the criminal investigation could ``give some Diet
members a perfect excuse for calling for a slowdown in the Diet
probe.''
   The alleged bribe was a flagrant example of the so-called
``money politics'' that underlie the Recruit scandal, with
reverberations to the top of Japanese politics and in the stock
market as well.
   A camera, hidden by Nippon Television Network with Narazaki's
permission, showed Matsubara asking the opposition parliamentarian
to help save the Recruit company and offering an envelope full of
cash, saying ``We intend to support you for the rest of your
political career.''
   Narazaki said Matsubara, who resigned his Recruit position as
soon as the video was shown on national television Sept. 6, visited
him three times offering $38,000.
   Matsubara's former boss, Hiromasa Ezoe, has been hospitalized
reportedly suffering from depression. But on Oct. 12 several
members of the Diet questioned him about Recruit's having sold
shares in Recruit-Cosmos at bargain prices to top political aides
before the company went public in 1986.
   The shares leaped in value when open trading began, yielding fat
profits, and it is widely assumed the money went to finance
political activities of the governing Liberal Democratic Party.
   The lawmakers quoted Ezoe, who founded the parent company
Recruit, as having told them he was sorry for having caused trouble
to people whose names had been revealed as having benefited.
   ``I cannot bear to see any more people resign or be
inconvenienced. I would rather kill myself than disclose their
names,'' Ezoe was quoted as saying from his hospital bed.
   Nonetheless, the plot's next unfolding revealed the biggest name
so far on the list of Recruit-Cosmos beneficiaries _ that of
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa. Previously it was said an aide to
Miyazawa bought Recruit-Cosmos shares.
   The finance minister, also deputy premier, denied purchasing the
shares himself and apologized for being lax in supervising an aide
who he said let a third party use Miyazawa's name to buy the shares.
   Still to be heard from are all the political aides who are said
to have actually held and sold the Recruit-Cosmos shares.
   Until Friday, news reports said 76 people received shares, but
the Asahi Shimbun quoted ``informed sources'' as saying Ezoe sold
shares to 140 people.
   No authoritative complete list has been made public yet, but the
politicians who have confirmed their aides held shares include
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, former Prime Minister Yasuhiro
Nakasone and former Foreign Minister Shintaro Abe, now secretary
general of the ruling Liberal Democrats.
   All have denied personal wrongdoing. The transactions were not
illegal but the scandal called sharp attention to political ethics
and intimate links between business and politics.
   The opposition and ruling parties all need money to run election
campaigns, constituency affairs and parliamentary activities, and
big business has always been a major source of cash. In Japan's
rapidly expanding economy, new companies like Recruit-Cosmos have
become a source of political money through the device of selling
shares at bargain prices before they go public.
   But never before has the practice made so many headlines or
administered such a jolt.
   The opposition Japan Socialist Party demanded Miyazawa's
resignation, but the finance minister has refused. Takeshita, who
needs Miyazawa to quarterback a tax-reform package through the
Diet, has said Miyazawa bears an ``ethical responsibility'' but
resignation was not called for.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
