<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MexicanHeroin     10-24 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexican Heroin,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Police Officials Charged In Planning Heroin Shipments To
U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans for a $50 million-a-month heroin pipeline
from Mexico were foiled with the arrest of two Mexican police
commanders who officials say boasted they could close airports in
their home state to help the smuggling.
   Pedro Guillen, 39, and Margaritan Villagrana, 42, commanders
from the state of Guerrero, which includes Acapulco, were to be
arraigned today, authorities said. They were arrested late Saturday
in a hotel following a four-month investigation, said Robert
Strang, a spokesman for the U.S. Drug Enforcement Adminstration.
   ``They had the arrogance to travel to the United States to
peddle their goods,'' said Robert M. Stutman, special agent in
charge of the DEA in New York.
   ``Whenever you have police officials involved in the trafficking
of major amounts of drugs it is truly the worst betrayal of the
public trust. To have foreign police officers come to the United
States to traffic in drugs is even worse.''
   The suspects agreed to supply 50 kilograms, or 110 pounds, of
heroin manufactured in Mexico each month, Strang said Sunday. A
kilogram of heroin has a street value of up to $1 million.
   Mexican heroin ``is not something we normally have available to
us here in New York'' because virtually all the heroin smuggled
into the city comes from Asia, said Strang.
   ``These two defendants were using their positions in the
Acapulco region (of Mexico) to safely transport the heroin to the
United States,'' Strang said.
   U.S. agents posing as drug traffickers spoke with the men in
Mexico by telephone, and the pair flew here Friday to complete the
deal, Strang said.
   After dining with the Mexicans on Saturday night, two undercover
agents went to the mens' hotel and gave them $15,000 as partial
payment, he said.
   A surveillance team then moved in and made the arrests, Strang
said.
   The two were charged with conspiracy to distribute heroin, a
felony that carries a penalty of 25 years to life in prison, he
said.
   The Mexican officers bragged to the undercover agents in
tape-recorded conversations that they could close down airports in
their home region if a plane from New York flew in to pick up the
heroin, Strang said.
   The Reagan administration has charged that drug enforcement
agencies in Mexico are filled with corruption. Earlier this year,
nine people, including three Mexican police officials, were
indicted in Los Angeles in connection with the torture and murder
of U.S. DEA agent Enrique Camarena in Mexico. Three, including a
former homicide investigator in Guadalajara, Mexico, have been
convicted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
