<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-24 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen today
while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange dipped slightly.
   After opening at 126.17 yen, its lowest level since June 21, the
dollar rose, apparently because dealers were concerned the Bank of
Japan might intervene to prop up the dollar.
   The currency peaked 126.75 yen shortly before closing at 126.60
yen, up 0.20 yen from Friday's close of 126.40 yen.
   Exchange dealers attributed the low opening rate to the market's
skepticism over the ability of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to reach agreement on production quotas among
members of the oil cartel.
   ``But the general perception of the market was the Bank of Japan
will likely intervene if the dollar declined to the 125-yen
level,'' said a currency dealer in Tokyo, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 32 points last week, lost 57.03
points, or 0.21 percent, from Saturday's close. It ended the day at
27,281.54.
   Stock dealers said the initial fall in the dollar today hurt
share prices.
   ``When there is a wild fluctuation in the foreign exchange
rates, investors are not enthused about participating in the stock
market,'' said a dealer at a major securities firm in Tokyo, also
speaking anonymously.
   Export-oriented shares, including electronic and automobile
issues, lost ground.
   Dealers added that Emperor Hirohito's continuing illness was
also having a negative impact on the stock market.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where most
major stocks are listed, was a thin 600 million shares.
</TEXT>
