<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Blaze     10-24 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Blaze,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shanghai Oil Refinery Blaze Kills 25, Injures 17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gas leaking from an oil refinery touched off
explosions and a raging blaze that killed 25 people and injured 17
in Shanghai's worst fire since the Communists came to power,
official media reported.
   Saturday's blaze at the Shanghai Gaoqiao Oil Chemistry Corp.'s
refinery occurred when ``liquefied gas'' leaked after a worker
opened a water drain valve, the city's Liberation Daily newspaper
said in its Sunday editions.
   The English-language China Daily said the fire was the worst in
China's largest city since the Communists came to power in 1949.
   Shanghai police say they did not know kind of gas caught fire
and called it only ``liquified gas.'' But editors at the China
Daily said when queried that they believed it to be liquified
natural gas.
   A guard reported the leak about midnight Friday but nobody paid
attention, the reports said. An hour later, the gas was ignited by
sparks from a nearby construction workers' shed, touching off a
fire that quickly spread back to the refinery, they said.
   More than 400 firemen rushed to the refinery area in the city
680 miles southwest of the capital to fight the blaze, which was
extinguished in an hour, China Daily said.
   Twenty-three bodies were found in a dozen construction workers'
sheds destroyed by the fire, the report said.
   Nineteen other people were injured, but two died on the way to
hospitals. Three of the remaining survivors were in critical
condition and doctors expected the death toll to rise, China Daily
said.
   The newspaper identified one of the injured as the refinery
janitor, whose attempt to report the fire failed because the
telephone was not working.
   An official in Shanghai, reached by telephone today, said there
was no change in the number of casualties.
   The reports gave no estimates on the damage.
</TEXT>
