<HEAD>Leftists Rebels Free 131 Prison Inmates In Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels freed 131 prison
inmates, including five held for political reasons, in an attack on
a town in northern El Salvador, military officials said.
   Members of the leftist guerrilla group, Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, on Sunday attacked military installations and the
prison in Ilobasco, a town 35 miles northeast of San Salvador in
Cabanas province, the military said.
   The two-hour attack ended when the 20 guards defending the
prison abandoned their positions. Two were wounded, officials said.
   A military bulletin said that Jose Flores, 77, who had served
five years of a 10-year term, did not escape. All the rest of the
prisoners left with the rebels.
   The FMLN simultaneously attacked goverment forces in nearby
Tejutepeque. No victims or material damages were reported there.
   Four days ago, rebels freed 50 prisoners in Santiago de Maria,
where they also inflicted heavy damage on three coffee processing
plants. Santiago is an important coffee-growing city in eastern El
Salvador.
