<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoleSurvivor     10-24 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sole Survivor,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sole Survivor of Four-Fatality Crash Gives Thanks With Recital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENSSELAER, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager demonstrated his talent as a
gifted pianist to show how far he has recovered since an automobile
accident last May which killed four classmates.
   Bernard James ``B.J.'' Sell of Brook, a 17-year-old St. Joseph's
College freshman, held the free recital Sunday night in the college
chapel.
   He was the only person to survive a car accident that killed
four other honor students at South Newton High School in the
northwest Indiana town of Kentland on May 21.
   The music was nearly the exact program Sell had intended to play
at his high school graduation recital the next day, said Professor
John Egan of St. Joseph's, Sell's piano teacher the past 10 years.
   On the day of his commencement, Sell was fighting for his life
at a hospital as the 59 remaining seniors struggled through the
emotional ceremony.
   Months of extensive surgery and rehabilitation followed, with
Sell receiving support from family, friends and people he had never
met.
   ``My music is my way of saying `thank you' to my family, my
friends and everyone who encouraged me during the time I was at St.
Anthony's Hospital and during the months of my recovery,'' Sell
said in a written statement.
   ``Your thoughtfulness, flowers, cards and prayers meant so much
to me. Words cannot convey how much I appreciated everything,'' he
added.
   Sell has avoided interviews since the accident that killed
Richard S. Overdeer, 18, of Goodland; Mike Kindell, 18, of Brook;
Amy Hancock, 17, and John Piegza, 18, both of Kentland.
   Police believe the five were returning from Watseka, Ill., about
20 miles west of Kentland, when Overdeer, the driver, fell asleep
and veered into a utility pole.
   Sell was, who was pinned under the dashboard, suffered multiple
injuries, including a crushed leg, a broken left arm, a broken jaw,
broken cheekbones and a broken pelvis. Doctors hope for a complete
recovery.
   Crystal Sell said her son was determined to start college on
time and that deadline drove him during his recovery. He was
dismissed from the hospital June 22, a month after the crash, and
abandoned his wheelchair Aug. 18, two days before classes began.
   A couple of weeks ago, he had surgery to remove a pin from his
leg. He faces more surgery to remove other pins next summer.
   ``I'm proud of him,'' Mrs. Sell said. ``He has been through so
much with the physical pain and mental anguish, and he's had so
much determination and courage.''
   Sell believes his piano skills are about 95 percent of what they
were before the accident, said Egan, who considers Sell a gifted
student.
   ``He's incredibly good,'' Egan said. ``I've often called him my
Mozart.''
   Sell tires more quickly than he once did and his left hand may
not yet be able to do what it could before the accident, Egan said,
but in another sense the accident has made him a better pianist.
   ``I'd say he has surpassed where he was before. He has a far
deeper set of experiences and he grew as a person. It shows in his
music,'' Egan said.
   ``He's an exceedingly popular young man. I think everything
about him cries out that it's great to be alive,'' Egan said. ``I
think he's the kind of kid who could come here and major in
anything and do exceedingly well.''
</TEXT>
