<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SnakePlot     10-24 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Snake Plot,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Trying to Use Snake to Kill Mom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A construction worker accused of plotting
to have his mother killed with a rattlesnake borrowed $300 from her
to pay the snake handler, police said.
   Tipped off by a Florida snake handler, police arrested Reginald
Pope on Thursday in his 62-year-old mother's Alabama home. Pope is
in the Marengo, Ala., County Jail on a charge of conspiracy to
commit murder.
   ``He must have had this idea in his head for some time because
he had all the details planned out,'' said Escambia County
sheriff's Cpl. Wendall Hall.
   Authorities didn't identify the snake handler, but said he told
Escambia sheriff's Deputy Ed Hudson about the proposal after
meeting Pope at a Pensacola restaurant more than a week ago.
   ``They started talking, and when Pope found out that the man
trapped rattlesnakes as a hobby, he said, `Well, you're just the
man I've been looking for,''' Hall said. ``Then Pope told him he
wanted to hire someone with a rattlesnake to kill his mother.''
   Authorities said the snake handler went to Alabama, taking a
snake with him, in order to fool Pope into thinking he was
cooperating in the plot.
   ``He wanted the rattlesnake to bite her on the neck at the
jugular vein so the venom would go straight to the heart or the
brain,'' Hall said.
   The motive apparently was money; Pope was the sole beneficiary
of her insurance policies and will, Hall said.
   ``He even borrowed $300 from his mother to give to the
rattlesnake handler after he saw the snake,'' Hall said.
   Alabama authorities got the mother out of the house, and Pope
was arrested just before the snake was to be let loose when he
walked into the house.
</TEXT>
