<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0850EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-RoundTable     10-24 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Round Table,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Round Table Really Is Round</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For weeks it seemed all of Poland was
waiting for the ``round table.'' Now it has finally arrived.
   A specially made table 29 feet in diameter has been delivered to
the Jablonna Palace for the expected talks between representatives
of authorities and the opposition, a furniture maker said.
   The talks could begin as early as this week.
   The doughnut-shaped table is hollow in the center and can seat
more than 50 people, said a Polish media source. It comprises 14
sections, is made of pine and is covered with a veneer, the source
said.
   The manager of the Warsaw Factory of Artistic Furniture, Henryk
Lewandowski, said the table took two weeks to manufacture and was
delivered this morning to the government palace just outside
Warsaw. He said he was not authorized to give further details.
   Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak and Solidarity leader
Lech Walesa agreed at a meeting Aug. 31 to hold ``round-table''
discussions that will cover broad social questions, including
Solidarity's future and economic and political pluralism in Poland.
   Both sides say they want the talks to begin as soon as possible,
and blame the other for delays.
   The government Saturday said it wants another meeting between
Kiszczak and Walesa to remove last-minute obstacles to the talks,
including disputes over certain individuals nominated by the
opposition to participate.
   Walesa says such a preparatory meeting is unnecessary because
Solidarity will not change its proposed delegation to the talks,
and any other technical matters can be cleared up through
lower-level intermediaries.
</TEXT>
