<DOCNO> AP881024-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MonitorProtest     10-24 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Monitor Protest,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Protest Electronic Lunchroom Monitor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 90 elementary school students who
objected to an electronic monitor that buzzes and flashes when they
get too loud in the lunchroom won't have to endure it if they stay
reasonably quiet, the school's principal says.
   ``I think the light stinks,'' said Richmond School sixth-grader
Scott Doyon. ``It's a big waste of money. I think the aides do a
good job of making us quiet.''
   He was among fifth- and sixth-graders who submitted a
handwritten petition last week asking that the monitor be removed.
   The monitor is equipped with a noise-measuring device that scans
the lunchroom.
   As many as 175 pack into one of four daily lunch shifts at the
705-student school, Principal Pasquale Nappi said.
   With relative quiet, the monitor is green. If it gets louder,
the signal changes to yellow and the monitor emits a loud
electronic beep. More noise, and the red light comes on and the
monitor buzzes.
   If the red light blinks on more than five times during a lunch
shift, the lights are switched off and the students eat in the dark.
   Additional red lights mean the students lose a 10-minute recess
period after lunch.
   Nappi, bowing to the the fifth- and sixth-graders' protests, has
ruled that they won't have to eat under the monitor's continuous
scrutiny as long as they remain reasonably quiet.
   But first- through fourth-graders will remain under the
monitor's electronic supervision, Nappi said.
   The Richmond Parent-Teacher Organization bought the device in
the spring for $450. It was installed in time for the first day of
school last month.
   The acquisition was a reaction to complaints from lunchroom
aides that noise in the cafeteria, which also serves as an
auditorium and a gymnasium, was intolerable at times.
</TEXT>
