<HEAD>Jackson Returns To Civil Rights Fold During Lowery Celebration</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to CORRECT number of people attending to 2,000
sted 300.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson joined a symbolic reunion
of civil rights leaders at the conclusion of a tribute to the Rev.
Joseph Lowery's 40 years as a United Methodist minister.
   ``It was like a homecoming,'' Lowery, president of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, said of Sunday night's event,
which reunited many of the men who made civil rights history during
the Sixties.
   A rift developed in the SCLC after the 1968 death of its leader,
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., and relations between Jackson and
other King aides became chilly and distant.
   All that was set aside when Jackson marched onstage Sunday.
   The two-time presidential candidate was greeted warmly by
Lowery, Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young; King's widow, Coretta Scott
King; the Rev. Ralph David Abernathy, King's best friend; and Rep.
John Lewis, D-Ga., a former leader in the Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee.
   Young told an audience estimated at 2,000 people that King
``would be proud'' of Jackson's political accomplishments.
   Jackson said he has been a ``direct beneficiary'' of Lowery's
philosophy, and described Lowery as ``common sense dressed in work
clothes'' whose leadership achieved social change in the 1970s and
1980s.
   ``I respect you Brother Joe, in all seriousness,'' said Jackson,
who flew to Atlanta Sunday for Lowery's anniversary after stops in
Boston and New York. ``I was determined to be here tonight. My
sense of history obligates me to be here.''
   Jackson took the opportunity to blast Vice President George
Bush, saying the Republican presidential nominee, if elected, would
appoint federal judges who would jeopardize further progress in
civil rights.
   Jackson encouraged the audience to vote for Democrat Michael
Dukakis and his running mate, Lloyd Bentsen.
   Other leaders praised Lowery as a foot soldier who carried his
ministry from an Alabama ghetto to the forefront of a movement that
shaped the nation's moral conscience.
   Lowery encouraged the audience to vote in each election,
pointing out that blacks have ``come too far, marched too long,
bled too profusely and died too young'' so that others may have
that right.
   He said the tribute was a ``tremendous humbling experience.''
   ``I'm grateful to Jesse,'' Lowery said, ``particularly because
he had such a grueling schedule and he juggled it and compounded it
to be here.''
</TEXT>
