<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Empress     10-24 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Empress,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landmark Victoria Hotel Closes For Renovation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last guests were ushered
out, staff members took pictures and cried and disbelieving
tourists were turned away when the stately Empress Hotel closed for
the first time in its 80-year history.
   ``Where else serves afternoon tea?'' one woman asked the doorman
anxiously Sunday about a tradition that is part of this provincial
capital's heritage.
   The 416-room hotel will be closed for nearly six months for a
multimillion-dollar facelift, including restoration of the Crystal
Ballroom and refinishing of antique furniture.
   ``It's been a bit of an emotional helter-skelter for the last
week,'' said general manager Ian Barbour. ``It's pretty traumatic
but we know we are closing for the right reasons.''
   A few staff members will continue to work during the closure and
some have moved temporarily to other Canadian Pacific hotels, but
the majority will take a six-month holiday.
   Fred Borg, a front office employee, said one of the most
difficult tasks has been trying to explain that there won't be a
Christmas package this year.
   ``Many customers are used to coming here every year,'' he said.
``It's almost like a pilgrimmage.''
   He said many Christmas regulars were referred to the Hotel
Vancouver, in Vancouver, British Columbia, which has been given
Empress secrets for a traditional Christmas.
</TEXT>
