<DOCNO> AP881024-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 0958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhoenixMissiles     10-24 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phoenix Missiles,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Faulty Part Forced Navy To Abandon 500 Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department is investigating an
Orange County company whose faulty production of a critical part
forced the Navy to abandon 500 Phoenix missiles worth $425 million,
the Los Angeles Times reported today.
   Micronics International in Brea is suspected of using a
substandard production process for making the missile's fuze, its
safety and arming mechanism, according to the newspaper.
   Rodney Hansen, special agent in charge of the Defense Department
inspector general's office in Santa Ana, confirmed that it is
conducting a criminal investigation into the concern.
   The Phoenix _ the principal weapon for the Navy's F-14 fighter _
is a radar-guided missile designed to fire at enemy aircraft 100
miles away.
   But the supply of $850,000 missiles is useless because of the
failure of the $4,500 part, which fires the warhead and also
prevents premature firing of the missile, Navy officials told the
Times.
   The company began manufacturing proper fuzes in February, the
Navy said. Those are expected to be installed in the warehoused
missiles by next year's end.
   E.W. Ritter, Micronics' business manager in Phoenix, said the
company had been subpoenaed early this month for documents
involving the missile program, but said they weren't told they were
the subject of a criminal investigation.
   Company officials previously placed the blame for the fuze
failures on Navy designs. And an investigation previously conducted
by the General Accounting Office concluded that the Navy shared
responsibility for the manufacturing problems.
   The company, a subsidiary of La Jolla-based Precision Aerotech,
refused to comment about its work on the Phoenix program.
   Micronics contracts over the last three years with the Navy Air
Systems Command for the fuzes totaled nearly $5.4 million.
   The company is accused of using a process called ``sand
casting'' to form the devices. In that process, sand is used to
mold the hot metal. Products resulting from this process have a
pitted, porous surface that fail to meet contract specifications.
   According to the Times, the Navy required the company to use a
process called ``investment casting'' in which molten metal is
poured into a wax mold to produce a smoothly finished product that
can meet precise specifications.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
