<HEAD>Lifeguards Rescue Gray Whale Trapped in Net</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Trapped Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two lifeguards freed a 25-foot gray
whale that became trapped in a weighted gill net while migrating
south, authorities said.
   Lifeguards Jason Hudson and Alan Powder hacked away at the net
for 45 minutes on Saturday and were able to clear all but a small
portion of the net fouling one of the endangered gray whale's fukes.
   The whale then continued its southward migration and whale
experts at Sea World in San Diego were alerted to be on the lookout
for it, said Capt. Randall Davis of the state Bureau of Marine
Safety.
   California gray whales migrate along the Pacific coast of North
America from the arctic region to Baja California for spawning.
Marine and wildlife officers occasionally are called to attempt
rescues.
   In Alaska, rescuers continued their efforts today to free two
gray whales that became trapped in Arctic Ocean ice while migrating
south.
