<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan-Bhutto     10-24 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Bhutto,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Postpones Start Of Campaign Due To Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Benazir Bhutto has
postponed the start of her November election campaign becaused of a
kidney infection, family sources said today.
   They said treatment for the illness would keep her at her
Karachi home for a few more days.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35-year-old leader of the left-leaning Pakistan
People's Party, had planned an eight-city swing by train through
Punjab province, starting today at their family home of Larkana in
Sind province to the south.
   She developed a fever Sunday and flew back from Larkana to
Karachi on her doctor's advice, family members said.
   It was to be her campaign debut for National Assembly elections
scheduled Nov. 16 and provincial assembly polls three days later.
She had been recuperating from the birth of her first child Sept.
21.
   Ms. Bhutto's main rival is the conservative Pakistan Muslim
League of former Prime Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo.
   About 1,370 candidates from 20 parties are contesting 217 seats.
Ms. Bhutto's party is believed to be Pakistan's largest party but
it has not participated in any national elections her father,
Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, won the 1977 polls.
   The army chief, Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, claimed the 1977
elections were rigged and ousted Prime Minister Bhutto in a coup.
   Zia had Bhutto hanged two years later for allegedly plotting to
kill a political foe.
   Zia ruled for 11 years until his death Aug. 17 in a plane crash.
Investigators concluded the crash, which also killed U.S.
Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 others, probably was caused by
sabotage.
   Senate Chairman Ghulam Ishaq Khan now is Pakistan's head of
state.
   Political observers predict Ms. Bhutto's party may be strong
enough to garner a simple majority in the new legislature, but
several right-wing Moslem parties have said they would oppose
having a woman as prime minister.
</TEXT>
