<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GirlFound     10-24 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Girl Found,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Teen-ager Found After Six-Year Search</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old girl who became the subject of
a nationwide search after she was abducted six years ago has been
living with her grandfather and is in good condition, officials
said.
   Authorities in Huntington Beach, Calif., arrested Leroy Freeman
for investigation of kidnapping and unlawful flight to avoid
prosecution, Huntington Beach police Lt. John Foster said.
   Lucas County Juvenile Court Judge Andy Devine said he would
decide today whether Karen Creswell will be granted custody of her
daughter, Charity, who was found Friday in Huntington Beach.
   Devine on Saturday gave emergency temporary custody of the girl
to the Lucas County Children's Services Board pending the outcome
of today's hearing. A doctor and the Children's Services Board will
decide whether she and her mother should be reunited before the
hearing.
   Devine said he did not return Charity immediately to her mother
based on ``information that was supplied to me that indicated this
custody action was necessary.'' He would not discuss the
information in detail.
   The girl was abducted in September 1982. Authorities had
searched for her in Ohio and New Mexico before Freeman was arrested
Friday in California. Detectives had gone to see him about an
automobile repossession and the girl answered the door, Foster said.
   Charity was not being held captive and appeared to be in good
physical shape, Foster said.
   ``Thank goodness, this may finally be coming to an end,'' said
Victor J. Gonzalez, an attorney for the girl's mother. ``It's been
a long, long ordeal.''
</TEXT>
