<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Himalayas-Deaths     10-24 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Himalayas-Deaths,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Czechs Die In Himalayas, Six Other Climbers Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Czech climbers fell to their deaths
in the Himalayas and four Czech members of another expedition were
missing on Mount Everest, the Tourism Ministry reported today.
   Also in the Himalayas, two Icelanders have been missing for six
days on Mount Pumori, the ministry said. It said the search for the
two had been abandoned.
   The ministry said the two Czechs who died _ Leous Horka and Petr
Gribek, both 45 and from Ostrava _ fell to their deaths on Mount
Tilicho Four.
   The two members of the 19-man expedition reached the top of the
23,399-foot Tilicho last Tuesday. They spent the night on the
summit and began descending the next morning, but slipped and fell
to their deaths about 2,000 feet below the summit.
   Another member of the team, Palecek Ludvik, 32, also from
Ostrava, left the expedition's base camp at 15,088 feet Thursday
and reached the summit of Tilicho on Friday, the ministry said.
   On his way down, Ludvik discovered the bodies of the two Czechs
hanging from their climbing ropes. He returned to base camp
Saturday.
   Four Czech members of another expedition have been missing since
Oct. 17 after they scaled Mount Everest, the Tourism Ministry said.
   The ministry said it received a message from the expedition's
base camp reporting the disappearance of Jozef Just, 33; Dusan
Becik, 34; Jaroslav Jasko, 27; and Peter Bozik, 34; all from
Bratislava.
   On Oct. 17, Just reached the top of 29,028-foot Mount Everest
and reportedly stayed for 20 minutes before starting his descent.
   The other Czechs climbing with Just reached 28,750 feet but
turned back because of high winds, the ministry said.
   The 14-member expedition included eight Czechs, five New
Zealanders and an American.
   The missing Icelanders _ Poesteiwn Gudjowsson and Kristinn
Runarsson, both 27 and from Reykjavik _ were last seen by other
members of their five-man team as they were heading for the summit
of Mount Pumori from 20,336 feet on Tuesday.
   The two had planned to make their assault on the 23,488-foot
peak Wednesday. Gudjowsson was one of the leaders of the
British-Icelandic expedition.
</TEXT>
