<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Swindall 1stLd-Writethru a0488 10-24 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Goes To Trial On Perjury Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to update with arrival at court, picks up
5th graf, `The prosecution...'; Judge refuses to let reporters
leave while court is in session so prospects of further updates are
uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Swindall said he was in good spirits and
confident of acquittal when he arrived at federal court today for
his speeded-up trial on charges of lying to a grand jury about
seeking an $850,000 mortgage.
   ``I have absolutely no problem when it comes to the truth. I
know the truth is on my side,'' he told reporters.
   Swindall's perjury trial was to start at 9:30 a.m., but was
delayed.
   The 38-year-old, two-term Republican congressman has contended
that any discrepancies in his grand jury testimony were memory
lapses. While waiting for the trial to begin Swindall joked with
reporters, and at one point in discussing his defense plans, he
qualified a statement by saying: ``But my memory is not that good.''
   The perjury trial stems from Swindall's negotiation of a loan
with a man he knew as Mike Martinez, who actually was undercover
Internal Revenue Service agent Michael Mullaney.
   Swindall told the grand jury in February that he was suspicious,
even afraid, of Martinez, but said his talks with Martinez never
gave him reason to go to authorities.
   The government contends Mullaney gave Swindall plenty of reason
to believe the $850,000 home mortgage loan he was seeking would
come from the drug trade.
   The prosecution claims Swindall lied to the grand jury about his
dealings with Mullaney and Charles LeChasney, who has pleaded
guilty to money laundering charges which do not involve the
congressman.
   Swindall, who is representing himself, has said he got tripped
up by ``a memory test'' in his Feb. 2 grand jury appearance, and
has vowed to prove he did not intend to deceive.
   The trial comes in the final stages of a bitter election
campaign between Swindall and Democrat Ben Jones, who played Cooter
on the ``Dukes of Hazzard'' television show.
   A poll conducted by The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta
Constitution last week found Jones leading Swindall 53 percent to
27 percent, with a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
   Swindall was indicted just a week ago. He demanded a swift trial
in an effort to clear his name before the Nov. 8 election.
   Swindall is accused of concealing knowledge that something
illegal was being planned by LeChasney and ``Martinez.'' The
indictment says that when the congressman was asked why he did not
take his admitted suspicions to authorities, he replied:
   ``Because I never satisfied myself of anything with respect to
criminality, other than I did not feel comfortable that the deal
was a right deal. I did not want to get in the posture of, if I
could avoid it, putting myself in the position of pointing my
finger at what could be a drug person, who could very well
jeopardize myself and my family. I frankly hoped that he was
legitimate.''
   The transcript of the government's tape recording of a Sept. 13,
1987 meeting says the undercover agent told Swindall, ``All I can
tell you is that my gut feeling is there are narcotics dollars in
there. That's it.''
   ``I don't recall any conversation like that. ... I don't
remember ever the term narcotic used,'' Swindall told the grand
jury. But he said he smelled trouble ``and I walked away from it,
basically.''
   Twelve days after that meeting, Swindall accepted a $150,000
check from LeChasney. The prosecution claims Swindall was lying
when he said the check was not part of his negotiations with the
undercover agent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
