<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StrandedBelugas     10-24 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stranded Belugas,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twenty-Seven Beluga Whales Stranded; Freed By Tide</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Trapped Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the eyes of the world focused on
the effort to free two gray whales stranded in ice near Barrow,
rescuers helped save 27 beluga whales that spent more than seven
hours trapped in mud near Anchorage.
   The whale pod apparently midjudged the tide and beached itself
at about 10 a.m. Sunday on a mud bar about halfway betwen Girdwood
and Portage along the Seward Highway, south of Anchorage.
   Dozens of people jammed the roadside to watch the silver-white
whales gently flopping on the mud, steam rising from their
blowholes. The whales ranged in size from about 6-feet-long to
16-feet-long.
   Kayakers Jim Diehl and Riley Cronk braved the treacherous
mudflats and swirling currents to spend more than an hour with the
whales, pouring water on them and wrapping them in wet tarps and
blankets until they could swim free.
   ``They were all alive. They looked all wrinkly when we first got
there and when we left they weren't wrinkly any more,'' Diehl said.
   A helicopter ferried veterinarian Tex Cody and National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration biologists to the stranded animals,
and U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service law enforcement agents also
visited them.
   ``We went in and checked all the animals, bathed their eyes and
kept them wet,'' said Roger Mercer, a NOAA biologist. The men threw
another dozen wet blankets over the whales and waited for the tide.
   The tide came in at about 5:35 p.m. ``It was really kind of
exciting,'' Mercer said. ``As soon as the tidal water hit them,
they started flopping around and then kicking.''
   The helicopter hovered nearby as the whales swam to freedom.
</TEXT>
