<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FairShooting     10-24 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fair Shooting,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Declare Fair A Success, Say Shooting Was Isolated
Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gun battle sent hundreds of people dashing for
cover at the Texas State Fair and ended with one man dead and three
wounded, but officials declared the 1988 fair a success and said
overall crime was down.
   ``Despite that isolated incident Friday, the officers on the
detail this year worked extremely hard to make this a safe fair,''
said Dallas police deputy Chief R.L. Schifelbein.
   Several fights broke out late Friday and Schifelbein, who
oversees fair security, decided to begin closing things down for
the night. Police had taken a pistol from a 14-year-old boy who
pulled it from a pocket during a scuffle with several youths.
Within a few hours officers had seized pistols from three other
people.
   ``Lord only knows what we didn't get,'' Schifelbein said. ``It
was obvious there were groups who came out here for the express
purpose of creating problems.''
   Then came the battle in which 18-year-old Bobby Joe Nabors Jr.
died of multiple gunshot wounds after he shot three other men,
police said.
   The first officer on the scene, Sgt. Manuel Vasquez, said he saw
Nabors shoot Joey Henry and tried to wrest the gun away. Vasquez
was shot in the hand during that struggle. Henry and another man
were in serious condition at Parkland Memorial Hospital.
   Off-duty police Cpl. James T. Daily, 38, who was working
security at the midway, saw Henry lying on the ground and Nabors
and Vasquez struggling. Police said Nabors pointed his pistol
toward Daily and Daily fired at him. Daily told investigators he
believed Nabors fired back, and the officer shot at Nabors again.
   However, police said Nabors was shot three times in the chest
and once in each arm. Investigators said the five wounds may have
been caused by fewer than five bullets, but police were unsure
whose gun fired the bullets that killed Nabors and aren't assuming
that only one person fired at Nabors.
   Eight pregnant women and several bystanders also were injured
when surrounding crowds pushed and shoved in a scramble to reach
shelter.
   In addition to the shooting, at least four people were slightly
injured Saturday when a Ferris wheel malfunctioned, jolting back
and forth several times and swaying uncontrollably, The Dallas
Morning News reported.
   Fair communication director Nancy Wiley said 2.9 million people
visited this year's 17-day fair, which ended Sunday night.
Attendance was up from 2.76 million in 1987, she said.
   Schifelbein said preliminary figures indicated 112 criminal
offenses were committed at this year's fair. That compares to 146
criminal offenses last year, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
