<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Greece-Hikers     10-24 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Hikers,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flash Flood Kills Man In Crete; Five People Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HORA SFAKION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain caused a flash flood today
as about 200 tourists trekked along the Samaria Gorge, and one man
was killed and five people were reported missing, police said.
   Some hikers sought refuge in a cave and others scrambled into
clefts in the rocky walls of the 11-mile long gorge as the water
rushed through, a police officer said.
   ``The rain has knocked out the phone to the village there so we
don't know exactly what happened. It seems there was a sudden flood
in a narrow part of the gorge,'' said the officer, who requested
anonymity in accordance with Greek practice.
   He said the body of a man in his 30s had been recovered but not
yet identified.
   Tourism Minister Nikos Skoulas was flying to Crete to supervise
rescue efforts.
   The Samaria Gorge, the longest in Europe, descends from an
upland plain to the southern coast of Crete. Its cliffs rise more
than 100 feet high and it narrows to around 10 feet wide at some
points. It is a popular hiking route in southern Crete.
</TEXT>
