<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RobberyAbduction     10-24 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robbery Abduction,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnap-Robbery Suspects Arrested After Lengthy Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers suspected of robbery
and kidnapping a woman in Illinois have been arrested after a car
and helicopter chase at speeds up to 120 mph in which a police
officer was shot, police say.
   The abducted woman said her captors took her as far as Memphis,
Tenn., where they put her on a bus back home.
   Kenneth Gravatt, 23, and his brother, Michael, 19, both of
Marion, Ill., were arrested early Sunday and charged with
aggravated assault, possession of a firearm in the commission of a
felony and possession of a stolen car, said Cathy Baio, a
spokeswoman for the Broward County Sheriff's Department.
   Ms. Baio said police started chasing the Gravatts late Saturday
in Clewiston, Fla., after a deputy tried to stop them because they
looked suspicious.
   The pair fired dozens of shots at their pursuers and wounded a
Palm Beach County sheriff's deputy, police said.
   The 90-mile chase ended about an hour after it began when a
trooper shot out a tire and the Gravetts crashed on U.S. 27 west of
Hollywood.
   ``I'd say that's as far as we ever chased anybody,'' said Lt.
Bill Chamness of the Hendry County Sheriff's Office.
   Ten patrol cars and two helicopters had joined in the chase by
the time it ended, officers said.
   Other Florida charges, including the shooting of a Palm Beach
County sheriff's deputy, were pending, she said. The officer was
not seriously hurt.
   The Gravatts have been charged in Illinois with aggravated
kidnapping, burglary and armed robbery. A third suspect charged in
the abduction and robbery, Joseph Johnson, 19, also of Marion, was
not with the Gravatts and was still at large, said Williamson
County Deputy Sheriff Robert McCurdy.
   The kidnapping victim, Michelle Sisk, 28, of Creal Springs,
Ill., a mother of three, was forced into her car by a gunmen last
week after she paid for gasoline, police said.
   Her captors then drove on a route that included Princeton, Ind.,
Louisville, Ky. and Memphis, where they bought her a bus ticket,
said Sheriff Harry Spiller of Williamson County, Ill.
   On Thursday, three days after she was abducted, Mrs. Sisk's
captors bought her a bus ticket in Memphis and let her go. She told
authorities they planned to kill police if they were stopped and
had vowed not to be taken alive, Spiller said.
   The three are suspected of burglarized two homes shortly before
the abduction, stealing 22 rifles and shotguns, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
