<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Germany-SAfrica     10-24 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Germany-SAfrica,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Meet With South African Opponents of Apartheid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEVERKUSEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet representatives joined
anti-apartheid South Africans at a conference Monday to discuss how
to combat the segregationist policy, organizers said.
   The Friedrich Naumann Institute in Bonn said participants at the
four-day meeting include Federik van Zyl Slabbert, the former
leader of the opposition Progressive Federal Party in South Africa,
and Wynand Malan, a member of the South African Parliament from the
independent National Democratic Movement.
   Also at the closed-door sessions were Joe Slovo, a member of the
executive committee of the African National Congress and head of
South Africa's Communist Party, and Breyten Breytenbach, an exiled
South African author, the insitute said.
   The Soviet Union will be represented by members of the
Afro-Asian Solidarity Committee.
   The outlawed ANC is engaged in an armed struggle against the
South African government, under which the 26 million blacks have no
voice in national affairs.
</TEXT>
