<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Kafka     10-24 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Kafka,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kafka Works to be Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will publish some
of Franz Kafka's works and correspondence, a cultural weekly said.
   The magazine Kmen, organ of the official Union of Czech Writers,
said part of Kafka's correspondence was purchased from a
second-hand bookshop in Prague two years ago.
   Among the stories to be published are his last completed novel
``The Castle,'' published in 1926, and ``Amerika,'' which came out
in 1927, the magazine said.
   Kafka's works are highly acclaimed in the West but have been
barely acknowledged in Prague, where he was born in 1883.
   Rejected for what was described as ``morbid pessimism'' and
``alienation,'' the communists allowed both the 100th anniverasry
of Kafka's birth and the 60th anniversary of his death to pass with
little fanfare in the 1980s.
   The intellectual flowering of the mid-1960s led to the
construction of Prague's only public memorial to Kafka near the
street where he lived.
   Kmen described Kafka as an integral part of Prague literary
scene. ``Today's remembrance of Kafka is not an act of piety or
strategy but a fact of a simple refreshment of cultural memory,''
it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881024-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--KegDeath     10-24 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Keg Death,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Killed by Exploding Beer Keg</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was killed when a beer keg placed on a
bonfire exploded and a piece of metal severed his spinal cord,
authorities said.
   Patrick Viola, 22, of Niskayuna died early Saturday at an
outdoor beer party, police said. He had been standing about five
feet from the fire.
   About one quart of beer remained in the bottom of the keg when
it was placed on the fire, and the liquid began to boil, causing
steam and pressure to build up until the keg exploded.
   An autopsy determined that Viola was killed instantly when a
piece of the keg entered the right side of his neck, said Albany
County Coroner Timothy Cavanaugh.
   None of the other people at the party in the wooded area were
injured, said Lt. Raymond Krolak of the Town of Colonie Police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881024-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-US     10-24 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-US,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Tells U.S. Bishops to Fight Abortion, Contraception</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II urged U.S. bishops Monday
to persuade couples to embrace marriage and reject abortion and
contraception, lamenting a world ``that often reduces sex to the
pursuit of pleasure.''
   In a speech to 18 visiting bishops from Michigan and Ohio, the
pope said he wanted to commemorate the 20th anniversary of Pope
Paul VI's encyclical Humanae Vita, which reaffirmed the church's
ban on artificial birth control.
   ``We see ever more clearly today how relevant and positive it
is,'' the pontiff told the delegation headed by Cardinal Edmund
Szoka of Detroit.
   The pope, speaking in English, said the bishops should increase
efforts to spread the church's teaching on marriage and family
issues, ``especially the sexual dimension.''
   ``In a world that often reduces sex to the pursuit of pleasure,
and in some cases to domination, the church has a special mission
to place sex in the context of conjugal love and of generous and
responsible openness to parenthood,'' John Paul said.
   ``As pastors we must encourage couples to maintain an openness
to life and a spirit of joyful sharing in regard to children,'' he
said. ``Children are really the supreme gift of marriage ... but
materialistic and selfish attitudes often deny the value of the
child.''
   The pope said he ``deeply appreciated'' the efforts of the U.S.
Bishops' Conference to defend the church position that life starts
with conception.
   ``Throughout the world we have seen an increase in the number of
abortions and a decline in the protection of unborn human life,''
he said. ``The bishops of the United States have steadfastly
opposed this destruction of human life by programs of education and
pastoral care and by advocating laws and public policies that
protect and sustain human life, before and after birth.''
   Referring again to abortion and birth control, the pope said:
   ``We must emphasize the sanctity of human life as a precious
gift from God that needs to be protected and fostered, while making
more systematic efforts to offer instruction in the natural methods
of family planning.
   ``Natural family planning enables couples to understand God's
design for sex, and invites them to dialogue, mutual respect,
shared responsibility and self-control.''
   John Paul also reminded the bishops of the importance of
priestly celibacy, describing it as a ``gift from God.''
   ``The rule of celibacy for the Latin Church is more than
ecclesiastical law,'' he said. ``It has deep theological and
doctrinal roots.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
