<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DavidvsGoliath 1stLd-Writethru a0426 10-24 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-David vs Goliath, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush is Ahead, but Uneasy Lies the Crown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 20th graf bgng ``This of...'' to CORRECT spelling of
Yasser</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In baseball, ``It's not over till it's over,''
and in basketball someone once appropriated an operatic metaphor,
``It ain't over till the fat lady sings.'' But in presidential
politics perhaps it is best put by Tom Cole of the Oklahoma
Republican Party: ``I don't think anyone who is outregistered 2-1
can take anything for granted.''
   And so it stands, two weeks before Election Day.
   George Bush is ahead, but uneasy lies the crown.
   Michael Dukakis picked up an underdog's second wind last week,
answering weeks of spectacular Bush advertising with some creative
counterattacks of his own, and stumping the industrial Midwest with
a fervent critique of Republican economics.
   ``George Bush cares about the people on Easy Street,'' Dukakis
told a crowd last week in Kalamazoo, Mich. ``I care about the
people on Main Street. He's on their side. I'm on your side.''
   ``The corpse winked this week in Michigan,'' wrote a columnist
for the Detroit Free Press even as Rep. Vin Weber, R-Minn., was
euphorically forecasting ``a Bush Republican landslide.''
   In Kansas, Democratic Chairman Jim Parrish said: ``I hope the
Republicans think it's over. They could be in for the shock of
their lives. This race will not end until Nov. 8.''
   Of course many people think it ended Oct. 13, the night of the
second and final presidential debate. Conventional wisdom said
Dukakis needed a breakthrough to regain his footing in the
presidential race. There was none.
   In the 10 days since, Dukakis has unveiled a strongly worded
message of economic populism. Democrats are glad to see him on the
attack, but Dukakis doesn't always seem comfortable there himself.
   He slid into a booth beside Tim LaChina and his daughter last
Monday at Shorty's diner in Cleveland where LaChina implored,
``Let's kick some ass out there,'' to which Dukakis replied
somewhat less emphatically, ``OK, very good, we'll do it.''
   In recent days, the Republicans have been walking a fine line
between overconfidence in private and ``cautious optimism'' in
public.
   ``You don't want to be Goliath in these situations,'' quoth Bush
campaign manager Lee Atwater. ``The crowd is always cheering for
David.''
   Not everyone is finding it easy to adhere to discipline on this
_ GOP vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle was crowing Friday
night that the Democrats ``might end up on Election Night having a
one-state strategy, or maybe they'll just have a District of
Columbia strategy.''
   Perhaps Quayle should speak with the governor of Kansas before
writing David off.
   Kansas is a Republican state where Bush has suffered from the
vicissitudes of the farm economy and the criticisms of Senate GOP
Leader Bob Dole. ``There's one thing I know: you never take
anything for granted,'' Gov. Mike Hayden was saying last week.
``You never let up. It's ours to win, but it's also ours to lose.''
   With so many voters disenchanted with both candidates, Oklahoma
GOP chairman Cole had no particular difficulty fighting off the
urge to complacency.
   ``We have a good lead in Oklahoma,'' he said of Bush and Quayle.
``We were eight points down in August ... and now we are 10 points
ahead according to the same poll. That's not enough to say this
thing is over; at the same time in 1984 we had more than a 25
percent lead.''
   So Cole looks for something to worry about, and in common with
Republicans across much of the country, when he casts his eyes
across his political kingdom, he sees a lot of voters with the
habit of pulling Democratic levers. Four of Oklahoma's six
congressman are Democrats, along with more than two thirds of the
Legislature.
   Not that this tendency to vote Democratic extends itself to
presidential elections. On an electoral map where Republican
victories are painted in stripes, you have to go back to the LBJ
landslide of 1964 to find Oklahoma in a Democratic shade.
   This of course is one of the mysteries of the universe, on a par
with Yasser Arafat's permanent stubble and flat-screen TV: How is
it that the Democrats can control the nation's city halls, its
legislatures, its statehouses and both houses of Congress, and yet
since 1952 they have won the White House just three times in nine
tries?
   In Quayle's Indiana (six Democratic congressmen out of 10, but
truly one of the more Republican states in the country), GOP
chairman Gordon K. Durnil was worrying recently that a last-minute
event could yet produce a sudden turn in Dukakis' favor.
   ``It's never over until it happens,' he said.
   What, me Goliath?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jonathan Wolman is AP's assistant bureau chief
in Washington.
</TEXT>
