<1ST_LINE>u a PM-RishTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0458 10-24 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rish Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0458,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opening Statements in Trial of Woman Accused of Stephen Small
Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with opening statements; ADDS
byline; picks up 8th graf, ``Up to...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``ticket to easy street'' prompted a
woman to help plan the kidnapping of businessman Stephen Small, who
was buried alive in a bid for a $1 million ransom, a prosecutor
said today.
   Small suffocated when a breathing device failed in the wooden
box in which he was buried after his abduction in September 1987.
   Nancy Rish is the second person to face murder and kidnapping
charges in the case.
   Daniel Edwards, who shared a home with Rish, was convicted in
May of kidnapping and murdering Small and was sentenced to death.
   Small's death was the result of a ``cold, callous, calculating
plan of Nancy Rish and Danny Edwards for the big score _ the $1
million jackpot,'' prosecutor Michael Ficaro told the jury in
opening statements.
   His life ``was what they were willing to do for $1 million ...
that ticket to easy street ... life in the fast lane,'' Ficaro said.
   Rish's attorney, Vincent Paulauskis, has said he was looking
forward to the trial ``to let the public know the whole story.''
   ``Up to this point,'' he said, ``the public has only been told
what other people have said, what Danny Edwards has said, and what
Danny Edwards has done. That's going to change October 24th.''
   Small, 40, was the great-grandson of a former Illinois governor
and son of the late Burrell L. Small, who controlled a group of
radio and television stations.
   The jury for Rish's trial was selected in Rockford because of
the extensive news coverage of the crime in the Kankakee area. The
jurors will be sequestered during the trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
