<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ConnecticutSenate Bjt   10-24 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Connecticut Senate, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sen. Weicker Fighting Toughest Battle of Political Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lowell P. Weicker Jr., a three-term
Senate maverick who regularly enrages fellow Republicans with his
independence, once seemed an easy bet for re-election in
Connecticut but he's suddenly running scared.
   His opponent is Joseph I. Lieberman, the state's popular
Democratic attorney general for the past six years, a lawyer and
the son of a Stamford liquor store owner.
   Lieberman is a lackluster campaigner who missed his own
nomination for the Senate last summer because the party convention
was held on Saturday while he was observing the Sabbath as an
Orthodox Jew.
   But Lieberman also was the Democrats' top statewide vote-getter
in 1982 and ranked second in 1986. A self-styled ``people's
lawyer,'' he churns out reams of press releases about his campaigns
against polluters, grocery chains and unscrupulous auto dealers.
   He is the best-financed challenger that Weicker has ever faced.
And Weicker, who has never lost an election, is fighting the
toughest battle of his political life, which began with his
election to the state House of Representatives 26 years ago.
   A Connecticut poll published last week by The Hartford Courant,
showed that Lieberman, who once trailed Weicker by 24 points, had
surged to a 39-39 tie with 22 percent undecided.
   Weicker said the poll was an aberration, and that other
independent surveys conducted shortly beforehand showed him leading
by 10 points or more. Lieberman said the latest poll confirmed his
contentions that victory in the Nov. 8 election is within his grasp.
   As if Weicker's troubles weren't enough, the conservative
Buckley family is nipping at his heels.
   A family ``BuckPac,'' the fund-raising arm of ``Buckleys for
Lieberman,'' reported raising $3,737.50 to be spent mostly on local
newspaper ads attacking Weicker as a far-out liberal who should
forsake the Republican label.
   Marla Romash of the Lieberman campaign said National Review
editor William F. Buckley Jr. helped raise money for the Democratic
candidate ``not because he likes Joe Lieberman but because he hates
Lowell Weicker.''
   Snorted Weicker: ``They care about their ultra-conservative
principles, be damned with the party.''
   Weicker is known for his frequent bashing of President Reagan
and other fellow Republicans, especially President Nixon for his
Watergate misdeeds. He opposes the balanced budget amendment to the
Constitution favored by many Republicans, and condemned Reagan's
military actions against Libya and Grenada.
   In a state where Democrats hold a 3-to-2 edge over Republicans,
Weicker owes his unbroken string of election successes to his
appeal among Connecticut's 550,000 unaffiliated voters.
   He also has won support among traditionally Democratic groups.
His endorsements this year by the Connecticut state AFL-CIO and
Connecticut Freeze Voter, a nuclear arms freeze organization, were
shrugged off by Lieberman as the sort that any incumbent senator
might get.
   As Lieberman has narrowed the gap, the campaign has become
increasingly shrill.
   Lieberman is running television commercials depicting Weicker as
a bear who sleeps through important Senate votes.
   Lieberman claims Weicker's 90 percent attendance record is among
the worst in the Senate, where he has served since 1970. Weicker
says 90 percent ``is an A in anybody's book.''
   At week's end, Weicker raised questions about Lieberman's
attendance record during his 10 years in the state Senate before he
became attorney general.
   Weicker also began airing a TV ad featuring Lieberman singing
Weicker's praises at a 1986 testimonial. The spot ends with the
announcer saying, ``If Lieberman believes what he says, he'll vote
for Weicker.''
   The two men have already set a spending record for a Connecticut
Senate campaign. Lieberman has raised about $1.8 million to
Weicker's $2.2 million, according to financial reports issued this
month. They're expected to spend another $1 million between them
before the election is over.
</TEXT>
