<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     10-24 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Nicaragua,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Charges That Ortega Used Hurricane for Propaganda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House accused Nicaraguan President
Daniel Ortega on Monday of seizing upon the hurricane which
thrashed his nation over the weekend as a tool for propaganda
against the Reagan administration's support of the Contra rebels.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said no request for U.S. aid had been
received from the Nicaraguan government and none is expected,
although the United States has provided weather information. He
said the administration would consider any request it received.
   Hurricane Joan killed at least 50 people and left 300,000
homeless in Nicaragua before weakening to a tropical storm and
moving north to Honduras and El Salvador.
   In Managua, the Nicaraguan government appealed for international
aid as authorities labored to restore communications and care for
the homeless.
   Ortega, asked whether the United States should send aid,
replied, ``The best humanitarian aid the United States could give
us would be to stop its terrorist policies against Nicaragua.''
   Citing its civil war with the U.S.-supported rebels, the
Sandinistas recently enacted a law banning aid from the United
States, but one official said the law would be waived for badly hit
areas.
   ``At the moment we don't have a request,'' Fitzwater said. ``We
are providing weather information but the question of other kinds
of assistance hasn't come up.''
   Asked whether a request was expected, he said, ``I frankly think
it's very unlikely.''
   ``Our concern, frankly, is that the Ortega government would use
this as another opportunity to somehow deal adversely with the
Contras, so we do have serious problems,'' the spokesman said.
   ``It seems clear he (Ortega) wants to use this storm as another
platform for propaganda against the Contras,'' Fitzwater said.
   He quoted Ortega as saying that ``U.S. aid was harming the
country and the Contras were harming the country in its ability to
deal with the storm and those kinds of things.''
   He said the administration has made no judgment on the question
of aid, but added, ``I simply point out the politicization of this
by Daniel Ortega.''
   When asked about press restrictions imposed in Nicaragua in
connection with the storm, Fitzwater said, ``To do it at this time
under cover of a storm is really no worse really than the
performance he has displayed for the past six or seven years in
terms of closing down the press.''
</TEXT>
