<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Frat-SlaveAuction     10-24 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Frat-Slave Auction,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fraternity Suspended; Incident Under Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Wisconsin fraternity is
under investigation for sponsoring a mock slave auction in which
pledges reportedly donned black faces and Afro wigs, school
officials said today.
   ``The format was that the pledges would put on skits and then
the pledges would be put on auction for the sale of their
services,'' said Roger Howard, Assistant Dean of Students.
   Members of the Zeta Beta Tau fraternity could not be immediately
reached for comment on the incident, which occurred Thursday.
   However, the Interfraternity Council, a student body that
governs the university's fraternities, said some fraternity members
will be expelled and the fraternity will be suspended from
university activities because of the auction.
   ``Something needed to be done because what happened was horrible
and there's no place for that in the Greek system,'' IFC President
Andrew Bohman said.
   The council ordered the immediate expulsion of members involved
in the incident and suspended the fraternity from participating in
social and other events pending the outcome of investigations by
the university and the council, he said.
</TEXT>
