<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Fashion     10-24 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fashion,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chanel Offers Beautiful Long Looks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Designer Karl Lagerfeld dropped hemlines
dramatically in Monday's Chanel ready-to-wear summer show that
offered a dashing Deauville line.
   Lagerfeld played with the nostalgic beach resort and old
favorite Chanel themes nicely, recalling the days when
``Mademoiselle'' herself was just starting out at the fashionable
seaside resort.
   In fact, some of the long cardigan knit outfits almost looked
like carbon copies of what Chanel wore herself.
   Between wide A-line pants and knife-pleated skirts nearly to the
ankle, Lagerfeld brought out a new modified jodphur shape. More
sporty than the full pants, these lean trousers still had dressy
touches like welt seaming and gold buttons up the calf.
   Not all was long in this beautiful group of clothes that some
thought were generally more successful than Lagerfeld's collection
under his own label. A couple of nice knee-baring piped suits and
shorter shirtwaists dressed up with rows of gold buttons looked
chic as well.
   In nautical shades of red, navy and lots of white, the jackets
were either very short or very long, sometimes with vest-like
fronts and little V-shaped lapels or sailor collars underlined with
the Chanel bow and camellias rather than a knotted scarf.
   His boxy short jackets in delicately striped tweed had a new
piping of braid with loops.
   In addition to this easy silhouette, Chanel offered outfits in a
tubular shape with pleats flaring out at the hem.
   For a sexier look, there were tightly fitted suits in rose and
pink or turquoise and sky blue piped-knit jackets with very short
lean skirts.
   He also brought out some neutral shades like sand, caramel and
lichen _ using the latter in long pleated culottes and skirts with
billowy organza blouses.
   Now the Chanel woman can even wear a Chanel swimsuit, a new
offering here. Modest, though not at all nostalgic, they came out
in navy lycra with small white polka dots, and were highlighted at
waist or shoulder with the Chanel bow and flower.
   The Chanel logo comes up on short playsuits, chiffon dusters,
turned-up cuffs on pants and jacket linings _ as well as on silk
crepe full evening skirts with multicolored sequin tops.
   Dressy looks for summer were held to a minimum, but all were
beautiful. Gold sequin designs on navy linen blazers with flowing
ivory silk crepe pants or skirts are a good option out of the
collection for an informal dinner party. The lovely pleated and
tucked black or navy chiffon dresses can't be faulted for safe but
excellent chic.
   The loveliest evening clothes were gossamer-light white chiffons
with appliqued flowers on the billowing skirts and pearl edging
around the fitted sleeveless bodices.
   Sonia Rykiel, the sweater queen, showed both long and short
looks. The newest sweater was a shortie pullover teamed with wide
pyjama pants or narrow skirts flared at the knee.
   Among her most remarkable looks were suspendered shorts with
widely striped shirts in a collection that had a more youthful
touch than usual. The evening shorts were flippant fun, too, cut
cool and full in filmy chiffon, with embroidered jackets to match.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
