<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Ole Opry star Johnny Russell is
running a tongue-in-cheek race for president, vowing to have yard
sales and parties at the White House if elected.
   ``We will do away with the deficit,'' pledged Russell, a
singer-humorist who wrote the song ``Act Naturally.''
   ``Each Friday we will have a yard sale in the Rose Garden. Get
rid of some of that old furniture, some of those old pictures of
those old presidents and hang some new snapshots,'' Russell said.
   As a peace initiative, he pledged to ``bring all the world
leaders together at the White House for a barbecue ....''
   Russell, also known for his hit song ``Red Necks, White Socks
and Blue Ribbon Beer,'' was nominated for president recently by a
standing-room-only crowd of more than 400 friends and country music
fans at a Nashville nightclub.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HENDERSONVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country comedian Grandpa Jones says
that after performing almost 60 years he still gets ``a big kick''
out of performing on stage.
   Jones, 75, was honored Sunday by Roy Clark, George Lindsey, Roy
Acuff and other country celebrities Sunday.
   ``It just does me good to see how many friends I got,'' Jones
said.
   ``Come March of next year, I've been breathing bad breath in one
of these microphones for 60 years. How they stood it, I'll never
know.
   ``I've picked in many places in 60 years. I still get a big kick
out of getting on stage and showing off.''
   Jones also has been on the syndicated television show ``Hee
Haw'' since it began 20 years ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Philip, husband of Queen Elizabeth II, will
launch a British Broadcasting Corp. seminar on the English language
called ``A Language for the World,'' the BBC said Monday.
   The seminar, organized by the BBC World Service, aims to show
the dramatic growth of English as an international language.
   ``The English language is one of this country's biggest
invisible assets. There is a tremendous demand to learn English,
and in so many countries that means British English,'' said
Elizabeth Smith, controller of BBC English Services.
   ``In China alone, our TV series for learners of English called
``Follow Me'' is watched by audiences of tens of millions,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ADELAIDE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Duchess of York showed who's in
charge Monday when she said goodbye to her sailor husband wearing a
jacket with the word ``BOSS'' emblazoned on the back.
   She turned up with the jacket on the wharf of Port Adelaide
where her husband, Prince Andrew, was boarding his guided-missile
destroyer HMS Edinburgh.
   Following their lengthy tour of Australia, Andrew is returning
to England aboard the ship while his wife flies home.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old university student from Thailand
was crowned the 1988 Miss Asia-Pacific at the annual beauty pageant
Monday.
   Panpradub Preetanuch was crowned by last year's winner, Cilinia
Prada of Panama. She collected a gold crown with diamonds and an
undisclosed sum of money.
   Miss Panpradub, whose ambition is to become an actress, also won
the best national costume title.
   The first runner-up was Miss Mexico, Elsy Guadalupe Gurrola, an
18-year-old university student. She also took the best evening gown
title.
   Second runner-up was Miss Israel, Revital Mor, 19, a model. Miss
Panama, Jenia Nenzen, 20, a university student, was voted most
photogenic.
   Contestants from 32 countries and territories took part in the
pageant, organized by Hong Kong's Asia Television Ltd.
</TEXT>
