<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndianConvention     10-24 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indian Convention,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Congress of American Indians Meeting Gets Under Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA JORDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the smell of burning cedar filling
the hall, hundreds of delegates from as far away as Alaska and
North Carolina gathered Monday for the opening of the National
Congress of American Indians.
   ``I think we'll have a good turnout because it's an election
year,'' said John Blackhawk, chairman of the Winnebago tribe of
Nebraska, which is host for the gathering.
   The group opened the weeklong meeting by burning cedar to purify
the hall, and by singing a traditional prayer song in which they
asked the nation's leaders to listen to Indian concerns.
   ``We need to take an overall view of Indian country and the
problems that we need to address,'' said John F. Gonzales, chairman
of the congress. ``In some people's minds the organization has lost
sight of what we should be focusing our efforts on.''
   Gonzales called for unity from the more than 300 tribes
represented in the group, which is one of the nation's oldest and
largest Indian organizations.
   Rep. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, D-Colo., a Cheyenne Indian, spoke
to the group Monday.
   He said Indians can no longer rely on the Bureau of Indian
Affairs to carry their concerns to Washington.
   ``It's a heck of a lot easier to make change on the inside than
on the outside,'' he said. ``Indians must get involved in the
political process.''
   The congress is expected to formulate positions on issues
ranging from hunting and fishing to treaty rights and AIDS, which
will be presented to the next president of the United States.
</TEXT>
