<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ConfederateTombstone     10-24 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Confederate Tombstone,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confederate Soldier's Tombstone Returned To Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Descendants of Civil War soldiers came
to Jacksonville to pay tribute to a Confederate veteran whose
tombstone was brought home with full military honors.
   The tombstone was engraved to remember James Robert Houston, a
Confederate sergeant who died in 1909. It was found this spring
buried in a flower garden in Saginaw, Mich.
   Officials have no idea how the the tombstone got to Michigan but
speculate that a tourist took it from a Tampa cemetery as a
souvenir in the 1920s.
   The silence of the oak and magnolia-shaded Evergreen Cemetery
was shattered Sunday by a 21-gun salute from a troop of
gray-uniformed Confederate re-enactment soldiers.
   Several of Houston's descendants were visibly moved when a man
portraying a Union Army bugler played taps in tribute.
   ``It was fantastic, all the people who helped us who didn't know
us. There is no way we can thank them all, because there were so
many. It shows that there is still a lot of decency out there,''
said Hans Huntsinger, Houston's great grandson.
   Houston died in Tampa and is buried there, but there is no
record of the exact location. Relatives decided to place Houston's
tombstone beside that of his widow, Mary Draper Houston, who died
in 1950.
</TEXT>
