<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MyersonInformer     10-24 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson Informer,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Haven't Asked Why Daughter Informed on Her Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of the chief prosecution witness in
the Bess Myerson divorce-fixing case says neither he nor his wife
has asked their daughter why she agreed to testify when her own
mother is one of the defendants.
   Sukhreet Gabel, 39, allegedly was used by Miss Myerson to get to
her mother, former Justice Hortense Gabel. Mrs. Gabel was handling
the divorce case of Miss Myerson's boyfriend, Carl Capasso. All
three are defendants in the bribery conspiracy case in federal
court.
   The prosecution maintains that Miss Myerson, a former Miss
America who was city cultural affairs commissioner, hired the
daughter in 1983 and that in return, Mrs. Gabel reduced Capasso's
alimony.
   In addition to testifying for the prosecution, Ms. Gabel taped a
telephone conversation with her mother for investigators and handed
over documents belonging to her mother.
   ``Neither of us have asked her anything,'' Milton Gabel was
quoted as telling columnist Cindy Adams in Monday's New York Post.
``It's very strange that Sukhreet did this. How can you raise a
daughter all your life and then accept that she can do this?''
   Ms. Gabel, 39, lives on an allowance from her parents and will
come into money under her mother's will, Gabel said.
   ``She's our daughter, but she's always done odd things,'' Gabel,
a dentist, said.
   Asked if he loved his daughter, he said: ``I have a harder time
with that than my wife does.
   ``Sukhreet is brilliant but she's always been odd. I guess it's
sort of a mental thing. Like after she graduated from the U.N.
School, she wanted to just travel around the world and do nothing
for two years. She almost never seems to work.''
   Ms. Gabel had been job-hunting 18 months when Myerson gave her a
$19,000-a-year job to be what the witness has described as a
glorified ``gofer.''
   Gabel said that although his daughter lives a block away, she
did not visit her parents until the conspiracy case began to unfold.
   ``She never came near us,'' he said. ``She never invited us. She
never made dinner for us.''
   ``Still, we're supporting her,'' he said. ``Horty's pension and
Social Security is divided with Sukhreet. And we'll continue to
support her. She's our child.''
   Mrs. Gabel, 75, retired from the bench last year, citing poor
health.
   The Post said the daughter's allowance from her parents is
$1,700 a month.
   Ms. Gabel, named Julie at birth, became enamored of things
Indian after she dropped out of school at age 16 and took a job at
the India pavilion of the New York World's Fair. She changed her
name to Sukhreet, dyed her fair hair black and adopted Indian dress.
   Her marriage in 1975 to Dutch diplomat Jan Revis ended in
divorce.
</TEXT>
