<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     10-24 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warn Against Unofficial Demonstrations on Independence Date</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Monday issued a
stern warning against staging an unofficial demonstration on the
70th anniversary of Czechoslovak independence.
   Five independent groups have vowed to ignore a such a ban and
demonstrate on the anniversary, which is Friday.
   ``Some individuals and groups want to abuse the 70th anniversary
... for their anti-Socialist objectives,'' the state news agency
CTK said.
   An information bulletin adopted by the Czechoslovak Communist
Party's Politburo on Aug. 25 reveals that a ban on unauthorized
public gatherings was already agreed upon three months before it
was announced last week.
   The London-based Palach Press, a newsletter monitoring human
rights violations and other developments in Czechoslovakia, said
the five groups regard the ban as ``illegal and
anti-constitutional.'' They were the Charter 77 human rights group,
the Indpendent Peace Association, the Democratic Initiative, the
Czech Children and the Society for Friendship with the United
States.
   Palach Press said representatives of these groups sent a letter
Sunday to the Prague authorities explaining why two legal
provisions cited for the ban were inapplicable. They also made
clear they will go ahead with Friday's demonstration despite the
official ban.
   Palach Press also reported that a forum of the Independent Peace
Association was disrupted Saturday by several hundred armed police
and people's militiamen, who arrived in the village Lbin near
Litomerice in northern Bohemia, some three hours after the arrival
of the first busload of activists.
   Bohemia and Moravia form the Czech Republic, which together with
Slovakia makes up the Czechoslovak state.
   The second bus was stopped on the way to the forum, and all
activists were detained. Several of them, including Tomas Dvorak,
Ondrej Cerny and Jakub Kaplan, have not been heard from since and
were believed to be in detention, Palach Press reported.
   An emigre source in Vienna who asked not to be identified said
the Politburo information sheet was distributed to all party
organizations and groups for use at party meetings on different
levels.
   The document adopted four days after police broke up a major
demonstration of regime critics on the 20th anniversary of the
Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia, recently was circulated
among dissidents in Prague.
   CTK did not identify any individuals and groups but said ``they
are distributing various provocative declarations, including
appeals for participation in an illegal meeting in Prague.''
   Referring to an existing ban on unauthorized public gatherings,
CTK said, ``All anti-Socialist actions are organized in close
linkage with foreign agencies and emigrant circles with the
substantial assistance of Western communciation media.''
   On Saturday, the Communist Party daily Rude Pravo warned that
police would intervene if demonstrations planned by independent
groups for Friday are held despite the ban.
</TEXT>
