<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Bomb     10-24 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Bomb,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes at Popular Market; 2 Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion rocked a shopping center
in the Pakistani capital Monday night, injuring two people, police
said.
   The 11-pound bomb exploded about 7:30 p.m. in a cluster of
clothing shops in Jinnah Market, a rectangle of businesses in
central Islamabad frequented by Pakistanis and foreigners.
   The explosion occurred on the eve of the birthday of the Prophet
Mohammed more than 1,400 years ago. It is a national holiday in
this Moslem nation.
   The two Pakistanis who were injured were not seriously hurt,
said Police Superintendant Javed Noor.
   Glass and plastic from about 10 shop signs littered the sidewalk
around the popular market with clothing, souvenirs, jewelry stores
and restaurants.
   It was the second blast in Islamabad in 24 hours. On Sunday
night, a bomb exploded in a bus at the city's main bus stand. Nine
people were injured, four seriously.
   Officials have blamed scores of terrorist bombings the past two
years on agents of neighboring Afghanistan's communist government.
   Pakistan and the United States back Moslem rebels fighting the
Soviet-supported Kabul government.
</TEXT>
