<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle     10-24 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Charges of GOP Racism `Totally Absurd'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARNOLD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle said Monday it is ``totally
absurd'' for Democrats to suggest that the Republican are making
racist appeals in the presidential campaign.
   GOP nominee George Bush's vice presidential running mate labeled
the allegations a political diversionary tactic.
   Quayle said the charges by his Democratic counterpart, Lloyd
Bentsen, and by the Rev. Jesse Jackson and others reflected
desperation among supporters of the flagging candidacy of
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
   ``It's totally absurd. I think it shows just how desperate they
really are to start fanning the fires of racism in this country.
It's totally unfounded,'' Quayle told reporters aboard his campaign
plane as he flew from Washington to Missouri.
   Bentsen and Jackson alleged last weekend that the Bush campaign
was sending a racial message by hammering Dukakis over the case of
black convicted murderer Willie Horton Jr., who raped a white woman
in Maryland last year after he had escaped from a Massachusetts
prison furlough.
   ``Our opponents have begun a massive campaign of disinformation,
a concerted effort to divert this campaign away from the issues
that George Bush and I have raised,'' Quayle told a rally at Fox
Senior High School in this small town outside St. Louis.
   ``If I had to defend the Dukakis record, I'd look for
diversions, too,'' the Indiana senator said.
   Quayle attacked what he called the Massachusetts governor's
``pathetic positions in the area of national defense and crime.''
   When reporters asked about Jackson's contention that the
Republicans are using the word liberal to refer negatively to civil
rights activists, Quayle replied, ``Tthat's absolutely absurd to
say that liberal has some sort of racial connotation. Liberalism is
a political philosophy.''
   Stumping for votes in Missouri, a state with 11 electoral votes
where the presidential race is considered close, Quayle accused
Dukakis of being ``afraid of sharing his true ideology wih the
voters of America.''
   After his speech, Quayle walked up and down the aisles of the
crowded high school auditorium taking questions from the students.
   After stating his firm opposition to abortion, Quayle was asked
if he would feel the same way if his wife had been raped and become
pregnant.
   Quayle paused only slightly before saying the decision would be
left to his wife, Marilyn, although he hoped she would avoid an
abortion.
   ``If that situation happened, which would be tragic, it would be
tough not only on Marilyn, but tough on me and tough on our
children. But if that happened, I would think that she would, and I
would hope she would have _ as tough as it may be _ have the child
rather than the abortion.''
   Replying to another student, Quayle said he would do again
``exactly what I did'' when he joined the Indiana National Guard
rather than fight in Vietnam.
   Quayle planned two other campaign stops in Missouri, which he
called ``a tossup state,'' before flying to Kentucky.
   One scheduled appearance was to tour a Job Training Partnership
Act program in Union, Mo. Quayle cites his sponsorship of the job
training legislation as one of his chief legislative
accomplishments.
</TEXT>
