<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1651EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HelicopterTrial     10-24 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helicopter Trial,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arms Dealer Goes on Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arms dealer went on trial in federal court
Monday on charges that he exported a demilitarized helicopter,
armored seats and gun mounts to Surinam.
   Ruel Peter Playfair-Scott has been an arms dealer for eight
years, his attorney said. Peter Playfair, as he is known, operates
from Miami.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Eric Dubelier said during opening
statements that Playfair and a Surinam consular official from Miami
bought the helicopter in Panama City, Fla., in 1987.
   Playfair arranged to have it sent to Surinam by ship, although
he had been notified that the helicopter and the other equipment
were on a U.S. government list of items not to be shipped to
certain countries, Dubelier said.
   The cargo arrived in Surinam but was held on orders from U.S.
officials and eventually returned to the United States.
   Defense attorney Kent Wheeler said evidence will show there was
no intent to break the law and that Playfair was given incorrect
information by government agents concerning the legality of the
shipment.
   He also said the helicopter, gun mount and armored seats
actually were en route to Georgetown, Guyana, and were not supposed
to be unloaded in Surinam, a small country in South America with a
military government.
   The case is being tried before U.S. District Judge Kenneth
Ryskamp.
</TEXT>
