<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SoccerRiot     10-24 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer Riot,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot Video, Procedural Argument Dominate Soccer Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors showed a videotape of a
1985 fatal soccer riot Monday at the trial of 26 Britons charged
with involuntary manslaughter in the clash.
   The 60-minute tape showed rioting British fans tearing down a
flimsy fence and charging Italian supporters before a championship
match at Heysel Stadium. Thirty-nine people were killed and more
than 500 were injured.
   Judge Pierre Verlynde later adjourned the proceedings for two
days to study a defense motion to read aloud the prosecution's
48,000-page file of charges and supporting evidence at the trial if
they do not get a free copy of the file.
   The reading could delay the trial for months, officials said.
   Only two of the 26 British defendants showed up Monday. Verlynde
angered defense lawyers when he declined to hear arguments from
those lawyers whose clients were absent. Some defense lawyers
briefly threatened to walk out.
   On Sept. 18, the court let 14 defendants go home, but they were
due to return Monday. Two other defendants are in jail in Britain
on unrelated charges.
   Defense lawyers acknowledged that the demand to read the bulky
file made little sense, but they said they needed a free copy so
they could study it.
   The court provides a copy of the file but does not permit the
defense lawyers to take it home.
   Verlynde said the defense based its argument on a rule put into
effect when many defendants were still illiterate.
   But the defense contended the Britons, who do not speak French,
fell under such a ruling. The trial, which began Oct. 17, is
conducted in French.
   The British defendants face up to 10 years in jail if convicted.
   Two Belgian police officers and a former Belgian soccer
federation chairman also are on trial, accused of providing lax
security at the 1985 European Cup soccer final between Liverpool
and Juventus Turin of Italy.
   The Belgian defendants face up to two years in jail.
   The TV footage of the riots led to the extradition of 26 Britons
last year. It showed British fans charging into the neighboring
stand and beginning the fatal stampede.
   English soccer clubs have been banned competing in Europe's
three main cup tournaments since the riot.
</TEXT>
