<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     10-24 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Claim Fall of Fifth Provincial Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas said Monday they
captured a provincial capital in northeastern Afghanistan, their
fifth since the start of the Soviet withdrawal in May.
   There was no independent confirmation.
   The Afghan News Agency, operated by the Hezb-i-Islami
guerrillas, said Mahmud-i-Raqi, 33 miles north of the Afghan
capital of Kabul, fell to its fighters Sunday.
   The guerrillas claimed Mahmud-i-Raqi fell after two days of
intense fighting in which about 100 Afghan government soldiers were
killed and 83 were captured. It claimed only four guerrillas were
wounded.
   The province has long been reported the domain of the rival
Jamiat-i-Islami group, which has kept the capital under siege.
   ``This is the first I heard of it,'' said Jamiat spokesman Basir
from his Peshawar, Pakistan headquarters.
   Hezb-i-Islami said guerrillas destroyed 21 tanks and captured
three. It also captured trucks, and light and heavy weapons.
   Western diplomats previously confirmed the guerrilla takeovers
of Kunar and Paktika provinces in the east, Takhar in the north and
Bamyan in central Afghanistan. All had been abandoned by
withdrawing Soviet troops, guerrillas said.
   Also Monday, Jamiat leader Burhanuddin Rabbani criticized U.N.
mediator Diego Cordovez for alleging guerrilla disunity and calling
for the formation of an Afghan government including communists and
Moslem guerrillas.
   Cordovez ``allows himself to interfere in the domestic affairs
of Afghanistan and to request certain individuals to form _ or help
to form _ the future government of Afghanistan,'' said Rabbani,
chairman of the seven-party guerrilla alliance, in a statement to
U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   ``We also wonder how Mr. Cordovez gives himself the right to
interfere in our affairs while he himself stated that only the
Afghans can decide their future,'' the message said.
   Cordovez mediated the U.N.-sponsored accord last spring in which
Moscow agreed to withdraw its more than 100,000 troops from
Afghanistan between May 15 and Feb. 15, 1989.
   The guerrillas, not a party to the negotiations, have rejected
the accord although they have scored a string of victories against
government troops since the pullout began.
   Guerrilla leaders repeatedly have rejected suggestions of
sharing power with the Marxist government of President Najib.
   The governing People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan seized
power in a bloody 1978 coup. Soviet troops intervened in December
1979 and have been fighting the U.S.-backed guerrillas ever since.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
