<2ND_LINE>PM-Trapped Elk, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0583,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Elk Trapped On Ledge Are Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS throughout to reflect that officials now say hunter
didn't kill elk, and that one of three fell off ledge.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DOLORES, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three elk trapped on a ledge were killed
over the weekend and two of the carcasses were donated to the
Dolores County Welfare Department, a state Division of Wildlife
official said today.
   The state had asked a hunter to kill the two cows and one calf,
stuck on a 12-foot by 80-foot ledge six feet below the top of a
cliff.
   Wildlife officers accompanied the hunter to Disappointment
Valley Saturday, but because of the difficult terrain the hunter
was unable to get into position to shoot the elk.
   A wildlife division officer shot two of the elk, and the other
fell off the ledge, said Mike Zgainer of the wildlife division
office in Durango.
   The elk were beginning to show the effects of hunger by late in
the week.
   The stranded elk were reported early last week, shortly after
elk season opened, by a rancher who complained that the wildlife
division planned to do nothing to rescue the three animals.
   Kip Stransky of the wildlife division said that after the
animals were killed, the hunting party made a sling and lowered the
carcasses from the ledge. The meat will be donated to the county
welfare department to help feed the poor.
</TEXT>
