<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape Recant,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov. Thompson Puts Off Decision on Dotson For Several Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. James R. Thompson said Monday he'll withhold
a decision on whether to pardon convicted rapist Gary Dotson until
he can determine the scientific reliability of a test that cleared
Dotson of the 1977 attack.
   The Illinois Prisoner Review Board was unanimous in recommending
the pardon, Thompson said.
   Dotson was convicted of raping Cathy Crowell Webb and was
sentenced to serve a 25- to 50-year prison term. Thompson in 1985
commuted the sentence to time served after Mrs. Webb recanted her
testimony.
   The governor said at the time he did not pardon Doston because
he did not believe Mrs. Webb's recantation. But Thompson also said
Dotson's time in prison equalled that of other convicted rapists,
and called the release a gesture of mercy.
   Dotson's attorney, Thomas Breen, contends Dotson deserves a
``full and complete pardon'' after the most recent test, a kind of
genetic fingerprinting performed by a California firm, exonerated
Dotson.
