<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Angola     10-24 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Disappointed With Senate Refusal To Fund Angola
Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administration told the Senate that its
refusal to allocate funds for a possible U.N. peacekeeping force in
southern Africa may delay the pullout of 50,000 Cuban troops from
Angola, it was disclosed Monday.
   The administration had sought permission from Congress to
transfer $150 million from a foreign aid account to a special fund
for peacekeeping operations. But the Senate balked in the final
hours of the 100th Congress, despite assurances Friday from
National Security Adviser Colin Powell that the United States would
not abandon Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi.
   The money was specifically intended to cover the U.S. share in
start-up costs of a 7,500-member U.N. force that would supervise a
Cuban pullout from Angola and independence for neighboring
Southwestern Africa, known as Namibia.
   Negotiations are at a stalemate over the timetable for a Cuban
pullout, but the administration is hoping for a breakthrough that
could come while Congress is in recess. The 100th Congress
adjourned on Saturday and the 101st will not be sworn in until
January.
   ``So naturally, we're disappointed'' that the money for the
peacekeeping force wasn't approved, State Department spokesman
Charles Redman said. ``We were hopeful that Congress would have
authorized this transfer, given the importance to the United States
of ongoing peacekeeping efforts in several regions of the world.''
   Senate approval was blocked by supporters of Savimbi, whose
UNITA organization has been receiving U.S. help in its fight
against the leftist Angolan government.
   The senators wanted assurances that Savimbi's future would be
included in any package worked out between Angola, South Africa and
Cuba, with the mediation of the United States.
   Seeking to assuage those concerns, Powell wrote Sen. Dennis
DeConcini, D-Ariz., on Friday assuring him the United States would
not abandon Savimbi until the Angolan government includes him in a
political settlement.
   U.S. support for ``the valiant UNITA ... has not and been and
will not be a bargaining chip in the negotiations for Cuban troop
withdrawal'' from Angola, Powell wrote.
   He urged DeConcini and his colleagues to approve funding for the
peacekeeping force. ``If there are insufficient funds ... Cuban
troop withdrawal will be delayed,'' he added.
   DeConcini dropped his objections to the administration's request
after reading Powell's Oct. 21 letter, but other opponents were not
swayed, an aide to the senator said.
   Angola has rejected U.S. urgings to discuss UNITA's role in a
settlement, saying the matter is an internal affair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
