<1ST_LINE>r p AM-FloridaEnglish     10-24 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida English,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Injunction Against English Language Referendum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday refused to bar from the Nov.
8 ballot a referendum to declare English the state's official
language.
   The ruling clears the way for Florida to join Arizona and
Colorado in posing ``Official English'' ballot questions to voters.
   U.S. District Judge James Kehoe refused to grant an injunction
sought by opponents of the measure, saying the citizens' initiative
did not violate the 1965 Voting Rights Act.
   A spokeswoman for Florida English, which sponsored the
initiative, called the ruling ``a great relief,'' but its opponents
said an appeal was certain.
   A class action with four Spanish-speaking residents of Dade
County as the named plaintiffs was filed against the ballot
proposal, known as Amendment 11. It contended that the proposal
violated the federal Voting Rights Acts because the petitions
seeking to put it on the ballot were circulated only in English.
   ``The state's involvement in the petition process does not
amount to state action triggering application of the Voting Rights
Act,'' Kehoe said in a seven-page ruling.
   ``While a petition initiative in Florida is subject to state
approval, such approval must be granted so long as certain format
requirements have been adhered to,'' the judge ruled.
   Under a provision of the Voting Rights Act, election literature
must be distributed in a second language in areas where more than 5
percent of the population has limited knowledge of English. That
would include Dade and five other counties _ Collier, Dade, Hardee,
Hendry, Hillsborough and Monroe.
   The suit was based on a Colorado suit that persuaded a federal
judge in Denver last month to invalidate thousands of signatures in
areas of Colorado where petitions for a constitutional amendment
making English that state's official language were not circulated
in Spanish.
   But one day after the Florida suit was filed, an appeals court
in Denver overturned the lower court decision.
   Kehoe noted in his final paragraph: ``The court stresses that
this decision in no way represents a judgment as to the merits of
the constitutional amendment at issue. Rather, the present ruling
is limited to the narrow question of whether the petition to place
the proposed amendment on the election ballot is subject to the
language minority requirements of the Voting Rights Act.''
   ``We were a private group, not a government agency,'' said Pat
Fulton, a spokeswoman for Florida English. ``It was really
stretching federal law'' to try to apply the Voting Rights Act.
   The suit's plaintiffs were backed by an organization named Speak
Up Now For Florida.
   ``My inclination is to appeal,'' said Donald Middlebrooks, an
attorney for the plaintiffs. ``I think the amendment is divisive to
the community. ... It is looked upon as anti-Hispanic.''
   Jeff Browne, statewide coordinator for Speak Up Now For Florida,
said there were excellent grounds for an appeal and that he was
certain one would be filed.
   ``We thought that at the trial court there was a very good
chance it would go against us, so we're well-prepared for that,''
he said by telephone from his Washington office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881024-0136 </DOCNO>
