<DOCNO> AP881024-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EMPSuit     10-24 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EMP Suit,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Group Files New Challenge of Nuclear Simulation
Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group and a North Carolina
regional planning commission filed suit against the Navy and
Defense Department on Monday, attempting to stop further testing of
a high-powered electrical generator that simulates one of the
effects of a nuclear blast.
   The suit, which requests preliminary and permanent injunctions,
accuses the Navy of starting tests of the Empress II generator off
the North Carolina coast this summer on the basis of a ``hopelessly
premature and flawed'' environmental impact statement.
   It accuses the Navy of ignoring potential adverse effects on
test workers and recreational or commercial boaters and fishermen,
as well as on marine life and the radio equipment of passing ships
and planes.
   ``Empress II poses a grave potential risk to the environment and
public health and we intend to shut it down until the Navy conforms
with federal laws governing environmental safety,'' said Jeremy
Rifkin, president of the Foundation on Economic Trends, an activist
environmental group based in Washington.
   The foundation filed suit in U.S. District Court here with the
Albemarle Commission, a regional planning and development
commission based in Hertford, N.C., that represents 24 local North
Carolina governments, including Currituck County.
   The Navy's initial testing of Empress II occurred this summer in
the waters of the Atlantic Ocean off the coast of Currituck County,
just south of the Virginia Capes near the Virginia-North Carolina
border.
   ``The radiation emitted by Empress II presents hazards to the
well-being of marine life and of human beings exposed to it,
including sailors, fishermen, tourists and others in the area
subjected to such radiation,'' the 19-page lawsuit asserts.
   The Navy declined immediate comment on the suit. Lt. Cmdr. Craig
Quigley, a Navy spokesman, said initial Empress II testing had been
completed for the year and would not resume until next summer.
   Empress II is a Navy barge that has been fitted with two diesel
generators and a huge spread of antennas. The equipment is capable
of sending ``pulses'' of electrical power into the atmosphere at
power levels up to 7 million volts to test a phenomenon known as
electro-magnetic pulse, or EMP.
   Each pulse lasts only a billionth of a second, and the Navy
maintains the testing will have no effect on human or marine life.
   Electro-magnetic pulse is a powerful wave, or surge, of
electrical energy that is released by a nuclear explosion and which
can travel long distances through the atmosphere or water.
   EMP became a matter of concern to the military in the early
1960s when the Pentagon discovered a nuclear bomb detonated at high
altitudes could generate a pulse so strong it could disable the
electronic components used in computers, communications and
guidance equipment.
   As a result of that discovery, military laboratories have
studied the phenomenon for 25 years in the course of developing
methods for ``hardening'' electronic weapon components to withstand
EMP. The Navy wants to use the Empress II barge to test its success
in hardening electronic equipment on its warships.
   The foundation sued the Defense Department in March 1987 with
the goal of stopping all EMP testing until environmental impact
studies had been performed.
   Earlier this year, the Pentagon agreed to settle that lawsuit by
sharply curtailing or shutting down EMP research facilities across
the country until environmental assessments were performed. In the
case of Empress II, however, the Navy argued it already had
performed the necessary environmental study and thus could proceed
with testing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
