<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RishTrial     10-24 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rish Trial,0377</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Kidnapping, Murder Trial of Nancy Rish Begins
^By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged with kidnapping a
businessman and helping bury him alive in a failed attempt to get
$1 million in ransom is the victim of mistaken identity, an
attorney said Monday.
   It was another woman _ not Nancy Rish _ who took part in the
abduction of Stephen Small, who was placed in a wooden box equipped
with a makeshift air system before being buried, defense attorney
Sherri Carr told the jury.
   But prosecutor Michael Ficaro said Rish was willing to help her
boyfriend kidnap Small, the great-grandson of a former Illinois
governor, because she wanted to share in ``the $1 million jackpot.''
   Small, 40, was abducted from his home in September 1987. He
suffocated when the air pipe in the box failed.
   Rish, 26, is charged with murder and kidnapping. Daniel Edwards,
31, her roommate, was convicted of the same charges in May and
sentenced to die.
   ``The burying of Stephen Small alive was what they were willing
to do for $1 million ... that ticket to easy street ... life in the
fast-lane,'' said Ficaro. ``The murder was a result of a cold,
callous, calculating plan of Nancy Rish and Danny Edwards for the
big score, the $1 million jackpot.''
   But Ms. Carr called the case ``a whodunnit'' and said the
defense would identify the woman who really helped Edwards carry
out the kidnapping.
   ``They would like you to believe this mystery is solved,'' she
said. ``The mystery is why this young woman (Ms. Rish) is sitting
before you today.''
   Fingerprints and hair samples taken in the case did not match
those taken from Rish, and soil samples from the remote grave site,
between Kankakee and the Indiana border, did not match soil on any
of Ms. Rish's shoes, Ms. Carr said.
   Ficaro told jurors they would hear a chilling tape recording of
Small's ``voice from the grave,'' pleading with his wife, Nancy, to
raise the $1 million ransom.
   The jury for Rish's trial was selected in Rockford because of
extensive news coverage of the case. The jury will be sequestered
during the trial.
</TEXT>
