<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1933EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Strikes     10-24 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Strikes,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wage Controls Are The Achilles Heel Of Economic Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking railroad workers
paralyzed train service and stranded tens of thousands of commuters
Monday to try to win wage increases and regain buying power lost to
inflation.
   Unions representing mailmen, teachers, doctors and other
employees among the estimated 1 million Argentines who work for the
state have staged, or are planning, similar walkouts in what has
become a major challenge to the government's anti-inflation program.
   President Raul Alfonsin said last week the government will try
to keep wage increases for state employees at 4 percent a month in
November and December, except in the industries where productivity
is increased. Private companies were urged to follow the same
guideline.
   Inflation for October is projected at 8 percent. Unions are
demanding wage increases of at least as much to keep pace with the
inflation rate, which was 25 percent in July, 27 percent in August
and 12 percent in September.
   Unions representing the railroad workers are demanding wage
increases of 39 percent for October.
   Postal workers went on strike on Monday and Tuesday last week,
and have called another nationwide strike for Wednesday. Mail
deliveries also were interrupted Friday and again this week.
   Flights of the national airlines, Aerolineas Argentinas, were
disrupted Friday by striking pilots, ground crew and other
personnel, who are planning further work stoppages.
   The 30,000 employees of the state oil company Yacimientos
Petroliferos Fiscales threatened to strike last week, but agreed to
accept 4 percent raises in November and December after the
government reduced the work day from eight hours to seven hours.
   Teachers in the Buenos Aires district won 15 percent pay raises
for October, but doctors at 150 public hospitals and court clerks
across the nation are to go on strike Wednesday.
   The country's biggest labor federation, the General Labor
Confederation, is demanding that the minimum wage of about $87 be
drastically increased.
   Carlos Menem, the opposition Peronist Party's candidate for
president in the national elections set for May, estimated last
week that workers' buying power has shrunk by 30 percent since
Alfonsin took office in December 1983.
   Since January 1984, inflation has soared by 49,466 percent and
the gross national product has remained stagnant for five years at
about $76 billion. Alfonsin's government has imposed wage and price
controls, currency devaluations and budget cutbacks in an
unsuccessful effort to curtail increases in the cost of living.
   The economy is the main issue in the political campaign and
Menem has promised pay raises and tax cuts if he is elected
president.
   Eduardo Angeloz, the presidential candidate of Alfonsin's
centrist Radical Civic Union, is depending on the government's
anti-inflation plan to take hold.
   Argentines will have to endure a ``clenched teeth struggle,''
Angeloz said in a campaign speech last week. Once the economy has
been reorganized by selling off state companies and boosting
exports, ``Argentina will finally recover its rightful place in the
world.''
   In a poll published by the newspaper La Nacion last week, twice
as many voters support Menem as Angeloz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
