<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GirlStrangled     10-24 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Girl Strangled,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Search for Strangler of 16-Year-Old Church Organist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREWTON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have narrowed to four the
list of suspects in the strangling of a 16-year-old church organist
who was abducted from the sanctuary where she was cleaning up for
services, police said Monday.
   One, an 18-year-old high school student, was interrogated for
about three hours Saturday night before police released him, Police
Chief Grover Smith said.
   ``We haven't eliminated him yet, but there was not enough
evidence to arrest him,'' he said, describing the case against the
student as ``very circumstantial.''
   Police have no idea why Stephanie King, a well-known teen-ager
in the southern Alabama city, was killed. Her body was found
Saturday afternoon in her car, which was parked in a wooded area
about four miles from Alco Baptist Church.
   But Smith said he thinks the girl was slain in a crime of
opportunity.
   ``He (the killer) just went over there (to the church), saw her
by herself and took advantage of the situation,'' the chief said.
   ``She wouldn't have had enough money to justify robbery, and
there was no indication of any (sexual) assault,'' he added.
   Smith said authorities ``believe this person forced her to drive
out where we found her. And the assault took place in the car,
apparently.''
   About 10:45 a.m. Saturday, Miss King had telephoned the Rev.
Bobby Rone from the church to tell him that someone there wanted to
talk to him, Smith said.
   Rone spoke to the unidentified person over the telephone and
answered his question about when the church office would be open,
Smith said.
   The pastor became concerned about the call because Miss King was
at the church alone. He went there and, not finding the girl,
contacted her family to see if she was home.
   Police do not know whether the caller was the killer.
   ``She was cleaning up the church, she had a part-time job
there,'' Smith said. He declined to comment about the position of
the body in the car or whether it appeared she might have known her
assailant.
   ``I'd rather not get into that,'' he said.
   Miss King was a senior honor student at T.R. Miller High School
and played with the school band, in addition to performing as the
church organist.
</TEXT>
