<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Legislation     10-24 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Legislation,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Signs Base-Closing Bill; Prepares To OK Veterans Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed legislation Monday
authorizing the Pentagon to close unneeded military bases as the
White House began poring over mounds of bills passed by Congress in
its waning days.
   Reagan, who often has complained about what he sees as
pork-barrel spending on Capitol Hill, kept his approval of the
base-closing legislation low-key. The president's approval of the
bill, passed overwhelmingly by both the House and Senate, was
merely noted in a White House press office statement listing an
assortment of bills he signed.
   Among the other pieces of legislation that Reagan signed were
one requiring the secretary of agriculture to set up a 10-year
program to study the effects of air pollutants on forest ecology.
He approved a bill extending temporary authority to pay overtime to
federal employees fighting forest fires and another one
establishing a new Technology Administration within the Commerce
Department.
   Reagan is scheduled to sign legislation Tuesday morning creating
a new Cabinet-level Department of Veterans Affairs. The president
will sign the legislation at the conclusion of a speech to the
National Defense University at Fort McNair in the District of
Columbia, the White House said.
   The bill giving the Defense Department authorization to close
bases has been estimated to have the potential of saving the
government up to $5 billion a year as Pentagon officials pare down
the list of 3,800 U.S. military installations.
   The Senate approved the bill 82-7 and the House followed shortly
afterward with a 370-31 vote.
   The bill sets up a complicated base-closing procedure which
essentially cuts through the thicket of laws enacted by Congress in
the past decade to thwart Pentagon efforts to shut down bases.
   It also endorses a Pentagon-appointed commission which has been
meeting for months, trying to put together a list of bases to be
closed. The current panel will be expanded to 12 members by the
bill.
   The panel will make its recommendations by Dec. 31. Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci would have until Jan. 15 _ five days
before he leaves office _ to either accept or reject the entire
list. He could not change the list.
   If Carlucci approves the list, Congress would have until
mid-April to overturn the proposal, but it could only do that by
approving a resolution which could then be vetoed by the incoming
president.
   No base closures would begin before 1990.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters that some
120 pieces of legislation had been received at the White House, and
that he expected action on many of them within the next few days.
Congress adjourned early Saturday.
   ``Out of 120 bills, some of them are going to be vetoed, yes,''
Fitzwater said. ``But I don't know which ones.''
   The spokesman said, for example, that while the White House has
signaled its general support for a bill making technical
corrections in the 1986 law overhauling the U.S. tax code, ``we
have major problems'' with some aspects of the legislation.
   Reagan is expected to sign legislation immediately authorizing
$500 million in new spending on the effort to combat drug
trafficking.
   The president's approval was virtually assured when the Senate
kept intact a House provision allowing for the death penalty for
certain crimes committed in the commission of drug trafficking.
   During his daily news briefing, Fitzwater called the 100th
Congress ``very productive'' and said ``we are extraordinarily
pleased that so many parts of the president's agenda have been
enacted into law in this Congress.''
   ``You all know the criticism that a lame duck president can't do
anything,'' he told reporters.
   He cited the timely passage of 13 appropriations bills financing
government operations in the new budget year, along with passage of
welfare reform, catastrophic illness and drug abuse legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
