<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Tree,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Helps Plant Tree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan turned seven shovelsful of
dirt Monday as he helped transplant a willow oak from Maryland on
the South Lawn of the White House as part of a program started by
Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1936.
   After the fourth shovelful, Reagan said, ``I may stay here.''
   After the seventh, a reporter asked him how long he thought it
would take to turn over the entire pile of dirt that had been
heaped up beside the 18-foot tall tree.
   ``It would seem as long as a press conference,'' he said.
Presidential press conferences usually last half an hour.
   ``I think I'll leave it to someone else,'' the president said.
   The tree, which is 14 years old, was grown at Angelica Nursery
in Kennedyville, on Maryland's Eastern Shore.
   It is a gift from the American Association of Nurserymen, which
formed a committee in 1979 to evaluate and maintain the White House
gardens and grounds.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the tree was planted
as part of a landscape plan commissioned by FDR three years after
he took office.
   The nurserymen's group also donated a sugar maple tree that
Reagan planted in 1984 just north of the West Wing.
   ``It is alive and flourishing,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
