<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1744EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NLRB-Harvard     10-24 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NLRB-Harvard,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NLRB Judge Rules In Favor of Union; Accuses Harvard of
Misrepresentations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Labor Relations Board judge on
Monday overruled Harvard University's objection to a union election
in May, accusing the university of misrepresenting both the union's
conduct and labor law.
   In a harshly worded opinion, NLRB Administrative Law Judge Joel
A. Harmatz certified the Harvard Union of Clerical and Technical
Workers as the winner in the election to unionize Harvard's 3,400
technical and clerical workers.
   The union, an affiliate of the 1 million-member American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, won the
election on a 1,530-1,486 vote characterized by a 90 percent
turnout among those eligible.
   Harmatz dismissed as unfounded Harvard's complaints that the
union illegally coerced ``yes'' votes through a coordinated
campaign to assure that union supporters cast ballots.
   Harvard's brief in the case, Harmatz said, ``is replete with
misinterpretations of the record'' of eight days of hearings the
NLRB held in August on the university's charges.
   ``Because these references either are not supported by, or
grossly overstate the proven facts, this decision seeks to, at this
level, bring a halt to this approach,'' the judge said.
   He further chastised Harvard, saying, ``Additional delay has
been occasioned by the employer's proclivity to disguise as fact
argumentative and sometimes frivolous interpretations'' of the
evidence in the case.
   The union drive, which began in 1975, and the university's
challenge had been viewed by several labor leaders as a major test
of their ability to organize new cadres of educated, white- and
gray-collar technical workers assuming a greater proportion of the
workforce.
   Harvard spokeswoman Marjorie Heffron said no decision has been
made on whether to appeal Harmatz's ruling to the full five-member
board. Under the law, it has two weeks to file an appeal.
   ``The university's position is sound, and the union acted
improperly,'' Harvard Vice President for Finance Robert Scott said
in a prepared statement, ``It is plain that the opinion (by
Harmatz) does not accurately reflect the record of the hearings in
many respects.''
   AFSCME President Gerald McEntee said Monday that the election,
and the NLRB action upholding the results, was crucial for AFSCME
and as ``a test case for the labor movement as a whole.''
   ``The issues raised in this campaign were the issues that affect
the workforce of today and tomorrow _ job and family issues that
include affordable, quality child care, decent pensions and
benefits and flexibility in hours of work,'' he said.
   Among other things, Harvard had accused the union of coercing
``yes'' votes by offering transportation to voting places and
maintaining lists of union supporters to assure that they cast
ballots.
   The university also claimed that a practice in which union
sympathizers often accompanied some of the voting workers to the
polls and the placing of pro-union balloons, banners and posters
around the campus but not in the polling places themselves also
amounted to coercion.
   ``Stripped of glossy unconfirmed characterization, the
employer's complaint here addresses a perfectly legitimate,
apparently successful, tactical maneuver by the union which was
calculated to convert pre-election support into `yes' votes to the
greatest extent possible,'' Harmatz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
