<2ND_LINE>AM-Operation Rescue, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religious Leaders Criticize Tactics of Anti-Abortion Group</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 11th graf pvs bgng, `More than,' with 1 graf to UPDATE
with release of protestors. Faith Evans is a man</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of religious groups on Monday
urged the leaders of Operation Rescue, the group responsible for
demonstrations blocking entrances to abortion clinics since July,
to ``repent.''
   ``Operation Rescue is an act of terrorism,'' Katherine Hancock
Ragsdale of the Episcopal Women's Caucus told a news conference.
``The illegal and immoral activities of Operation Rescue are a blot
on our nation's conscience.
   ``In the name of God, I call upon them to repent,'' she said.
   Ragsdale's views were shared by other representatives from some
of the 30 Jewish and Protestant religions that comprise the
Religious Coalition for Abortion Rights.
   ``Our organizations have gathered here today to announce that we
must _ and we will _ continue to defend our precious liberties,''
said Rabbi Jack Luxemburg of the American Jewish Congress.
   ``No group, no matter how many or how militant, will persuade us
to retreat to a time when women died from abortions obtained in
back alleys,'' he said.
   The coalition does not take issue with the New York-based
Operation Rescue's anti-abortion stance, but with the group's
methodology, which they said was a violation of a woman's
constitutional right to choose abortion, said coalition president
Faith Evans.
   ``They act as if there is a national debate about the right to a
woman to have an abortion, but there is not. That's been settled by
Roe versus Wade,'' Evans said of the landmark Supreme Court ruling.
   He noted that the coalition's Operation Respect would continue
to offer escort and counseling services for harassed clinic workers
and clients.
   Operation Rescue, which has called for nationwide demonstrations
on Oct. 29, attempts to prevent or dissuade women from having
abortions by blocking clinic entrances or by conducting sidewalk
counseling.
   More than 1,200 anti-abortion demonstrators have been arrested
and refused to accept bail since the protests began July 19 during
the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta. All of the
protestors, including 300 arrested in a demonstration earlier this
month, have been released.
   ``Theirs is not the message of love, compassion and concern that
a Jesus of Nazareth would condone. Theirs is a message of lies, of
hate, of cruelty and punishment reflective of the witch burners and
torturers, disguised in the name of religion,'' said Natalie
Gulbrandson of the Unitarian Universalist Association.
   Coalition members criticized Operation Rescue's attempts to
align their actions with the ``civil disobedience'' of the civil
rights movement, and decried Operation Rescue's attempts to compare
abortion to the Holocaust of World War II.
   ``By comparing abortion to the Holocaust, the civil rights
movement and anti-slavery movement, they impugn the humanity of
millions of Jewish and black people, '' said the Rev. Theodore H.
Erickson of the United Church Board for Homeless Ministries of the
United Church of Christ.
   ``The main thing about the civil rights movement,'' said Mary
Jane Patterson of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), ``was that the
people we sat in against were breaking the law. Abortion is not
against the law.''
</TEXT>
