<HEAD>Four Plead Innocent in Beating Death of Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four members of a Los Angeles-based youth
program pleaded innocent Monday to first-degree manslaughter
charges in the Oct. 14 beating death of an 8-year-old girl.
   Clackamas County Circuit Judge John Lowe scheduled a Dec. 12
trial for Willie K. Chambers, 35, of San Diego; Brian James
Brinson, 30; Constance Zipporah Jackson, 37; and Frederick Paul
Doolittle, 28, of Los Angeles.
   The death of the daughter of Eldridge Broussard Jr., leader of
the Watts Christian Center, led the state Children's Services
Division to remove 53 children from two homes the group operated in
Oregon. Two others are in custody in Los Angeles.
   On Oct. 14, four staff members took the body of Dayna Broussard
to a nearby fire station. She had been beaten and whipped, and died
of multiple blunt-  force injuries, authorties said.
   Juvenile authorities allege that the children were forced to
watch and keep count as adults, using paddles or electrical cords,
administered ritualistic beatings of up to 800 strokes to other
children.
   The beatings were intended to enhance athletic performance, not
to punish misbehavior, authorities have said.
   The four people who appeared in court Monday were jailed pending
a hearing Wednesday, said Deputy District Attorney Al French.
</TEXT>
