<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DodgersParade     10-24 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dodgers Parade,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Downtown Awash in Dodger Blue as Fans Honor Baseball Heroes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA14, LA15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNIE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50,000 jubilant Dodger fans Monday
joined their World Series champs for a party in the streets,
savoring the improbability of it all during a mid-day parade that
had downtown awash in a sea of blue.
   Fans, some dangling from tree limbs outside City Hall, hooted,
hollered and applauded wildly as their triumphant Los Angeles
Dodgers were introduced.
   Announcer Vin Scully called the celebration ``a love-in.''
   ``How sweet it is,'' yelled pitcher Orel Hershiser, the World
Series Most Valuable Player who last Thursday struck out the final
Oakland batter to win the championship and chalk up his second fall
classic victory.
   Nearby, fans hoisted a banner reading: ``A's Flunked the Orel
Exam.''
   ``I want to thank the greatest team that any manager could ever
have,'' said Manager Tommy Lasorda. Moments later, he began
lurching back and forth in a unique twist-style dance step after
recalling his spring training prediction that, come October, he
would be dancing in the streets.
   The victory parade for baseball's unlikely champions mixed deja
vu and Dodger Blue for southern Californians accustomed to reigning
sports champs.
   The world champion Los Angeles Lakers basketball team was the
focus of attention five months ago, drawing 40,000 fans to a
similar parade. In college football, the UCLA Bruins are rated No.
1 in the nation.
   ``With all the championships we've had here, it was about time
we came to one of the parades,'' said Jose Rodriguez, 28, of
Bloomington.
   Approximately 30,000 fans gathered curbside along Broadway to
see the players pass on floats while another 20,000 were clustered
at City Hall, said police Lt. Fred Nixon.
   One of the police officers keeping order was Michael Strawberry,
older brother of New York Mets slugger Daryl Strawberry. He
conceded: ``It's kind of strange that I'm here on Dodger Day.''
   Marching bands also participated in the Dodger Day ceremony,
featured on five Los Angeles television stations.
   ``I'm the ultimate Dodger fan,'' said Ernesto Zepeda, 30, a
Hughes Aircraft worker from El Segundo who, along with his
3-year-old son Ernie Jr., were paradeside with faces painted Dodger
Blue.
   Other fans wore T-shirts hawked by vendors. Other wares included
Dodger horns, pennants, buttons and even blue cotton candy.
   The Dodger party was sweeter in light of the team's improbable
victory over the Oakland Athletics, a highly touted club of
sluggers that won 104 games in the regular season.
   The players Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley called ``the
Cinderella team of the 1988 series'' stole the championship from
the A's in five games.
   The highlights included a ninth inning home run by a hobbling
Kirk Gibson to clinch the first game; a 6-0 shutout by Hershiser in
the second; Mickey Hatcher's two-run homers in the first and fifth
games; and a complete game by Hershiser in the fifth for the title.
   And the party isn't over yet for the Dodgers. On Wednesday, the
blue crew is off to the White House for a reception with President
Reagan, who said during the series he was a Dodger fan.
</TEXT>
