<1ST_LINE>r p AM-VotingAds     10-24 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Voting Ads,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bipartisan Ad Campaign Urges People To Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic and Republican party chairmen
briefly put aside their differences on Monday to endorse a
bipartisan television advertising campaign urging Americans to vote.
   They also combined their voices in criticizing news
media-sponsored election polls, which they say discourage voters
from going to the polls.
   The ad campaign, underwritten by Bell Atlantic, relies on
bipartisan commercials urging Americans to ``be more than just
talk'' and vote on Nov. 8.
   ``It seems to me we have lost sight that with the rights granted
under our form of government are certain very, very important and
fundamental responsibilities,'' said GOP Chairman Frank J.
Fahrenkopf Jr., lamenting the traditionally low voter turnout in
U.S. elections.
   ``In this the most advanced Democracy in the world, we have
close to the lowest voter turnout,'' said Democratic Chairman Paul
G. Kirk Jr. About 54 percent of Americans over 18 voted in the 1984
presidential election.
   Kirk, answering questions at a news conference where the ads
were unveiled, said the negative tone of this presidential campaign
has ``turned people off,'' which may affect voting levels this year.
   But he and Fahrenkopf said the media also could do more to
motivate and educate voters with their coverage of the campaign.
   They said they were concerned that polls commissioned by the
media to determine who was ahead in the campaign discouraged voters
from casting a ballot.
   When polls show one candidate comfortably ahead before the
election is over, ``people have a feeling, `What good is my
vote?,''' Fahrenkopf said. Kirk said polls undertaken by the news
media have a ``skewing effect and a psychological effect.''
   The get-out-the-vote ads feature appearances by Presidents
Carter and Ford. Felix Cavaliere of the Rascals singing group
rerecorded his 1968 song, ``People Got To Be Free,'' as the theme.
   The ads were produced in conjunction with Vote America, a
nonpartisan, nonprofit group that works to increase voter
participation.
</TEXT>
