<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 2019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UNAnniversary     10-24 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN Anniversary,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Marks Charter's 43rd Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations celebrated the 43rd
anniversary of its charter Monday with a U.N. Day peace walk in the
rose garden of the New York headquarters and praise of the world
organization's peacekeeping efforts.
   The celebration followed a weekend rebuff by the U.S. Senate
that rejected a Reagan administration request for $150 million to
help support current or anticipated U.N. peacekeeping efforts in
Afghanistan, the Persian Gulf and southern Africa.
   Some senators said they were not satisfied, despite
administration assurances, that U.S. aid to anti-Marxist rebels in
Angola would continue.
   Washington has been withholding regular dues to compel the
United Nations to make budgetary and political reforms. That has
made the United States, which is assessed 25 percent of the budget,
the largest debtor to the United Nations but still its largest
contributor.
   On Oct. 14, the United States paid $85.6 million in back dues,
reducing its regular-budget arrears to $366.3 million. It is
withholding another $59 million until the main U.N. financial
committee adopts austerity measures.
   U.N. officials had little to say Monday about the Senate action.
   ``There is no reaction,'' said Francois Giuliani, spokesman for
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar. ``Obviously member
states have a legal obligation to participate in peackeeping
operations, as assessed by the General Assembly, but this is an
internal (U.S.) problem.''
   Officials and diplomats strolled silently through the U.N. rose
garden on the banks of the East River in a meditative ``walk for
peace.''
   In a statement marking U.N. day, Perez de Cuellar said the
United Nations is playing a larger peacemaking role.
   ``After years of drift and decline in multilateral cooperation,
the organization has begun to resume its rightful role in
international life,'' he said.
   Dante Caputo, foreign minister of Argentina and current
president of the General Assembly, told a gathering Sunday at the
Cathedral of St. John the Divine in New York that the world
situation is improving and the United Nations has been instrumental
in resolving conflicts.
   ``The threats of nuclear catastrohe, great power tensions and
many regional conflicts and problems have been significantly
lessened this year,'' he declared.
   This year's Nobel Peace Prize went to U.N. peacekeeping
operations around the world.
   Perez de Cuellar praised the peacekeepers in his statement and
said the United Nations ``no longer is bypassed or ignored.''
   He said the United Nations should avoid ``self-congratulation''
because nations with the will to make peace deserve the credit, and
``we are but the servants of this will.''
   The United Nations is the instrument for translating ``the
impulse for peace into concrete agreements,'' he added, and ``helps
show the way to peace with honor and compromise without
capitulation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881024-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-24 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Falls in the Upper Great Lakes As the Sun Shines Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell Tuesday on Michigan's Upper Peninsula and rain spread
from New England southward along the Atlantic coast while much of
the nation was treated to a day of autumn sunshine.
   West and northwest winds blew across the Great Lakes, bringing
much cooler air and cloudy skies to the region and the Ohio Valley.
Wind gusts averaged 25 to 35 mph around the lower Great Lakes.
   Up to 6 inches of snow was reported Monday afternoon at
Ironwood, Mich., and up to 5 inches was measured at Bessemer, with
an additional inch or two expected. Four inches of snow also was
reported at Hurley in Iron County, Wis.
   Light snow fell in northern Indiana and the mountain areas of
Pennsylvania, and rain was scattered across the central Great Lakes.
   In Michigan, heavy rains since early September have turned
grain-rich central areas into mud, and farmers say their fields are
too wet to harvest or plant next year's crops.
   So much rain has fallen since the drought ended that average
statewide precipitation for the year is only 5 inches below the
normal 25{ inches, according to the National Weather Service.
   ``It's so wet and so soggy, (farmers) take their equipment out
there and they just go straight down,'' said Bob Craig of the
Michigan Farm Bureau. ``They get stuck _ it's as simple as that.''
   Elsewhere, skies were mostly sunny across much of the rest of
the country, but low clouds and fog socked in parts of the Pacific
coast.
   Temperatures varied from the 30s and 40s across the upper
Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and parts of New England to the
80s in southern Florida, the southern tip of Texas and the desert
Southwest.
   Miami broke its 1979 record high of 88 degrees for the date with
an 89-degree reading. West Palm Beach, Fla., tied its 1983
temperature of 88.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees at Ely, Hibbing and Thief River Falls, all in Minnesota, to
91 degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz. The low in the nation Tuesday
morning was 11 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Tuesday, northwesterly winds will bring widespread showers
over the Great Lakes and New England, mixed with wet snow at times.
Rain also was forecast for Washington state, while fair skies were
predicted from the northern Rockies through the Plains into the
southern Atlantic states.
   Afternoon highs were expected to reach the 60s and 70s across
much of the country, but in the 40s and 50s from the northern
Rockies and northern Plains through Iowa, the Ohio Valley and New
England and the mid-Atlantic states. For the upper Mississippi
Valley and upper Great Lakes, highs were forecast in the 30s. On
the warm side, highs in the 80s were predicted for southern
Florida, southern and central Texas and across the Southwest to the
interior valleys of California, but in the low to mid 90s in the
desert.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
