<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     10-24 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Disperse Demonstrators, Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Police used clubs Monday to
disperse about 500 people protesting a Roman Catholic church order
to transfer an activist priest. Radio stations reported several
injuries, including one person shot in the leg.
   It was the third week of demonstrations protesting the transfer
order of the Rev. Jean Bertrand Aristide, considered to be Haiti's
most popular priest.
   Radio Inter and Radio Antilles, independent stations, said
police struck protesters with billy clubs, injuring several. A
woman told Radio Inter she saw a man shot in the leg.
   The police and army refused comment.
   Ten policemen and two trucks filled with soldiers were on hand
for the protest. The crowd of about 500 was the smallest since the
church order was announced. It was the first time authorities used
force on pro-Aristide demonstrators.
   His superiors at the Salesian Order in Rome want Aristide out of
Haiti on grounds his preaching on ``active non-violence''
encourages class struggle.
   They told the priest to report to the St. Claire church in
Montreal, Canada, by Oct. 17, but friends say he remains in Haiti.
   A massacre at Aristide's slum-neighborhood church Sept. 11, in
which thugs killed 12 people and wounded more than 70, was a factor
in the most recent military coup.
   Sergeants seeking democratic reforms and an end to
state-sponsored violence overthrew Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy on Sept.
17 and put Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril in power.
</TEXT>
