<HEAD>Bush Targets Hispanic Voters With Texas Ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush's campaign
launched a new advertising drive aimed at Hispanic voters Monday
with bilingual ads featuring his daughter-in-law, Columba, and
three Bush grandchildren.
   In the new Bush ad, Columba Bush, who was born in Mexico and is
the wife of Bush's son Jeb, appears with the couple's three
children and Bush.
   ``For Hispanics like me this presidential election will be the
most important in our history,'' Mrs. Bush begins.
   The vice president winds up the commercial saying, ``As
president, I'll have a lot of reasons to help Hispanics everywhere,
because I'll not only be answering to my grandchildren, I'll be
answering to history.''
   Bush campaign officials said the new advertisement, which is
being aired in both Spanish and English, is designed to take
advantage of what they called Spanish-speaking Michael Dukakis'
failure to appeal to the substantial Hispanic vote in Texas.
   ``We think, from our internal surveys, that there is a
tremendous opportunity in the (Rio Grande) Valley and within the
Hispanic community overall in the state,'' said Reggie Bashur,
deputy campaign manager.
   ``Dukakis has not gotten his message through in Texas, and
clearly he has not gotten a message through to Hispanics,'' Bashur
said.
   Mark Sanders, a Bush campaign spokesman, said the commercial
began airing Monday on stations in Dallas, Houston, San Antonio,
the Rio Grande Valley and El Paso. They will run until the Nov. 8
election, he said, while declining to say how much money was being
spent on them.
</TEXT>
