<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO     10-24 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Seeks Turkish Backing for Independent Palestinian State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat met on Monday
with Turkish Premier Turgut Ozal and President Kenan Evren in his
fast-paced quest for support for an independent Palestinian state
in the Israeli-occupied lands.
   The leader of the Palestine Liberation Organization flew to
Ankara from Iraq, where he held weekend discussions with presidents
Saddam Hussein of Iraq and Hosni Mubarak of Egypt.
   Arafat and Mubarak first met King Hussein of Jordan in Aqaba,
Jordan, on Saturday and then went on to Iraq.
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile,
is scheduled to meet next month in Algeria to decide on an
independent Palestinian state.
   British diplomat William Waldegrave said Monday in Abu Dhabi,
United Arab Emirates, that Britain welcomed peace moves by Jordan's
Hussein and Arafat, and said if Israel failed to respond, ``then it
will find itself very isolated in the world community.''
   Waldegrave, minister of state for foreign and Commonwealth
affairs, told a news conference at the British Embassy: ``I think
we can have some influence on the United States in bringing it to
see that Israel must respond.''
   But in an interview broadcast in London on Monday, Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel said the PLO will never change,
and so Israel _ which views the PLO as a terrorist organization _
will never negotiate with it.
   In Cairo, Egypt, visiting Norwegian Defense Minister Johan
Joergen Holst said Monday that the recent meetings of Arab leaders
showed ``something is happening'' which will bring closer an
international peace conference.
   Holst said of the Jordanian-Egyptian-Palestinian summit on
Saturday: ``I think this meeting serves eloquent notice that
something is happening (with) a new initiative and a new momentum.
   ``I think this will bring the world closer to the international
peace conference to settle the problem,'' he added.
   Both the United States and Israel oppose convening an
international conference on the Arab-Israel conflict with PLO
participation.
   Turkey's Ozal said in a dinner speech that he believed the
Palestine National Council ``will adopt a policy that will lead to
a legitimate and lasting peace process in the Middle East.''
   Ozal said the Palestinian problem could come to an end with the
recognition of the legitimate rights of Palestinian people,
including self-determination and establishment of an independent
state. He said Israeli troops should withdraw from the occupied
Arab lands.
   Turkey recognizes the PLO as the sole legitimate representative
of the Palestinian people.
   In Amman, Jordan, a senior PLO official said Monday that King
Hussein's meeting with Arafat signaled a ``new era in the history
of relations between Jordan and the PLO.''
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
meeting ``had a positive impact on all aspects of
Jordanian-Palestinian relations.''
   He said the simultaneous Amman meetings of the joint committee
that disperses funds in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip were held in a ``brotherly atmosphere.''
   The PLO official told The Associated Press that the committee
meetings focused on the situation in the occupied territories, torn
by a Palestinian uprising since last December, and ways of
increasing financial aid from Arab countries.
   In his broadcast remarks, Shamir dismissed as a ``tactical step
of doubletalk'' any notion of the PLO's reconciling itself to
Israel's existence.
   Shamir said on British Broadcasting Corp. radio: ``We know the
PLO. They will never change their character, their philosophy, and
therefore we will never negotiate with them.''
   Asked if he had any sympathy for the Palestinian demand for a
homeland, Shamir said: ``My objective is to solve our problems and
not the problems of the Arabs and Palestinians.''
</TEXT>
