<HEAD>Hampshire College President Picked To Head MacArthur Foundation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hampshire College President Adele Simmons has
been selected to head the MacArthur Foundation, one of the nation's
largest philanthropic organizations, a foundation spokesman said
Monday.
   ``We are delighted to have settled on Mrs. Simmons to become
president of the foundation,'' said Thornton Bradshaw, chairman of
the foundation's board of directors.
   Mrs. Simmons, 47, became president of Hampshire College in
Amherst, Mass., in 1977.
   ``Adele has been central to Hampshire's success,'' said John
Watts, chairman of the college's board of trustees. ``Her
contributions will serve the college well for many years to come.''
   The foundation, formally known as the John D. and Catherine T.
MacArthur Foundation, has assets of $2.5 billion and annual grants
of $127 million, in fields ranging from health, education and
environmental concerns to international peace and cooperation and
mass communications.
   John Corbally, who has directed the foundation's philanthropic
efforts since 1979, will retire in May 1989.
