<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Ships 1stLd-Writethru a0686 10-24 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Ships, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0686,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Ship Captain Charged With Manslaughter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 18 pvs `In the Italian port ...' with 1 graf to
restore name of ship owner Aldo Grimaldi. PICKS up 19th pvs ``The
Greek press ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of an Italian freighter that
collided with a Greek cruise ship and left two people dead and two
others missing appeared in court Monday on manslaughter charges and
said he was not to blame for the accident.
   Capt. Flavio Caminale, of Genoa, Italy, was arrested Friday
after his freighter Adige hit and sank a Greek cruise ship carrying
486 British students and their teachers.
   Two Greek seamen were killed and more than 60 people were
injured before the 6,300-ton cruise ship Jupiter went down less
than one mile off Piraeus harbor near Athens. Two British
passengers _ Vivienne Barley, 14, and Bernard Butt, 41 _ were
missing and presumed dead, the Merchant Marine Ministry said.
   Caminale, 45, is charged with manslaughter through negligence,
causing serious injuries, causing a shipwreck and ignoring shipping
regulations.
   ``I'm innocent,'' Caminale said during the 30-minute hearing.
   ``I was not technically responsible for this tragedy and am very
sorry about the death of these people,'' a weeping Caminale said
outside court.
   District attorney Antonis Roussos and investigating magistrate
Telemachus Flezouras ordered the captain detained pending a court
appearance Wednesday in which he will be questioned and the charges
formally recorded.
   Under Greek judicial procedure, a defendant must be presented
with the charges in a court the next working day after his arrest.
In a subsequent hearing, he is questioned at length and the
magistrate revises the charges if necessary before formalizing them.
   The magistrate will decide Wednesday whether Caminale will be
jailed pending trial. If convicted of the charges, Caminale could
spend one to five years in prison.
   The 5,500-ton Adige was sailing into Piraeus with a cargo of
automobiles when it punched a hole in the side of the Jupiter,
which was taking the British children and their teachers on an
eight-day Mediterranean cruise. The children jumped overboard and
were picked up by tugboats and fishing vessels before the Jupiter
sank 40 minutes later.
   Two Jupiter crewmen died when they were crushed against the
ship's side as they tried to attach cables from a tugboat.
   More than 60 passengers were hospitalized, most suffering from
shock and minor injuries. All but one have returned to Britain.
   None of the Adige's 22-member crew was injured and the vessel
suffered only minor damage.
   Greek and Italian accounts of the collision differ sharply.
   The Jupiter's chief mate, Kyriakos Moustakis, said the Adige was
heading toward the cruise ship on a collision course and failed to
change direction.
   Under international maritime rules, ships leaving harbor have
right of way.
   Caminale said the Adige was waiting for a Greek pilot to assist
it in docking and was not moving when the Jupiter changed course
and plowed into its prow.
   In the Italian port city of Genoa, Aldo Grimaldi, owner of the
Italian freighter, said Monday that Greek officials were trying to
hide the truth about the accident to protect their own tourism.
   ``The Greek press ... is accomplishing this moral lynching of
Commander Caminale ... We have asked for the intervention of the
Ministry of the Merchant Marine and the Foreign Ministry as well as
the Italian ambassador in Athens to protect the good name of the
Italian merchant navy and of our crew that did all it could to save
human lives,'' he added.
   Grimaldi echoed Caminale's comments that the Italian ship had
stopped when the Jupiter changed course and struck the Italian ship
in the bow as it turned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
