<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins For Two Cleveland Teamsters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts two grafs after 2nd graf to UPDATE with start of
testimony, estimate of length of trial. Picks up 3rd graf pvs,
`Friedman, a...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Teamsters president Jackie Presser
could hire as he saw fit at his local and did so in conjunction
with his secret role as an FBI informant, a defense lawyer said in
opening statements at a racketeering trial Monday.
   Harold Friedman, 66, and Anthony Hughes, 52, are the remaining
defendants in an alleged ``ghost employee'' scheme federal
prosecutors contended was masterminded by Presser, international
president of the Teamsters from 1983 until July 9, when he died of
brain cancer.
   The first prosecution witness in a trial that could run eight
weeks was Richard A. Crino, an area administrator with the U.S.
Department of Labor.
   He explained the federal financial disclosure statement union
locals are required to submit. The documents contain names of paid
employees at Teamsters Local 507 in Cleveland, some of whom
allegedly were paid but did no work.
   Friedman, a Teamsters international vice president and president
of 5,000-member Local 507 in Cleveland, has since replaced Presser
as president of the Ohio Conference of Teamsters.
   Friedman is charged with two counts of labor racketeering, two
of embezzlement and two of filing false reports with the Department
of Labor.
   Anthony Hughes, 52, recording secretary at the local, faces two
counts of labor racketeering and one of embezzlement.
   They and Presser were indicted May 16, 1986.
   The indictment alleges that four men were hired and paid more
than $700,000 while doing no work for the union. Hughes is alleged
to have been one of the so-called ``ghosts,'' getting paid by
Bakery Workers Local 19 in Cleveland, a close affiliate of
Teamsters Local 507. Allen Friedman, George Argie and Jack Nardi
were identified in the indictment as Teamsters Local 507 ghosts.
   Since the indictment, the Justice Department has revealed that
Presser and Hughes had been FBI informants, providing information
about the union and possible links to organized crime.
   Two FBI agents based in Cleveland in 1985 gave sworn statements
during an FBI internal investigation that Presser was authorized to
place certain people on the Local 507 payroll in order to protect
his informant status.
   Paul J. Cambria Jr., Friedman's attorney, said in opening
statements that the bylaws of Local 507 give its
secretary-treasurer full authority to hire business agents and
assign them their duties. Presser was the local's secretary
treasurer, Cambria said; Friedman was its president.
   ``But Presser's gone. He's not here to talk about what he told
my client and others. And in this case, that's a crime and that my
client is here on trial is a crime,'' Cambria said.
   Cambria told the jury Friedman had nothing to do with Presser
relationship with the FBI.
   Allen Friedman, Argie and Nardi are expected to testify for the
government, said prosecutor Stephen Jigger, head of the Cleveland
office of the Justice Department's Strike Force Against Organized
Crime.
   Jigger said in his opening statement that testimony will reveal
that Presser and Hughes set up a ``sham defense'' in 1985 with the
help of an FBI agent in an attempt to block an embezzlement
prosecution.
   ``Very simply, this case is about the abuse of union office by
Jackie Presser, Harold Friedman and Anthony Hughes by paying in
excess of $700,000 to people who did no work,'' Jigger said.
   Detailed defense demands for government documents plus Presser's
health problems resulted in repeated delays of the trial, which
U.S. District Judge George White originally scheduled to start more
than a year ago.
   Jurors were selected Friday.
</TEXT>
