<HEAD>Boys Town Student Mayor Still Waiting Reply From Bush, Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOYS TOWN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young people haven't received the
recognition that's due them from presidential candidates George
Bush and Michael Dukakis, Boys Town student mayor Corey Randall
said Monday.
   Randall, 17, a senior, sent letters Sept. 27 to the two
presidential candidates, listing the main issues facing children
and youth.
   The mayor, whose duties are much like those of a student body
president, was still waiting for a reply, and said he was
disappointed in not getting one.
   Randall drafted the letters after students in religion classes
at the home for abused and neglected youth were asked to vote on
topics they thought the next president should address.
   Part of the letter read: ``We come from 44 of the 50 states in
the Union, and we know from our own personal experiences of
brokenness _ perhaps better than most boys and girls in America _
the importance of these issues.''
   The most important issues listed by the students included:
freedom from abuse; freedom from hunger; good health care; literacy
for children; therapy for abuse and neglect; hope for children
without homes and away from home; and good schools.
   Randall said that if Republican Bush and Democrat Dukakis do
respond, he would like them to tell the 500 children of Boys Town
what they're going to do about childrens' needs.
</TEXT>
