<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VincennesHomecoming 1stLd-Writethru a0711 10-24 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes Homecoming, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0711,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emotional Return For Vincennes, Cruiser That Downed Iranian
Airliner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Reorganizes throughout to move up captain's disputing a
portion of official Pentagon report. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos GO2, GO6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy captain whose ship shot down a
civilian aircraft over the Persian Gulf disputed a Pentagon
report's suggestion that stress played a role in the tragedy, as
the crew arrived Monday for an emotional homecoming.
   ``There, of course, were mistakes made and there always are in
an intense combat environment,'' Capt. Will C. Rogers III said at a
news conference. ``But both my crew and the system performed
basically as designed. No particular mistake was critical to the
engagement decision ... It's my opinion that stress was not a
factor during the entire engagement proceedings.''
   The official Pentagon report concluded the crew of the USS
Vincennes mistook the airliner for an Iranian F-14 fighter jet on
July 3, resulting in the deaths of all 290 people aboard. It said
crew members misinterpreted computer and radar data because of
stress in their first combat situation. At the time, the Vincennes
was engaged in a firefight with several Iranian gunboats.
   Monday's return of the Aegis-class cruiser marked the end of a
six-month deployment for the crew of the Vincennes, named for a
Revolutionary War battle near Vincennes.
   ``We're glad to be home, I assure you of that. This is a nice
place,'' said Rogers, who earlier got a kiss, a hug and flowers
from his wife, Sharon.
   After a brief welcoming ceremony featuring William Rose, mayor
of Vincennes, Ind., and Rep. Bill Lowery, R-Calif., of San Diego,
the 380 sailors poured off the ship into a sea of relatives,
friends and Navy colleagues.
   One woman held a sign that read, ``I love you Beefcake
Collins.'' A little girl waved to her father and said ``Hi, daddy.
You're home!'' One sailor bolted down the gangway, crying ``Hi
mom,'' and gave his mother a hug.
   ``I don't even know what we were doing there. It's a tragedy
that it happened. But I'm glad I'm home and I'm alive,'' said Petty
Officer 3rd Class Steve Hile of Niles, Mich., who got a warm
embrace from his girlfriend, Vallita Lawwill.
   Rogers said the fate of the USS Stark, on which 37 sailors died
in an Iraqi missile attack, was in the back of his mind throughout
the Vincennes deployment.
   ``No skipper sails in the (Persian) Gulf without the Stark at
least in your subconscious,'' Rogers said. ``Was it a factor during
that decision process? I don't consciously remember.''
   In response to a question from an Iranian reporter, Rogers said
he regretted the loss of civilian life. Asked if there were lessons
in the tragedy, he said: ``We wish we had 100 percent hindsight.
That's not a luxury you have in combat.''
   The captain said that he knew within 1{ hours after ordering two
missiles fired that the target destroyed was a civilian airliner.
Rogers said he later assembled the crew to tell them the news and
that they took it quietly.
   ``At first we were all devastated,'' Rogers said. ``It goes
without saying. But I have to look at it, and my crew looks at it,
that given the fact that the airliner made no indication that it
was not a hostile craft, we had no other choice.
   ``So our grief and our despair over that is tempered by the
knowledge that we did what we had to do when we had to do it ... I
reviewed those few seconds one hundred times, one thousand times.
My decision was correct.''
   Navy chaplain Ted Atwood, who visited the crew from Sept. 27 to
Oct. 5 and talked frequently with the families of crew members,
said many sailors came to grips with the tragedy on the way home.
   ``When I was on board, I did not see a single depressed
sailor,'' Atwood said. ``Of course, the loss of lives is grievous
in any situation. I think they absorbed it and they have dealt with
it and they have grown beyond that grievous incident.''
</TEXT>
