<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UraniumPlant     10-24 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uranium Plant,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Governor Softens Call for Plant's Shutdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Celeste on Monday toned down his
demand that a federally owned uranium processing plant be closed
until something is done to stop the pollution it creates.
   Celeste urged instead that the nuclear weapons plant's
production workers be involved in a cleanup of the site near
Fernald, 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati.
   Celeste spoke at a news conference where he appeared with
leaders of a coalition of 14 striking employees' unions at the
plant, known officially as the Feed Materials Production Center.
   Last Tuesday, Celeste sent President Reagan a letter demanding a
shutdown of the plant until measures could be taken to ensure the
health and safety of employees and residents. But that same day,
Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, disagreed with Celeste and said the
Department of Energy is more likely to proceed with cleaning up
radioactive wastes on the plant's 1,050-acre site if the facility
stays in operation.
   The governor said he would not want to see the Energy Department
abandon the plant. DOE officials said last week they have no plans
to close the plant and have already begun a 10-year, $500 million
program to clean up and modernize it.
   ``I shudder to think what would happen if the Department of
Energy tried to wash its hands of this facility,'' Celeste said.
``We know that a cleanup can be accomplished, and the people best
to do it are the people who work there.''
   The plant has been widely criticized since the DOE admitted in
January 1985 that at least 200,000 pounds of radioactive uranium
oxide dust have been released into the atmosphere from the plant
during its 37 years of operation.
   Celeste said he sent a telegram Monday to Energy Secretary John
Herrington requesting a meeting to review the federal plans and
timetable for cleaning up the plant site. The department received
the telegram in Washington but Herrington had no immediate response
on when such a meeting might occur, department spokesman Tom Bauman
said.
   The state of Ohio has had a lawsuit pending against the Energy
Department since 1985, accusing it of polluting air and water at
the site. State officials and environmentalists are worried that
radioactive runoff from the plant could threaten the underground
Great Miami River aquifer, which supplies water for businesses and
some southwestern Ohio communities.
</TEXT>
