<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 2239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Nicaragua     10-24 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Renews U.N. Bid To Pressure U.S. on World Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua is asking the General Assembly
once again to condemn the United States for ignoring a World Court
ruling that bars U.S. aid to Nicaraguan rebels.
   Nicaragua also is protesting what it says is U.S. interference
in its domestic affairs.
   The Nicaraguan resolution _ identical to one submitted last year
and marking the third consecutive year Nicaragua makes the request
_ says all states are obliged under international law not to
intervene in the internal affairs of other states.
   The General Assembly will consider the agenda item sometime next
month.
   U.S. aid to Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, is seen by many
nations as a violation of the principle of non-interference and of
the June 17, 1986 ruling by the International Court of Justice.
   The court, the central U.N. legal body, ruled against the United
States regarding U.S. military and financial aid to the Contras.
Under the U.N. Charter, all member states agree to abide by the
decisions of the World Court.
   But the United States often has ignored the court and its
rulings when they run counter to what Washington perceives to be
U.S. interests.
   This year's Nicaraguan resolution urgently demands full and
immediate U.S. compliance with the court ruling.
   The 159-nation General Assembly has overwhelmingly voted each
year since 1986 to support Nicaragua and uphold the World Court
ruling. The vote last year was 94-2, with 48 abstentions and the
remainder absent. The United States and Israel voted ``no.''
</TEXT>
