<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     10-24 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Four Towns; 15 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels raided four towns in
northern Colombia late Sunday and early Monday and blew up three
bridges to prevent army pursuit, Antioquia state Gov. Antonio
Roldan Betancur said.
   According to police, 13 guerrillas, one policeman and one
soldier were killed, he said.
   National police reported that a total of 400 guerrillas attacked
the four towns _ Turbo, Necocli, Saiza and Currulao _ within a few
hours, Roldan said in a broadcast interview with the Colombian
radio chain RCN.
   Guerrillas have attacked 24 towns and 33 government security
installations this year, the worst wave of rebel raids since the
guerrillas organized 25 years ago.
   An attack on Saiza on Aug. 23 killed 42 people _ 18 guerrillas,
12 civilians, 10 soldiers and two policemen.
   The governor said the latest attacks were made by the Colombian
Revolutionary Armed Forces and the People's Liberation Army. He
called the raids in the north's banana-growing region an obvious
attempt to undermine parts of Colombia prior to a one-day general
strike declared for Thursday.
   Colombia's two largest labor unions _ the Workers' Unitary
Central and the General Confederation of Labor _ declared the
strike to protest the nation's 22 percent inflation, to demand a
price freeze and an increase in the minimum wage, and to try to
force government action against right-wing death squads.
   The army said last week it uncovered plans by Colombia's six
guerrilla groups to send armed rebels into the streets during the
strike and to blow up bridges, highways, communications facilities
and electric power lines Thursday.
   Colombia's last big general strike was in 1977, when 29 people
were killed when soldiers fired on rioters in Bogota.
   Death squads have killed about 900 people in the last two years,
including 180 labor unionists.
   The minimum wage in Colombia is about $90 a month. It usually is
adjusted once a year to compensate for inflation. The next
adjustment is due in January.
</TEXT>
