<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Frat-SlaveAuction     10-24 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Frat-Slave Auction,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fraternity Suspended For `Slave Auction'; Eight Protesters
Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight people were arrested Monday for
protesting outside a University of Wisconsin fraternity that was
suspended for holding a mock slave auction, complete with
black-painted faces and Afro wigs.
   ``Going to classes is a priority, but I'm willing to get
arrested for this,'' said protester Kris Hoeksema, 18.
   Demonstrators took turns chaining themselves to a bench outside
the Zeta Beta Tau house and being removed by police. They vowed to
return until the fraternity is ousted from the campus.
   The school's Interfraternity Council said Monday Zeta Beta Tau
was suspended indefinitely from social, athletic and other events
pending the outcome of an investigation.
   Assistant Dean of Students Roger Howard said the auction was
held Thursday night. He said the participants ``would put on skits
and then the pledges would be put on auction for the sale of their
services.''
   Efforts to contact the fraternity for a comment Monday were
unsuccessful because members were not answering the telephone or
their door.
   Madison police said the protesters were cited for unlawful
trespass on fraternity property and were released. Such citations
carry fines of $150.
</TEXT>
