<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-OilRig     10-24 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Oil Rig,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Bodies Recovered From Remains of Offshore Oil Rig</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five bodies have been recovered from
the shattered remains of the offshore oil rig Piper Alpha that sank
in the North Atlantic last July leaving 112 people missing, police
reported Monday.
   They were the first bodies to be found in the huge, four-story
living section of the rig that caught fire and exploded on July 6,
claiming 167 lives.
   It is believed many of the 107 workers still listed as missing
will be found in the accomodations section of the platform that was
retrieved during a massive salvage operation. Barges and cranes
salvaged the section and transported it to the Orkney Islands off
of Scotland's northern tip.
   The five bodies were found Sunday but have not been identified,
a police spokesman in Aberdeen said.
   The rig's dormitory section, welded to a barge, arrived Saturday
at an oil terminal of the platform's operator, Occidental Petroleum
Corp.
   There, in shallow water, 40 police officers began searching and
found the five bodies, according to the spokesman. He declined to
comment when asked if other bodies had been found Monday.
   Occidental spokesman Alex Blake-Milton issued a statement saying
work was continuing at the site of the tragedy, 120 miles off the
northeastern coast of Scotland, to strengthen the remains of the
platform to ensure safe passage for ships.
</TEXT>
