<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 2302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0731 10-24 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0731,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Renews Racism Complaint Against Bush Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Little Rock appearance, INSERT four grafs
after 5th pvs, ``They are...''
^With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential
candidate Lloyd Bentsen, stumping in Gerald Ford's old
congressional district, attacked what he called ``racist''
Republican advertising Monday as appealing to the lowest instincts
of the electorate.
   The Texas senator also told local businesmen that sticking with
GOP policies was not good enough in a changing world that includes
a ``decline of the Russian empire.''
   On Sunday, Bentsen agreed in response to a question by a TV
interviewer that the Bush campaign was making a racist appeal in
its attacks on Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis as being soft on
crime.
   Talking to reporters Monday, Bentsen cited the GOP's focus on
the case of convicted murderer Willie Horton Jr., who raped a
Maryland woman and slashed her fiance last year after Horton had
escaped from a Massachusetts prison furlough.
   ``They are obviously dealing with a black man who, in that
instance, had raped a white woman, and that certainly came through
in the ad,'' said Bentsen. Asked what came through, he replied
``racism.''
   And in Little Rock, Ark., Monday night, Bentsen told a black
congregation at the Greater Paradise Baptist Church that the
Republicans ``bear false witness against Michael Dukakis and we're
gong to set that record straight.''
   ``The truth is catching up,'' he said. ``And the power of the
truth will prevail,'' he said.
   Bentsen did not mention the issue of race, but he received an
enthusiastic welcome from the congregation. The church resonated
from the voices of two choirs and Bentsen joined in for a rousing
rendition of ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic.''
   Bishop L.T. Walker, a visiting preacher who presided over the
rally, told the proverb about how for the want of a nail, a battle
was lost. ``The Duke can ride with Lloyd Bentsen at his side,'' he
concluded.
   In a speech before the Grand Rapids Economic Club, Bentsen said
the Democrats recognized the tough international competition
American business faces today.
   With new products coming to the market, such as high-definition
television, Japanese and European industries are cooperating but
American businesses are operating on their own, he said.
   Complicating that situation, he said, ``I think we're going to
see a continuation of the decline of the Russian empire'' which
must be handled with caution.
   He and Dukakis would offer ``a creative partnership'' between
business and government, ``not an industrial policy,'' Bentsen said.
   Asked by reporters to elaborate on his statement about the
Soviets, Bentsen said, ``We see their economy in a shambles and
people demanding something be done about the standard of living and
that they have a reasonable amount of consumer goods.''
   ``You see them backing off around the world. And you see the
American economic system being adopted more and more in other
countries. You're seeing a serious decline setting in on the
Russian empire,'' he said.
   ``We have to handle that with considerable care,'' he added.
``There is a tendency when one is going into a decline for the
military to strike out. It's important that we keep our defenses
strong during that process.''
   Bentsen received a polite reception from the Michigan luncheon
crowd, in the Republican Western part of the state. Democrats are
trailing in the race for Michigan's 20 electoral votes by some 7 to
9 points in recent polls and it's one of the states in which they
hope to stage a comeback.
   From Grand Rapids, Bentsen flew to Cape Girardeau, Mo., where he
toured a clothing factory. He viewed computer-operated cutting and
plotting machines that aid in the manufacture of men's suit coats
and blazers, and then addressed employees.
   Bentsen did not mention the racism charges in his address, but
referred to the furlough program as one of many ``distortions'' the
Republicans were peddling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
