<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 2309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Politics     10-24 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Politics,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Cabinet Chief Calls Syria an Occupying Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Michel Aoun, who heads the Christian
Cabinet in Lebanon's rival governments, said Monday that Syria's
refusal to recognize him makes it ``an occupation power.''
   Police reported three people killed and four wounded Monday in
sporadic exchanges of mortar and gunfire between Moslem Druse
militiamen and Christian units of the army in the hills overlooking
Beirut.
   The victims were civilians apparently caught in the crossfire in
Aley, near the hilltop town of Souk el-Gharb, seven miles southeast
of Beirut.
   On Saturday, two people were killed and four wounded in a
three-hour clash in the same area.
   Fears have risen that Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war between
Christians and Moslems would flare up as a constitutional crisis
deepened sectarian divisions, threatening to split Lebanon into
ministates.
   ``Syria's failure to recognize the constitutional Cabinet means
it does not recognize Lebanon's Constitution, which further means
that Syria has declared itself as an occupation power,'' Aoun told
reporters.
   Aoun, 52, a Maronite Catholic, was named by former President
Amin Gemayel to head an interim military Cabinet just minutes
before Gemayel's six-year term ended on Sept. 22. Parliament had
failed to elect a new head of state to succeed Gemayel.
   Moslems and leftists allied with Syria have rejected Aoun's
Cabinet and pledged allegiance to acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss,
who heads what was left of the government installed during
Gemayel's term.
   Syria, which has 40,000 troops stationed in 70 percent of
Lebanon's 4,035-square-mile territory, has branded Aoun a
``military usurper of power.''
   ``Syria has no right whatsoever to reject the Cabinet,'' Aoun
said.
   ``As a neighboring country, it has the right to withhold support
and even to be in dispute with the Cabinet. But to withhold
recognition is a different matter of grave seriousness.''
   Iraq, Syria's archrival in the Arab world, called on the Arab
League Monday to ensure that Lebanon's Parliament meets to elect a
new president and end the constitutional crisis.
   Christian deputies have boycotted parliamentary sessions, and no
president from among the Syrian-backed candidates, the main
contenders, could be chosen without a quorum.
   In a statement broadcast by Baghdad Radio, Iraqi Foreign
Minister Tareq Aziz called action by Parliament ``imperative ... in
order to elect a new president for this Arab country.''
   His statement followed a report by the Christian Voice of
Lebanon radio that the United Arab Emirates asked the Arab League
to convene an emergency summit to discuss the Lebanese crisis.
   Under an unwritten covenant dating from Lebanon's independence
from France in 1943, the presidency goes to the Maronites, the
premiership to Sunni and the speakership of Parliament to Shiite
Moslems.
   Iraq has recognized Aoun's Cabinet. It is the only country to
have done so in a move clearly designed to antagonize Damascus.
   It has also armed the Christians' main militia, the Lebanese
Forces, which opposes Syria.
</TEXT>
