<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Astronauts,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Astronauts Honored with A Motorcade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COCOA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five astronauts who flew Discovery
on the first post-Challenger space shuttle flight were honored
Monday by several thousand people who applauded them along a
five-mile motorcade route.
   Cocoa Beach is just south of the Kennedy Space Center and is
home for many of the workers who helped launch Discovery there on
Sept. 29.
   Astronauts Frederick H. Hauck, Richard O. Covey, George D.
Nelson, John M. Lounge and David C. Hilmers flew to Patrick Air
Force Base from their training base in Houston and climbed into
convertible cars for the motorcade.
   Along the route the astronauts were greeted by high school
bands, congratulatory signs, American flags and rounds of applause.
Hundreds of green ribbons, the community's ``green for go'' symbol
for the mission, were visible.
   The motorcade ended at a Cocoa Beach motel, where a $25-a-plate
dinner featured a film with highlights of the four-day journey that
returned Americans to space 32 months after the Challenger disaster.
   In the 1960s, Cocoa Beach regularly held parades for astronauts
who returned from space flights. But the one Monday was the first
one since the Apollo 12 moon landing crew was honored in 1970.
   Workers at the Kennedy Space Center on Monday were joining the
space shuttle Atlantis to its two solid fuel booster rockets and
external fuel tank, preparing it for a launch in late November with
a classified Defense Department satellite.
</TEXT>
