<HEAD>Court Appointed Doctor: Harry Helmsley Has Memory Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court-appointed doctor has concluded that
billionaire real estate magnate Harry B. Helmsley has memory and
reasoning problems that would impair his standing trial on tax
evasion charges, it was disclosed Monday.
   U.S. District Judge John Walker, who revealed the doctor's
findings at a pretrial hearing, said he would determine the
79-year-old Helmsley's fitness to stand trial at another hearing in
December.
   Helmsley and his wife, Leona, 67, were indicted April 15 on
state and federal charges of evading taxes on almost $4 million in
income by passing it off as business expenses.
   Helmsley's lawyers have contended he was unfit to stand trial
because of memory problems and they are seeking to have him severed
from the case. Four of five medical experts who have examined him
have concurred that his memory is impaired, according to court
papers.
   Walker appointed Dr. Martin L. Albert, professor of neurology at
Boston University's School of Medicine, to examine Helmsley.
   Walker revealed Albert's conclusion that Helmsley ``could not
substantially assist in his defense'' because of ``memory
difficulties and difficulties in reasoning and difficulties in
problem solving in new and rapidly shifting settings.''
   Among other things, Albert concluded, Helmsley would ``not be
cognitively fit to respond to a hostile cross examination.''
   At the request of prosecutors, Walker said he would hold a
hearing on Helmsley's fitness to stand trial Dec. 19.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James DeVita said that if Walker found
by ``a preponderance of the evidence'' that Helmsley was unable to
assist his own defense ``the government would not object'' to
removing the aging billionaire from the trial.
   Walker also rescheduled the trial's start from Jan. 16 to Jan.
23.
   Helmsley and his 67-year-old wife are charged with disguising $4
million in renovations to their Greenwich, Conn. mansion as
business expenses and taking bogus tax deductions.
</TEXT>
