<1ST_LINE>a w PM-SafetyBarometers Adv24   10-24 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Safety Barometers, Adv 24,0394</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Mon Oct. 24 and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>No Easy Way to Judge Airline Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Deregulation-Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some consumer advocates have been asking the
government to take its monthly reports comparing airline on-time
performance another step and issue a comparison on how each airline
ranks on safety.
   The idea may sound fine at first blush, but is complicated by
the fact that the Transportation Department and its Federal
Aviation Administration have yet to figure out what indicators give
an accurate reading on safety.
   The FAA earlier this year hired the Flight Safety Foundation, a
private consulting firm, to develop some criteria that might be
used to gauge aviation safety.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor said he wanted a ``kind of Dow
Jones index of safety'' to tell whether the airways actually are
becoming more or less safe.
   The consultants are going beyond raw accident statistics and
rates. They are examining air traffic controller errors,
near-collision reports, runway incidents, among other things.
   But FAA officials suggest even when the index is found it's
unlikely any attempt will be made to use it to rank airlines on the
basis of safety.
   Such a move would likely be vigorously opposed by the airlines.
   ``It doesn't make much sense,'' says Bill Jackman, a spokesman
for the Air Transport Association. He said it would be difficult,
if not impossible, to compare on safety grounds airlines that fly
in vastly different weather and air traffic conditions.
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, earlier this year was asked to examine whether the
government should develop an airline ranking system based on safety.
   While such a ranking might be desirable, the GAO said it could
``not find any performance indicators that are currently usable to
compare objectively the safety levels of individual airlines.''
   It said that there is some agreement among aviation safety
experts that such areas as pilot competence, quality of maintenance
and financial stablility as well as ``management attitude'' toward
compliance with federal regulations could be used in comparing the
airlines' safety record.
   But it said neither the FAA nor its parent Transportation
Department has enough such information available to be of use.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs Mon Oct. 24 and thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
