<DOCNO> AP881024-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv25   10-24 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 25,0699</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday Oct. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rent Control: An Old Argument Coming Up Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Upward pressure on rents is likely to occur in
the near future, and if that is so you may expect a rise in demands
for rent controls.
   One without the other has been rare in recent years, and nothing
seems likely to change that relationship. Some people will always
be for rent control and others will oppose it; seldom can they
speak civilly to each other.
   The usual fireworks may be expected, therefore, as pressure
builds on the rental market, a consequence of reduced tax benefits
for owners and builders and a proliferation of local restrictions
on new construction.
   Recognizing the emerging situation, the non-profit,
independent-minded Urban Land Institute commissioned an
``evaluation'' by Anthony Downs, a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution. He comes down hard against controls.
   Downs contends in his recently released volume that controls
inhibit new rental construction, cause existing units to
deteriorate faster, and actually impose disadvantages on those who
are thought to benefit.
   It is a conventional finding and it is likely to be treated
conventionally by those opposed philosophically or morally to
free-market rents.
   Its impact is likely to be diminished even further be its
sponsorhip, which includes the National Multi Housing Council, the
Building Owners and Managers Association International and the
National Association of Realtors.
   Nevertheless, it has much to say about the subject that is
worthwhile, especially in view of the likelihood that reductions in
rental construction, plus a tendency toward rent inflation, will
resurrect the debate.
   Though the subject lies dormant now, there are more than 200
communities with some form of residential rent controls, most
adopted during periods of rapid general inflation in the 1970s, and
most in the Northeast and California.
   Do they work? For some and for a limited time, it seems. But
Downs contends that in the long run they impose two major
disadvantages upon those who are supposed to be the major
beneficiaries _ low-income households.
   First, he says, controls increase rather than decrease the
discretionary power of owners by intensifying tenant competition
for vacant units.
   Says Downs: Owners then tend to choose higher-income tenants
over poor ones since the former pose less risk. Owners also
discriminate against tenants on the basis of race, ethnicity, age
and number of children.
   Then, he contends, controls may increase homelessness by
reducing the available supply of rental housing, and thus the
access of the poor to that supply.
   These contentions are likely to play a big role in the arguments
to come because already there is a serious shortage of low-income
housing.
   According to Downs, in 1983 the number of renter households for
whom $250 or less represented 30 percent of income was 12 million.
At the same time, the number of units priced at $250 or less per
month was 8.75 million.
   Harsh as that reality was, it has grown worse since then, says
Downs, and that brings up the question of how to handle the
problem. By imposing rent controls to temporarily assist while
worsening the long-term problem? Or, by allowing free-market rents,
which eventually bring more units on market?
   Philosophically, there is probably no meeting ground for those
at the extremes of this argument, no more than there is a common
interest regarding another aspect of the subject, i.e., the fate of
landlords.
   Rent controls obviously impose economic losses upon the owners
of rental housing units _ penalties that no other participants in
the economic community are expected to accept.
   Owners of controlled units, for instance, may be forced to take
operating expenses from their own pockets, in effect denying their
own families. The market value of the property declines. Their
investment can even be wiped out.
   Landlords legitimately ask, therefore, if attempts at fair play
for one member of society should arbitarily be at the expense of
another, rather than of the total community?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues Oct. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881024-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Bertinelli ADV25   10-24 0808</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Bertinelli, ADV 25,0825</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, Oct. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Valerie Bertinelli Plays Aviator Pancho Barnes</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Valerie Bertinelli had to learn more
than just her lines to portray aviation pioneer Pancho Barnes.
   Barnes was at home not only in the cockpit of an open stunt
plane but also in the saddle atop galloping horses.
   ``I'd ridden horses a long time ago, but I was always scared and
never knew how to ride well,'' said Bertinelli. And she had never
been up in a small plane.
   Prior to beginning her role in the three-hour movie ``Pancho
Barnes,'' on CBS tonight, Bertinelli went to the Texas location
site a week early. She wanted to practice horseback riding and to
become acquainted with open-cockpit planes.
   ``I spent a lot of time with the wranglers,'' she said. ``I
really enjoy riding now. I was afraid of the horse at first, but I
spent every weekend during the shoot riding. The last week I was
able to able to do my own stunt of riding the horse in a race next
to the camera car.''
   She also took her first ride in a small plane. ``I couldn't wait
to get up,'' she said. ``When I got to the airfield the pilot was
doing loops and stalls. It looked like fun. When he landed I had
him take me up right away. It was such an experience. I was so
exhilarated.''
   The movie also stars Sam Robards, Ted Wass, James Stephens,
Geoffrey Lewis, Cynthia Harris and Richard Young. It was filmed on
location near Dallas.
   The beautiful Bertinelli was an odd choice to play Barnes, whom
test pilot Chuck Yeager described in his autobiography as ``one of
the ugliest women'' he had ever met.
   Pancho Barnes is probably best known today as the woman who ran
the watering hole with the wall of photos of dead test pilots in
the movie ``The Right Stuff.'' Kim Stanley played her in that 1983
movie. But Barnes was also an early pilot who competed in women's
cross-country air races with Amelia Earhart and Beryl Markham. She
organized the Stunt Pilots Association, which performs movie
stunts. She trained pilots in World War II, and her ranch later
became part of Edwards Air Force Base.
   The movie starts with her introduction to flight in her
grandfather's hot-air balloon. He was Professor Thaddeus S.C. Lowe,
who was appointed by Abraham Lincoln to head the Union Army's
balloon corps in the Civil War. She shunned more traditional
feminine pastimes for horseback riding and flying.
   ``She was a woman before her time, '' said Bertinelli. ``She led
her own life. She was one of the guys. She was respected in her
circle.''
   The movie romanticizes Barnes. It mentions only two marriages,
although Barnes had four husbands. She married her fourth husband,
Gene ``Mac'' McKendry (Sam Robards), after World War II, when he
was 26 and she was in her mid-40s. In the film, however, they meet
and marry in the 1920s. They were divorced in 1968. She died in
1975.
   Bertinelli, who starred as the kid sister in ``One Day at a
Time,'' was last seen in the miniseries ``I'll Take Manhattan.''
   ``I've just been taking it easy and keeping my eyes open,'' she
said. ``I don't want to rush into anything. I'm going on the road
with my husband (rock musician Eddie Van Halen) until Thanksgiving
and Christmas. I don't think I'll do anything new until next year.''
   Bertinelli has a series commitment from CBS, but has not yet
decided on the concept of the new show. ``A script's being
written,'' she said, ``but you never know how it's going to turn
out. I want to be very sure before I commit to it.''
   Several movies and miniseries are being written for her
production company.
   ``The parts get better as you get older,'' said Bertinelli. ``I
enjoy being 28. I don't look 28, but I don't look 19 either. I'm
not going to play teen-agers anymore. They're not as interesting.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   CABLE AWARDS _ The 10th Annual ACE Awards for cable television
will be presented Sunday, Jan. 15, from the Wiltern Theatre in Los
Angeles. John Moffitt and Pat Tourk Lee will produce the awards
show, which will be carried by the 10 basic cable networks. ...
   NEW COMPANY _ Richard and Esther Shapiro, who created ABC's
``Dynasty,'' have formed a production company, and their first
project is a six-hour miniseries for NBC, tentatively called ``When
We Were Young.'' The Shapiros also created ``The Colbys'' and
``Emerald Point N.A.S.'' and they wrote such TV movies as
``Intimate Strangers'' and ``Minstrel Man.'' Richard Shapiro wrote
the screenplay for ``John Steinbeck's East of Eden.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, Oct. 25</NOTE>
