<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV06   10-24 1035</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 06,1064</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kate Nelligan has made a career on Broadway of
playing strong, independent women.
   In ``Plenty,'' she was the disillusioned wife of a British
diplomat witnessing England's decline after World War II. In Eugene
O'Neill's ``A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' she was a hearty and
plain-spoken Irish farm girl, bewitching the playwright's
whiskey-soaked alter ego. In ``Serious Money,'' she was a voracious
American arbitrageur, wheeling and dealing on the world's financial
markets.
   Now she has returned to New York in what could be her best stage
role yet _ the vibrant, volatile, red-haired heroine of Michael
Weller's 1950s family drama, ``Spoils of War.''
   She portrays Elise, a left-wing, much-married, extravagant woman
whose one true passion is her teen-age son Martin. The play,
described by Weller as ``semi-autobiographical,'' centers on
Martin's attempt to bring his mother and his long-absent father
back together. Nelligan's co-stars include Jeffrey DeMunn as the
husband and Christopher Collet as her adored son.
   For the actress, ``Spoils of War'' represents nearly a year-long
journey to Broadway. Nelligan has lived with the character and the
play since last January when the director, Austin Pendleton,
suggested her for the role of Elise.
   ``The play was presented to me then as an unfinished piece of
work,'' says the Canadian-born actress. ``The first act was pretty
much in shape and the second act wasn't. There was a beginning and
an end. But I didn't say `What are you going to do with it?' I
said, `I want to do it.'''
   About two weeks before rehearsals started, Nelligan sat down for
a three-hour meeting with Weller to talk, not about the play, but
about the woman in it. They discussed who she was, as well as
things the playwright knew about Elise from his own life.
   It was the first time in her 16 years as a professional actress
that Nelligan was there during the creation.
   ``I've worked on new plays with writers, but I've never worked
on a play that came such a long way,'' the actress says. ``Michael
was finding the play as we went along.
   ``The character of Elise started out as an Auntie Mame. She was
just a real good-time girl. In the first performance, she appeared
as a ghost to a character who is no longer even in the play, the
adult Martin who is on the point of divorcing his wife.''
   Weller rewrote the play several times before the drama opened in
May at the tiny off-Broadway Second Stage. The theater company was
devoting its entire season to the playwright and ``Spoils of War''
was the finale in a year that also saw productions of Weller's
``Moonchildren'' and ``Loose Ends.''
   The rewriting continued during the play's Second Stage
engagement, often with the actors rehearsing one version during the
day and performing a different one at night.
   ``It was an awful period,'' Nelligan admits, particularly until
the actors discovered the people they were playing. All they could
do was trust the playwright, she recalls.
   ``I thought Michael was moving toward something but it was just
very painful to be performing something when I didn't know what I
was doing a lot of time,'' Nelligan says. ``I've always been sure
of my lines, and now I wasn't sure what would come out of my mouth
because the lines were always being changed.''
   There were other changes after the off-Broadway run ended, and
the company prepared for its November opening at New York's Music
Box Theater.
   There was a break from the end of June until the middle of
August while Weller worked on a new ending.
   ``There are a couple of new actors, a new set and more
rewrites,'' Nelligan says.
   One thing Nelligan didn't discuss with Weller was what he was
going to do with the play.
   ``I'd never ask him that,'' the actress says. ``I think that's
the way he likes to work. It's his play. It isn't mine.''
   Nelligan insists the role was not tailor-made for her.
   ``Michael was writing from memory,'' she says. ``But it's been
useful to see all the places he has gone to with the play because
that informs what you end up with. Even all the rejected
possibilities that he explored. They might be taken out but they
are in your memory to use for what's left.''
   It was Nelligan's idea to let her character sport long red hair
and she willingly donned a wig to make Elise more flamboyant and
fun.
   ``The character has got quite a range _ bigger than anybody I
ever played,'' Nelligan says. ``She can have a lot of fun and gives
people a lot of fun. And then she's also in a lot of pain and a lot
of trouble. She's a human, flesh-and-blood creature.''
   Although born in Canada, Nelligan didn't make her professional
Canadian debut until ``Spoils of War'' opened in Toronto in
September before coming to New York.
   Most of her career has been centered in England and the United
States. Despite her schooling at London's Central School of Speech
and Drama, her best training, she says, has been has been watching
other performers, particularly at the National Theater and the
Royal Shakespeare Company.
   ``The greatest teacher I ever had was an actor named Colin
Blakeley who died last year,'' Nelligan says. ``I did George
Bernard Shaw's `Heartbreak House' with him when I was 24 years old
and I learned a lot.''
   Nothing she had done prepared her for the intense, exhilarating
work of ``Spoils of War,'' particularly in its early days.
   ``The process had been so overheated what with all the rewrites,
the short, short rehearsal time and that tiny theater at Second
Stage and no money,'' Nelligan says. ``Getting it on stage and
having it survive all those things was hard.
   ``I was so tired,'' she remembers. ``Then after a few weeks, it
got to be something I could do and go away from.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881024-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReviews ADV00   10-24 1001</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Reviews, ADV 00,1036</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Bird'' and ``Mystic Pizza''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Bird''
   
   How well can one ever know a genius? Can we ever really open the
many doors to their lives and capture their scattered energies?
   Clint Eastwood attempts to harness the creative genius and
tortured man who was Charlie Parker in his movie, ``Bird,'' a
bittersweet portrait of the great jazzman who died at the age of 34
in 1955.
   His journey begins on the dusty dirt roads outside Kansas City,
when Parker was a horn-blowing child, and moves with the tempo of
be-bop to the hot clubs of New York, where a young trumpet player
named Dizzy Gillespie was all the rage.
   With Thelonious Monk and Bud Powell on piano, Kenny Clarke on
drums and later a young Miles Davis on trumpet, Parker and
Gillespie helped define and create a new musical venture in jazz _
bebop.
   ``Bird'' _ Parker's nickname was Yardbird and shortened to the
Bird _ harvests all the creative juices of that age, the
spontaneity, the excitement. At the same time, it pokes into the
underbelly of the jazz world _ drugs, alcohol, debauchery.
   And Parker was no stranger to that lost world.
   Forest Whitaker (``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' ``Platoon'') is
gentle yet fierce, playful yet obsessed in his role as Parker, for
which he was awarded the best actor prize at the Cannes Film
Festival. It was well deserved for a stunning performance that even
captures the hunched body stances assumed by the musician as he
performed.
   As Chan Parker, Diane Venora (``Ironweed,'' ``F-X'') finds the
right balance between free spirit and strong, loving wife who
battles her husband's philandering and personal demons and at the
same time champions his work and well-being.
   Their relationship and music are the only constants in Parker's
existence. We see him slip deeper into despair as drugs and alcohol
destroy him. Eventually, the death of his daughter pushes him into
the abyss. His grief and perhaps a glimmer of the Parker enigma are
shown when he tries to contact Chan after learning on the road
about the tragedy.
   He sends an endless stream of telegrams to Chan _ the first
signed ``your husband, Charlie Parker.'' This formality, in a way,
mirrors his inability to completely surrender himself in an
intimate relationship.
   Still, we never really know Charlie Parker.
   Eastwood is spare in his direction, allowing his actors to reach
deeper into themselves. He has filmed the Malpaso Production for
Warner Bros. in muted tones and shadows. Clearly, he intended the
somber moods of black and white and probably should have shot
``Bird'' in that pristine way because the movie suffers from being
too dark, sometimes obscuring what's on the screen.
   Lenny Niehaus did the score, which isolates Parker's original
playing of ``Laura,'' ``April in Paris,'' ``Ornithology,''
``Parker's Mood'' and other jazz tunes and remixes his recorded
solos with contemporary musicians including bassist Ron Carter,
trumpeter John Faddis, pianists Walter Davis Jr. and Barry Harris.
   Jazz purists won't like the scoring; others will find the
soundtrack outstanding.
   Rated R for language, drug use.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Mystic Pizza''
   
   What kind of a movie is ``Mystic Pizza''? A far-out rock
musical? A horror story about a man-killing pizza? It is neither.
Rather, it concerns the romantic misadventures of three waitresses
in a pizza parlor in the town of Mystic, Conn.
   Don't be put off by the ambiguous-sounding title and the lack of
star names. ``Mystic Pizza'' is a marvelously warm and funny
comedy-drama that is frankly sentimental but never cloying. It is
far more satisfying than the big-budget offerings with box-office
names.
   The film begins with a nervous bride, Jojo (Lili Taylor),
walking down the church aisle amid the approving glances of family
and friends. Midway through the ceremony, she passes out cold. End
of wedding.
   Jojo's problem is that she adores the body of fisherman Bill
(Vincent O'Donofrio) but she resists commitment. Her friend, Kat
(Annabeth Gish), might be willing to commit but boys are put off by
her intellect _ she's going to study astronomy on a Yale University
scholarship. Boys are no problem for her beautiful sister Daisy
(Julia Roberts). She has Ado Annie's problem: the inability to say
no.
   Daisy becomes enmeshed with a spoiled rich kid (Adam Storke),
and her sister falls for a married architect (William R. Moses)
with Robert Redford looks and a daughter who needs babysitting.
Most of the film concerns the unraveling of the three romances, but
there are colorful scenes in the pizza joint presided over by the
mountainous Conchata Ferrell.
   What makes ``Mystic Pizza'' so enjoyable is the wittily
vernacular script by Amy Jones, Randy and Perry Howze and Alfred
Uhry. It is one of the few occasions when multiple authors appear
to have enhanced a screenplay.
   The direction by Donald Petrie is right on the mark _ crisp,
funny, intensely human.
   The performances are a delightful surprise. Roberts is a
gorgeous brunette with fire in her eyes. Taylor has a sharp comedic
style, and Gish evokes the most sympathy of the trio. Moses
(``Falcon Crest'') is silkily seductive as the architect, and
Storke and D'Onofrio are excellent.
   The seaside town of Mystic also plays a major role, and it is
beautifully photographed by Tim Suhrstedt.
   ``Mystic Pizza'' is rated R for language and sex scenes. A
Samuel Goldwyn Jr. release. Running time 104 minutes.
   _ By Bob Thomas, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or ault
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
