<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--MedicineSunday ADV4-6   10-24 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Medicine Sunday, ADV 4-6,0845</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 4-6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Simplicity With a Beat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medicine Sunday believes in simplicity: with a
beat.
   No horns. No synthesizers. No voice lessons for their lead
singer.
   Medicine Sunday wants nothing to get in the way of their music _
or their audience. Ask anyone who has seen them play.
   ``Some people will sit there and listen and really understand,
and there are people who get into the energy of the band and they
start dancing and jumping around,'' bassist Matt Barton said. ``If
the crowd's jumping around, we start jumping around. I'll jump off
the stage.
   ``It feeds off each other.''
   ``I don't feel seperated from the audience on stage,'' added
vocalist Frank Pupo. ``Anything that happens, happens.''
   Along with Barton and Pupo, are guitarist Oliver Wolf and
drummer Steve Reisman. Pupo and Wolf formed the band two years ago.
   ``We kind of clicked and started rehearsing,'' Pupo said.
``Things started going good and we decided to get a bass player.''
   The bass player, Barton, came from a diverse musical background.
   ``I played in pop rock bands and jazz bands,'' Barton said. ``I
used to play gospel music in high school.''
   Medicine Sunday's sound has been compared to U2 and Joy
Division. Pupo, whose singing recalls Jim Morrison and the late Ian
Curtis of Joy Division, says the band tries to keep its sound as
simple as possible.
   ``When you have over-production, you lose a lot. You're
committed to sounding just like the record, otherwise people are
disappointed,'' Pupo said. ``All the bands I've ever liked have the
same basic formula.
   Pupo began performing live when he was 18.
   ``People put their fingers in their ears. I was kicked out of a
couple of bands.'' But Pupo kept singing and eventually caught on.
   ``I found someone who liked the way I sang,'' said Pupo, adding
that he learned how important breathing correctly was for a
vocalist. ``I sing from my throat a lot. I like the sound I get.''
   Pupo has been writing poems from an early age and is the group's
main lyricist.
   ``I started out in California. They had different ideas about
how things should be done. The lyrics they wanted are a lot more
literal: `I'm in love with a girl.' I don't write like that.
   Pupo says he tries to let the audience derive its own meanings
from his songs.
   ``I try not to force meanings on people. When you read a book,
you get an interpretation of a character. It's stream of
consciousness.''
   Simplicity, again, is an important part of Pupo's writing. ``I
try to get as much meaning to as many words as I can, like Japanese
haikus.''
   Medicine Sunday has signed with URG records and the first album
is expected to be released this fall. The band's most popular song
in concert has been ``Conviction,'' inspired by one of Pupo's poems.
   It's got that light tone. We try to communicate with the music
and the words,'' Pupo said. ``You're riding along and you go up a
little bit and you go down a little bit.''
   ``Conviction'' was structured around Barton's bass line.
   ``I put the bass line together when I was falling asleep in
bed,'' he said. ``I tried to calm myself down and started playing
these chords. It's a very hypnotic song, kind of like a battle
hymn.''
   Medicine Sunday produced its own album with the emphasis, not
surprisingly, on simplicity.
   ``What kills underground bands is they get in, they make a great
album, and they get over-produced,'' Pupo said. ``If everything is
over-produced, you can't feel the emotion of the music.''
   The band's songs, such as ``Dirty Little World'' and ``Big
Machine,'' are hard-edged. ``No Good Days'' lives up to the
bleakness of its title.
   ``You just have a lousy week and you wake up and it's going to
happen all over again. You see no light at the end of the tunnel,''
Pupo said.
   Medicine Sunday may share the harsh view of the world as
envisioned by punks, but they have no use for the ``hope I die
before I get old'' mentality of so many groups.
   ``We're not concerned about being young forever,'' Pupo said.
``I don't even think we'll put pictures on the album.''
   The band's goals, like their sound, are simple. Medicine Sunday
is not looking to make a million dollars, it just wants to remain a
part of the fans' lives.
   ``When I read a book and it really affects me, the guy has done
his job,'' Pupo said. ``Kafka did what he set out to do. I don't
necessarily have to meet him to be affected by him.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov 4-6</NOTE>
</DOC>
