<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary ADV27   10-24 0962</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, ADV 27,0993</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, Oct. 27, and thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for Oct. 27 in summary form.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Woman Working in Basement Lab Developing Acid-Eating Microbe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former high school science teacher is
growing microbes that could revolutionize mining by neutralizing
the acid drainage that costs companies and the government millions
for cleanup.
   Jo Davison has convinced Peabody Coal Co., the nation's largest
producer, to let her ``bugs'' eat the poisonous runoff from a West
Virginia mine.
   Acid drainage oozes its telltale red water anywhere mine
operators cut into earth and stone containing pyrites. The global
problem plagues miners of not only coal, but also of gold, silver
and other natural resources. It starts with the breaking of the
soil and lasts long after the mine has been shut down.
   ``Anywhere there are pyrites, there is acidic drainage,'' said
West Virginia University researcher Jeff Skousen. Pyrites are metal
sulfides that in the presence of air and water produce sulfuric
acid.
   Anywhere there is acid drainage, miners face expensive chemical
treatments to remove heavy metals and neutralize the water. Coal
industry officials have pegged water treatment costs at $1 million
a day in the United States.
   Davison's work parallels wetlands research at West Virginia
University. When a dam holding runoff broke and flooded a pristine
bog in German Valley, researcher Joe Lange discovered that water
leaving the bog was clear.
   Mine reclamation researchers urged building wetlands with
acid-tolerant cattails and sphagnum mosses to somehow trap and
negate the heavy metals that leach from mines. Scientists don't
understand fully how wetlands work, but they do work, and the
industry slowly is adopting the process.
   The plants themselves absorb only a minute amount of the heavy
metals. Indications are that most of the action is at the
microscopic level.
   Davison has bred microbes that attack specific metals. One
oxidizes iron, others do the same to aluminum, sulfur or manganese.
They chelate, or bond with, the metals so they can oxidize and drop
out of the water.
   Patents are pending on the microbes, their mixes, and the
growing mediums that allow the organisms to live in acid water in
the first place.
   The industry itself has been slow to take the bait. State Energy
Department spokesman Roger Hall said Davison's results have been
amazing in the laboratory, but less impressive in the field.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>What Makes A Good Group? Not Just Smart People</HEAD>
