<HEAD>Lung Association Expands Flu Shot Recommendation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time, the American Lung
Association is urging a yearly flu shot for anybody who lives with
elderly people or others at high risk for influenza.
   Previously, the association recommended the vaccine only for
people who themselves were at high risk.
   ``We must draw a ring of immunity around our senior citizens and
others who are most vulnerable, because 80 percent of them are not
getting vaccinated each year,'' Frederick Ruben of the lung
association's medical section, the American Thoracic Society, said
in a statement.
   Flu and pneumonia kill about 68,000 people a year in the United
States, more than any other infectious disease, the lung
association says.
   People at high risk for potentially fatal complications of
influenza include those 65 or older, residents of nursing homes or
other long-term care facilities, and adults and children older than
six months who have chronic heart or lung disease, diabetes, kidney
ailments, anemia, infection with the AIDS virus or suppressed
immune systems, the lung association said.
   The category also includes children older than six months and
teen-agers up to 18 years who are receiving long-term aspirin
therapy, because of the risk of developing a potentially fatal
disorder called Reye's syndrome after flu infection, the
association said.
   Flu shots are also recommended for home care providers, such as
visiting nurses or volunteer workers, who are in daily contact with
high-risk people, the association said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Vigorous Running Can Produce Internal Bleeding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One in five marathon runners in a recent study
showed evidence of internal bleeding after completing a race, and
runners who cover shorter distances might also be susceptible to
bleeding, say two doctors from the Walter Reed Army Medical Center
in Washington, D.C.
   Such bleeding, detected by testing for blood in urine and stool
samples before and after runners competed, can lead to anemia and
can also hide more serious problems, such as stomach and colon
cancer, the doctors said.
   Speaking at a meeting in New York of the American College of
Gastroenterology, the doctors advised any runners who detect signs
of bleeding, such as black stools or urine, to seek medical help.
   Older runners, who face a greater risk of colon or stomach
cancer, should be tested to see whether the bleeding is the result
of running or is an early warning sign of cancer, the doctors said.
   ``Runners seem to accept this as a matter of course,'' said Dr.
David Peura, chief of gastroenterology at Walter Reed. ``They don't
seem to be too concerned about these things.'' That is a mistake,
he said.
   Peura said that up to 80 percent of ultramarathoners, those who
run 100-mile races, begin to discharge blood in stool or urine
following their races.
   Puera and Dr. Frank Moses, also a gastroenterologist, said they
took blood samples from 120 runners before and after a recent
Marine Corps marathon. None were bleeding in the digestive tract
before the race, but about 20 percent had blood in their stools
after the race, Puera said.
   Moses has also studied the abdominal cramping and diarrhea that
many runners complain of and found that running causes the passage
of food to slow through the small intestine, but that it might
increase its speed through the colon, leading to diarrhea. That
remains to be studied, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Metallic `Seeds' Implanted in Brain Aid Brain Tumor Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The implantation of heat-conducting metallic
``seeds'' into brain tumors should enable doctors to warm the
tumors, sensitizing them to anti-cancer drugs and radiation
treatments, a researcher says.
   Surgery is usually unable to remove brain tumors completely, and
the brain can tolerate only a certain level of anti-cancer drugs
and radiation. By heating the tumor, doctors hope they can increase
the likelihood that drugs and radiation will wipe it out, said Dr.
Sean Grady of the University of Washington School of Medicine in
Seattle.
   Grady said that initial animal tests had shown that tiny seeds
of a neodynium-iron-boron alloy could be inserted under the skull
and maneuvered with external magnets into brain tumors.
   Preliminary studies, reported in Chicago at the annual meeting
of the American College of Surgeons this week, showed that ``the
seeds would not damage normal brain tissue'' as they were
maneuvered into position, Grady said.
   ``Tumors occur in many different shapes, so it was important to
find out if the seeds could be moved easily in different
directions,'' Grady said. ``The studies suggest that you could move
the seeds into and back out of each limb or extension of the
tumor,'' he said.
   The next experiments are intended to determine whether the seeds
can be heated to desired temperatures, he said.
   He said he doubted that the new method would replace
chemotherapy or radiation, but ``we might find that the seeds will
become another modality for the treatment of malignant brain
tumors.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
