<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-NissanExpansion     10-24 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nissan Expansion,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nissan Announces Expansion of Tenn. Plant, New Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. U.S.A. today
announced it would assemble a new passenger car in an expansion of
the Japanese automaker's assembly plant in Smyrna, Tenn.
   But in a news release received in Detroit, the Japan-based
company did not say how much the expansion would cost or provide
other details.
   Nissan now makes the Sentra car and light truck at the plant
southeast of Nashville.
   Nissan Motor President and Chief Executive Officer Jerry
Benefield said a task force of company officials from Tennessee and
Japan will begin a study soon about the plant expansion, the new
car and how many new employees will be needed.
   ``We have been asking for the opportunity to expand our capacity
for some time,'' Benefield said. ``We are very happy and proud that
our board of directors and parent company have given all of us at
Nissan in Tennessee this vote of confidence.''
   The company's board of directors approved the expansion Oct. 15,
but decided to withhold the announcement until today, spokesman
David Fox said.
   The Smyrna plant, with a 3,200-employee work force, was designed
in 1980 with room for expansion. The company said as early as last
February it was looking into expanding the factory.
   Today's announcement is the latest in a series of moves Nissan
has made in the United States this year.
   In April, Nissan approved spending $31.1 million to begin
producing bumpers and assembling engines and truck axles at the
Tennessee plant.
   In September, Nissan and Ford Motor Co. announced a joint
venture to produce minivans at Ford's Avon Lake, Ohio, truck plant.
   Last week, Nissan Research and Development Inc. broke ground for
a $50 million research and design facility in Farmington Hills,
Mich., northwest of Detroit. Officials said among its projects
would be designing a new vehicle for the U.S. market.
</TEXT>
