<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pepperell-Farley 1stLd-Writethru   10-24 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepperell-Farley, 1st Ld-Writethru,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farley Offers $1.3 Billion for Pepperell</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Updates throughout with Pepperell comment, details, no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc., parent of the Fruit of the Loom
underwear company, today launched a tender offer for West
Point-Pepperell Inc. that values the textile giant at about $1.4
billion.
   Farley, one of the nation's largest privately owned
conglomerates, is offering $48 a share in cash for each of
Pepperell's 29.4 million outstanding shares.
   In early trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Pepperell
jumped $4.25 a share to $49.50.
   William Farley, who heads the Chicago-based concern, said in a
letter to Pepperell Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Joseph L.
Lanier Jr. that he hoped to ``move forward on a constructive,
friendly basis.''
   The offer was not entirely unexpected. In May, Farley sought
government permission to acquire up to 25 percent of Pepperell's
stock. So far, he has spent $88 million for a 9.8 percent stake in
the West Point, Ga.-based company.
   Pepperell spokesman Donald Downs said the company would have no
comment until it had studied the offer. Farley said had telephoned
him months ago ``and indicated he preferred to remain independent.''
   Farley said his company already has taken legal action to
challenge Georgia's anti-takeover statutes as well as Pepperell's
poison pill. Last June Pepperell strengthened its poison pill,
designed to make unwanted takeovers prohibitively expensive.
   The lawsuits would be dropped, however, if Pepperell agrees to
work with Farley on a friendly basis, Farley said in a statement.
   Pepperell, which manufacturs brand name products includiung
Arrow shirts and Martex towels, acquired textile rival J.P. Stevens
& Co. earlier this year for $1.2 billion and then split up Stevens'
assets with a rival suitor. Pepperell was left with most of
Stevens' linen and towel operations, giving the company about 25
percent of the nation's home fashion textile market.
   Farley has a $300 million war chest for acquisitions,
accumulated from a bond issue earlier this year, but has indicated
he wants to keep two-thirds of it in reserve for other investments.
   He said he would finance the Pepperell takeover with a
combination of bank financing and high-yield ``junk bonds'' offered
through the Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. investment banking firm.
   If the bid is successful, Farley said he would try to refinance
about $1.1 billion of Pepperell debt, much of it due to the Stevens
acquisition.
   The company's textile looms are not compatible with Fruit of the
Loom's products, so the takeover would not help the underwear
company's battle to meet demand.
   In addition to Fruit of the Loom, the nation's largest underwear
company, Farley also operates Acme Boot and Doehler-Jarvis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
