<DOCNO> AP881024-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PennCentral-RepublicAmerican     10-24 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Penn Central-Republic American,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Penn Central, Republic American Merging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penn Central Corp. said Monday it had signed a
definitive agreement to acquire Republic American Corp. in a $249
million merger.
   The companies said in a joint statement they expect to complete
the deal in early 1989, assuming that they receive required
approvals from regulators and the holders of two-thirds of Republic
American's outstanding common stock.
   Republic American, which sells workers' compensation insurance
in California, has about 18.4 million common shares outstanding.
   Penn Central already owns 14.3 percent of those common shares
and has committed to pay $15.75 per share in cash for the rest, or
about $249 million.
   Pen Central, which has its headquarters here, is a
telecommunications and defense systems company. It plans to merge
Republic American with a newly formed Penn Central subsidiary.
   American Financial Corp., a Cincinnati holding company
controlled by financier Carl Lindner Jr., owns 31 percent of Penn
Central's common shares and 38.6 percent of Republic American's
common shares. American Financial, whose interests include banking
and insurance holdings, has agreed to vote all its stock of
Republic American for the merger.
   The agreement revises Penn Central's earlier proposal to acquire
Republic American, announced in July. That move provoked objections
in court by Republic American stockholders. Under the original
proposal, Penn Central said it would give Republic American
stockholders 0.65 of a Penn Central common share for each
outstanding Republic American common share. The market price of
Penn Central's common stock was then about $22.50 per share.
   The two companies announced Oct. 13 that the Republic American
stockholders who sued to challenge the original proposal have
agreed, subject to confirmation and court approval, to settle their
suits in light of the new proposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
