<DOCNO> AP881024-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Phone     10-24 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Phone,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GTE Reports 5 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   GTE Corp.'s third-quarter profit rose 5 percent despite a $55
million pre-tax charge to cover the cost of reorganization and
streamlining, the Stamford, Conn.-based phone company said Monday.
   For the first time since mid-1986, GTE's operating results did
not include losses from US Sprint Communications Co., which it owns
equally with United Telecommunications Inc.
   Since GTE has agreed to sell a majority of its interest in US
Sprint to United Telecommunications at the start of 1989, it
accounted for the company's results differently in the third
quarter and was able to absorb the loss with money in a previously
established reserve, spokesman Harvey Greisman said.
   US Sprint's pre-tax loss in the quarter was $19 million, down
sharply from $165 million in the third quarter of 1987. US Sprint,
created in July 1986 from two predecessors, is the third biggest
long-distance company after American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and
MCI Communications Corp.
   GTE said it earned $313 million, or 91 cents a share, up from
$297 million, or 86 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 5
percent to $4 billion from $3.8 billion.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, GTE said its
profit rose 15 percent to $898 million, or $2.62 a share, from $785
million, or $2.30 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 7 percent
to $12.2 billion from $11.3 billion.
   The nine-month period of 1987 included an after-tax charge of
$39 million for a writedown at US Sprint, net of gains from certain
other actions.
   The $55 million charge will cover the previously announced
consolidation of GTE's seven telephone operating companies into one
centralized general office that will oversee four regional
headquarters in Florida, Indiana, California and Texas.
</TEXT>
