<HEAD>Pacific Gas and Electric, Enron Sign Agreement for Natural Gas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enron Gas Marketing Inc. has signed an agreement
to supply Pacific Gas and Electric Co. with up to 100 million cubic
feet of natural gas per day for 10 years, the companies announced
Monday.
   The estimated value of the transaction, based on current prices
and anticipated volumes, is in excess of $500 million. The gas
prices to be paid under the agreement will be periodically
renegotiated to reflect the market value of long-term natural gas
supplies, officials said.
   San Francisco-based PG&E will transport the gas to its
California system through El Paso Natural Gas Co.'s pipelines.
   ``This long-term purchase is an important addition to PG&E's
core portfolio supply,'' said John A. Sproul, PG&E's executive vice
president and general manager of its gas supply business unit.
Long-term case portfolio supply sources with take flexibility and
competitive prices are preferred by PG&E and are purchasd prior to
more costly or less reliable supplies, he said.
   John J. Esslinger, president of Enron Gas Marketing, a
subsidiary of Houston-based Enron Corp., said the agreement
represents a first ``long-term, firm sales agreement with a West
Coast customer. We are confident of our ability to serve PG&E
reliably at competitive prices, and we appreciate the confidence it
has placed in Enron.''
   PG&E is the largest investor-owned gas and electic utility in
the United States, serving more than 3.2 million gas and 4 million
electric customers in a 94,000-square-mile area of northern
California.
   Enron Gas Marketing is a non-jurisdictional supplier of natural
gas to numerous direct-use and resale customers throughout the
country.
</TEXT>
