<1ST_LINE>a f BC-HalloweenBusiness Adv29-30   10-24 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Halloween Business, Adv 29-30,0764</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 29-30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Halloween, Like Everything Else, Has Become a Yuppie Treat</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANNE HENK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If those trick-or-treaters who show up
at your door look you in the eye instead of the kneecap this year,
don't be surprised.
   The masquerading and tomfoolery of Halloween isn't just for kids
anymore.
   Like so many of life's finer things, the holiday has been
yuppified _ and has therefore become a big business.
   ``It's no longer a children's holiday. The majority of dollars
are spent on adults,'' said Jack Sheehan, owner of the Costumer in
upstate New York.
   According to Hallmark Cards Inc., an estimated $300 million will
be spent in the United States just on costumes for All Hallows' Eve
1988 _ which pretty much means the days of drumming up a Halloween
costume in a last-minute dash to the attic or basement are over.
   ``We've discovered that the single most important factor for an
adult in determining whether he or she has a good time at Halloween
is whether they find the right costume,'' said Michael DeMent, a
spokesman for Hallmark in Kansas City, Mo.
   Sheehan, who also rents costumes for theatrical productions,
does about 40 percent of his business for the annual holiday, which
traces its origins to the Druids in 700 B.C.
   Fifty million American adults are expected to attend Halloween
parties this year, an increase of 25 percent over the last three
years, and 28 million Halloween cards will be given in 1988,
Hallmark says.
   ``It's the second-largest adult party-giving occasion in the
United States,'' said DeMent. New Year's Eve is the top adult
partying occasion.
   There are several theories on the increased interest in
Halloween.
   ``One is that people are so busy with work and family and
community activities that it's almost like we have to give
ourselves permission to have fun. Halloween's kind of made for
that,'' DeMent said.
   ``I would say in general there has been a big increase in the
last several years in the value people place on fun and enjoyment
in life,'' said Lynn R. Kahle, a psychologist and professor of
consumer behavior at the University of Oregon in Eugene. ``Fun has
become a much greater priority for people.''
   Why the surge in Halloween buying?
   ``People buy things to represent their values,'' Kahle said.
``So it makes sense to me that people would be involved in (buying)
things that are especially fun.''
   Halloween also provides an opportunity to escape.
   ``The society we live in today is a very fast-moving, rapid
society. This is an opportunity to go back to our childhood ... to
a time when we think that life was a lot easier. It also gives us
an opportunity to be anything that we want to be for that one
day,'' said Philip Morris, head of Morris Costumes Inc., which
distributes and manufactures costumes in Charlotte, N.C., Chicago
and Los Angeles.
   ``It's controlled scream therapy where once a year you can
scream and be totally acceptable in doing it,'' added Sheehan, who
stocks 35,000 costumes.
   Morris said his company manufactured 60,000 Freddy Krueger masks
of the gruesome character from ``Nightmare on Elm Street.'' They
could have sold twice that number, he said.
   Children and adults alike are wearing more professional
costumes, Sheehan said. Mothers who in years past sewed a costume
for their children are working today and don't have time to make
them anymore.
   The rise of the young urban professional and discretionary
income also means people have more cash to spend on themselves,
Sheehan believes.
   Halloween can't compete with other holidays, like Christmas or
Presidents Day, when it comes to general sales, according to the
National Association of Retail Merchants. Granted, people don't
rush out and buy a microwave or clothes for Halloween.
   But a look in any store after Sept. 1 is a strong indication
that Halloween has its place in retail sales.
   As for Halloween candy, it doesn't matter whether its for kids
or adults.
   ``Halloween is one of the largest candy-selling holidays of the
year,'' said Philip Kimball of the National Confectioners
Association.
   A survey commissioned by the the association found that 93
percent of households with children under 12 will participate in
Halloween festivities either by trick or treating or giving treats
away, Kimball said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 29-30</NOTE>
