<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0331</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined slightly today in a
session dominated by takeover and buyout news.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 4.80 to 2,178.70
by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 558 up, 832 down and
514 unchanged.
   Takeover developments from late last week and the weekend sent
several prominent stocks higher.
   Kraft jumped 10| to 102|. The company rejected a $90-a-share
takeover bid from Philip Morris, and proposed instead a
recapitalization plan it valued at at least $110 a share.
   RJR Nabisco climbed 8~ to 85|. Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
said it had organized a company to offer $90 a share for RJR, which
said last week it was considering a management buyout.
   West Point Pepperell rose 4\ to 49{. William Farley, chairman of
Fruit Of The Loom Inc., began a $48-a-share bid for the company.
   Chicago Pacific gained 13] to 56}, and Maytag fell 2{ to 24,
after Maytag announced plans to acquire Chicago Pacific.
   Given the frantic deal-making pace, analysts said, other stocks
tended to suffer from neglect.
   The takeover wave has helped carry stock prices lately to new
highs since the crash last fall. But some observers worry that it
might eventually lead to trouble for the market, by heaping huge
new amounts of debt on an already-extended economy.
   Energy stocks were weak as the price of oil tumbled. Amoco
dropped 1| to 74\; Chevron | to 46]; Mobil { to 45}, and Atlantic
Richfield 1\ to 81{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.24 to 159.18. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .97 at 305.10.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 119.49 million shares with two
hours to go.
