<HEAD>Stocks Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with closing figures.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Monday on the London Stock
Exchange as worries about interest rates persisted.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 10.9
points, or 0.6 percent, to 1,848.4. It had been as high as 1,856.5
in the afternoon.
   Volume was light, as 464 million shares changed hands, compared
with the 484.2 million shares Friday.
   Share prices were marked down across the board in the absence of
news affecting speculative situations, a major force giving the
market its recent buoyancy, dealers said.
   ``We're just wandering around right now without much
direction,'' one equity salesman contended.
   Analysts said the possibility that interest rates may be headed
higher weighed on the market which is looking toward Thursday's
scheduled release of British trade figures.
   Oil company shares fell on disappointment that the three-day
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries committee talks in
Madrid failed to come up with a new production ceiling for the
13-member cartel.
   Mining finance and precious metal shares dipped in sympathy with
oils, dealers said, pulling the broader market lower.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was down 9.9 points at
1,499.4 at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 4.71
points to close at 1,050.20.
</TEXT>
