<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Airlines     10-24 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Airlines,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NWA's Profit Up 33.2 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NWA Inc. reported that strong passenger
traffic helped to boost its third-quarter profit 33.2 percent from
a year earlier and to lift quarterly earnings over $100 million for
the first time.
   The parent of Northwest Airlines said Monday that its net income
in the three months ended Sept. 30 jumped to $116.3 million, or
$3.98 a share, from $87.3 million, or $2.89 a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose to $1.61 billion from $1.44 billion.
   ``These results are the highest quarterly profits in our 62-year
history and mark the first time net earnings for a quarter exceeded
$100 million,'' said NWA Chairman Steven G. Rothmeier.
   ``Our third-quarter results were characterized by strong
passenger traffic and improved yield _ the measurement of revenue
per passenger mile,'' Rothmeier said in a statement.
   A passenger mile represents one paying passenger flown one mile
and is used to determine an airline's capacity.
   Northwest had a 5.6 percent increase in passenger traffic over
the third quarter of 1987, Rothmeier said.
   In the first nine months of the year, NWA earned $101.1 million,
or $3.47 a share, compared with $103 million, or $3.59 a share, in
the year-earlier period. The third-quarter profit offset a net loss
in the first half of the year.
   Nine-month revenue rose to $4.23 billion from $3.93 billion a
year earlier.
   Rothmeier also announced that NWA has reached an agreement in
principle to add Air Canada and Canadian Airlines International as
owners of PARS, a computer reservations system co-owned by
Northwest and Trans World Airlines Inc.
   The final agreement is expected to expand the PARS network to
more than 3,500 travel agencies in Canada in addition to more than
6,300 U.S. travel agencies now served by PARS, Rothmeier said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
