<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Finish Mostly Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid disappointment over slack
export sales and improved growing conditions for South American
crops.
   Soybeans, corn and oats ended substantially lower but wheat
finished down only slightly due to a late rebound on news that
China was seeking 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices.
   And the Agriculture Department's weekly report on grain
inspections for export, which was released after the close,
indicated greater movement of corn last week than expected,
analysts said.
   The USDA's report that 53.7 million bushels of corn were
inspected last week was ``really quite favorable,'' said Dale
Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   ``It was surprisingly good in light of the light vessel count we
saw at Gulf,'' he said.
   Soybean prices retreated on reports of fairly heavy weekend
showers in Brazil and forecasts for more rain by midweek in both
Brazil and Argentina, Gustafson said.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 4\ cents lower with
December at $4.17{ a bushel; corn was unchanged to 4} cents lower
with December at $2.79 a bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 5{ cents
lower with December at $2.44} a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to
10} cents lower with November at $7.64} a bushel
</TEXT>
