<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1915EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MorrellSuit     10-24 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Morrell Suit,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Files $35 Million Suit Against Morrell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the United Food & Commercial
Workers Union filed a $35 million lawsuit Monday in federal court
against John Morrell & Co. seeking unpaid wages and overtime over
the past three years.
   The court filing said Morrell, the nation's fifth-largest
meatpacker, failed to pay production workers for about 20 to 30
minutes of time spent each day putting on, taking off and cleaning
required safety equipment at its plants in Sioux City, Sioux Falls,
S.D., and Arkansas City, Kan. The suit could affect about 5,000
workers at Morrell plants, the union said.
   ``What they're basically doing is not paying you for every hour
you work,'' Ron Haase, chief steward of Local 1142 in Sioux City,
told a news conference.
   The suit was filed in U.S. District Court in Sioux City by 11
present and former workers at Morrell's Sioux City and Sioux Falls
plants, and incorporates claims by 185 other employees at Sioux
City and 352 others at Sioux Falls. Morrell is a subsidiary of the
Cincinnati-based United Brands.
   UFCW President William H. Wynn said in a news release from
Washington that the suit seeks $17.5 million in unpaid wages and
overtime, $17.5 million in ``liquidated damages'' and an injunction
barring Morrell from continuing willful violations of the federal
Fair Labor Standards Act.
   Morrell officials in Sioux City were in a meeting Monday and
could not be reached for comment. Officials at its parent compnay,
United Brands Co. in Cincinnati, did not return telephone calls.
   In the court filing, the workers said Morrell requires each
employee to clean safety equipment at the end of each shift and
some are required to clean equipment at meal breaks.
   Most of the workers who were not paid for cleaning the equipment
should have been compensated at the overtime pay rate of time and a
half, the union said.
   The court papers said Morrell ``continually required as a
condition of employment that its production workers handle and
clean required safety equipment.'' Such equipment includes steel
mesh aprons and gloves, arm guards and belly guards, the suit said.
   The union said the U.S. Labor Department sued IBP Inc. for
similar violations in 1986, and that IBP is contesting the claims
for back pay.
   Wynn pointed out that the filing came on the 50th anniversary of
the Fair Labor Standards Act.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881024-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1919EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PanAm-Labor     10-24 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pan Am-Labor,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am Flight Attendants File Age Discrimination Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flight attendants union at Pan Am Corp. has
filed a complaint with the federal government accusing the airline
of age discrimination in the recent closing of its San Francisco
base.
   The Independent Union of Flight Attendants, which represents
some 4,300 attendants at Pan Am, said it filed the discrimination
complaint on Oct. 13 with the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission.
   Pan Am hadn't seen the complaint yet and had no immediate
comment on the action, spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon said Monday. She
said it was the first such complaint filed against the airline in
recent years.
   The company's closing of the base on Oct. 1 was a ``purposeful
attempt'' to phase out older, higher paid and more experienced
flight attendants in favor of younger employees, Margaret Brennan,
president of the Pan Am local, said in a statement.
   ``Pan Am's trying to bring us back to the day of `no wrinkles in
the aisles,''' Ms. Brennan said. ``More than 100 of the 245 flight
attendants based in San Francisco were over the age of 40.''
   More than 90 percent of the 245 attendants were earning salaries
in Pan Am's higher wage scale, ranging up to $40,000 a year, the
union said. Current starting salaries for flight attendants at the
airline are about $10,000 to $12,000 annually.
   In its charge, the union is asking the EEOC for an
investigation, the reopening of the base, and damages to be paid to
flight attendants who retired early, were transferred or were laid
off as a result of the closure.
   As of mid-October, 19 attendants at the base had accepted early
retirement and 95 had been laid off, the union said. It said that
``many'' other attendants, now commuting from San Francisco to
other Pan Am bases, are expected to accept furlough or early
retirement.
   An age discrimination charge may be filed with the EEOC if the
party involved is over 40 years old and feels that he or she was
discriminated against because of age. The commission has agreed to
look into the flight attendants' charge, indicating that it
believes there may be merit in the accusation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
