<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1924EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NissanExpansion     10-24 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nissan Expansion,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nissan To Expand Its Smyrna, Tenn., Plant For Another U.S.-Made
Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. U.S.A. on Monday
announced an anticipated expansion of its car and truck plant in
Tennessee, saying it planned to add a third assembly line and use
it for passenger cars.
   The expansion was approved earlier this month by Nissan's board
of directors, but announcement was held until Monday. Nissan
already builds its Sentra cars and light trucks at the Smyrna,
Tenn., plant.
   However, the announcement didn't indicate the investment Nissan
would be making in the expansion, the kind of car to be made there
or production dates and capacities.
   It said a task force with members from the company's U.S. arm
and the parent company in Japan would study the project for three
months.
   ``We have been asking for the opportunity to expand our capacity
for some time,'' said Jerry Benefield, president and chief
executive officer of Nissan Motor Manufacturing. ``We are very
happy and proud that our board of directors and parent company have
given all of us at Nissan in Tennessee this vote of confidence.''
   It is the latest in a series of projects Nissan has announced
this year for the United States.
   In April, Nissan's board approved spending $31.1 million to
begin producing bumpers and assembling engines and truck axles at
the Tennessee plant, southeast of Nashville.
   Last month, Nissan and Ford Motor Co. announced a joint venture
to produce minivans at Ford's Avon Lake, Ohio, truck plant.
   And last week, Nissan Research and Development Inc. broke ground
for a $50 million research and design facility in Farmington Hills,
northwest of Detroit. Officials said among its projects would be
designing a new vehicle for the U.S. market.
   Nissan spokesman David Fox said Monday that initial plans call
for most of the new cars built at the Smyrna expansion plant to be
sold in the United States, but the company wasn't ruling out
shipping some cars overseas.
   Analyst Joseph Phillippi of the investment firm Shearson Lehman
Hutton in New York speculated that Nissan, like Honda, may be
positioning itself for penetration of the European market.
   ``I guess the intriguing thing is ... with respect to Europe in
1992,'' he said. ``There's a lot of discussion in Europe as to what
is a Japanese car and what is a transplant.
   ``If you build a Honda here with 80 percent U.S. content, is it
a car from Japan or a car from the United States?'' he asked.
   European countries have entered into a variety of trade
agreements, quotas and voluntary restraints with Japan limiting the
number of Japanese cars coming to the continent.
   Nissan's Smyrna plant, with a 3,200-employee work force, was
designed in 1980 with room for expansion. The company said as early
as last February it was looking into expanding the factory.
   American Honda Motor Co. Inc. runs two assembly lines in
Marysville, Ohio, and will add a third in East Liberty, Ohio, in
the fall of next year.
   Toyota Motor Manufacturing U.S.A. Inc. has a plant near
Georgetown, Ky., which operates one assembly line and shares two
production lines with General Motors Corp. in their joint venture,
New United Motor Manufacturing Inc., in Fremont, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
