up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, The Delaware ...; ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. announced Monday that
Chairman Carl Icahn's plan to take the airline private has been
completed.
   TWA said the way for the privatization plan was cleared when a
Delaware court denied a request by some TWA shareholders for an
immediate injunction blocking the scheme.
   The Delaware Chancery Court rejected late Friday the injunction
requested last summer by several TWA shareholders, said Mark
Buckstein, the airline's general counsel. He said the request was
denied on the grounds that if the dissident shareholders aren't
satisfied with the amount they receive for selling their stock to
Icahn, they would be able to file for damages against him.
   The shareholders' suit seeking damages as a result of the
privatization plan is still pending in the Delaware court.
   Last week, the TWA pilots union withdrew its petition for an
injunction blocking Icahn's plan. The pilots retained their lawsuit
against the privatization proposal, however.
   The pilots' withdrawal of the petition, which came at a
preliminary hearing in New York State Supreme Court, was in return
for a guarantee that Icahn gave at the hearing. The financithan $1.
