<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Arco-Lyondell     10-24 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Arco-Lyondell,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arco Considers Sale of Part Interest in Texas Chemical Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantic Richfield Co. announced it is
considering selling stock in its Lyondell Petrochemical Co.
subsidiary to the public while retaining a controlling interest in
the Texas firm.
   Arco's board of directors ordered a study of the plan Monday,
and hasn't decided definitely whether to make the public offering,
the company said.
   Lyondell produces petrochemicals in Channelview, Texas, and has
an oil refinery in Houston.
   If the stock offering proceeds, Arco would sell about 50 percent
of Lyondell and retain slightly less than half of the stock, the
company said.
   Money raised through the stock sale would be used for general
corporate purposes at Arco, including expansion of a stock
repurchase program.
   Arco also said it was considering having Lyondell take out $500
million in loans, and transferring that amount to Arco in a special
distribution if the stock offering proceeds.
   The announcement came as Arco, the eighth largest U.S. oil
compnay, reported a 24 percent increase in its profit for the third
quarter to $391 million, or $2.17 a share, from $315 million, or
$1.71 a share, a year earlier. It said the profit at Lyondell
jumped to $156 million from $23 million.
</TEXT>
