<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1937EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Boeing-Spokane     10-24 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing-Spokane,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing To Build Manufacturing Plant Near Spokane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. will build a small manufacturing
plant near Spokane that should initially employ about 350 people to
make air conditioning ducting for the aerospace company's
jetliners, company officials said Monday.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton said the
manufacturing facility will manufacture fiberglass and Kevlar
ducting and will research automated production of jetliner floor
paneling. The facility could eventually produce floor panels for
all of Boeing's commercial jetliners.
   Construction is scheduled to begin next spring, with production
starting in spring 1990 at one of two undisclosed sites in the
Spokane area, Thornton said.
   The 230,000-square-foot, $20 million plant will produce ducting
used in air conditioning in Boeing jetliners. The finished ducts
will be shipped by truck to Boeing plants at Everett and Renton,
Thornton said.
   The manufacturing facility is the first step toward future
expansion, Thornton said. If development of the floor panel
manufacturing portion is successful, as many as 500 people could be
employed, he said.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes' fabrication plants make various
airplane components and are principally located in Auburn, although
the company also has such operations in Gresham, Ore.; Winnipeg,
Manitoba; Oak Ridge, Tenn.; and Macon, Ga.
   The company broke ground on a $235 million sheet-metal
manufacturing center in Auburn in July. That plant is intended to
replace Auburn's existing sheet-metal facility. In September, the
company also announced a $20 million expansion of its Gresham plant.
   Also in July, Boeing announced the signing of a three-year
contract with Kaiser Aluminum & Chemical Co. to supply sheet and
plate aluminum from its Trentwood rolling mill near Spokane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
