<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1944EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-UnionCarbide     10-24 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Union Carbide,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Carbide Reports Net Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. on Monday reported its
third-quarter profits nearly tripled amid sales increases in each
of the company's operating units.
   Net income during the quarter ended Sept. 30 totaled $213
million, or $1.49 a share on a fully diluted basis, up from $74
million, or 55 cents a share in the year-ago period.
   Consolidated sales for the third quarter jumped 22 percent to
$2.11 billion, compared with $1.73 billion a year ago.
   Chairman Robert D. Kennedy said the strong performance reflects
the upswing for chemicals generally and Carbide's strong position
in the markets that it serves.
   George Krug, senior chemical analyst with Eberstadt Fleming in
New York, said he was not surprised at Carbide's performance.
   ``Profits for all commodity chemical producers have gone through
the roof,'' Krug said.
   He said chemical companies are raising prices ``dramatically''
while costs are down. But Krug predicted that next year earnings
will be lower because prices will ``ease off.''
   For the first nine months of 1988, Carbide said net income
jumped 140 percent to $501 million, or $3.55 a share on a fully
diluted basis, compared with $209 million, or $1.57 a share in the
first nine months of 1987.
   Consolidated sales for the nine-month period were $6.19 billion,
up 22 percent from $5.07 billion a year ago.
</TEXT>
