<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-24 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rallies; Gold Prices Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose Monday, partly in reaction to a
Treasury Department report that said strength in the dollar this
year would not slow down reduction of the huge U.S. trade deficit.
   Gold prices fell $3 an ounce or more following an inconclusive
weekend meeting of eight oil producers. Republic National Bank of
New York said gold bullion was bid at $405.50 a troy ounce as of 4
p.m. EDT, down from $408.50 an ounce late Friday.
   In a report required by Congress, the Treasury Department said
it did not expect the dollar's rise from its lows of January to
``significantly alter'' prospects for continued progress on
shrinking the trade gap.
   Some currency traders saw the report as a sign that the Reagan
administration was not in favor of a continued fall in the dollar.
   ``It's the first salvo just to give notice to the market that it
is not a one-way street,'' said Charles E. Minnaar, a vice
president at Chase Manhattan Bank.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar edged up 0.20 yen to a closing 126.60. Later, in
London, it was quoted at the same rate. In New York, the dollar
rose to 127.02 yen from 126.28 yen late Friday.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound, which was
quoted at $1.7520, cheaper than $1.7620 late Friday. In New York,
the pound fell to $1.7501 from $1.7615 Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7898 West German marks, up from 1.7778; 1.5175
Swiss francs, up from 1.5061; 1.1986 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1992; 6.1100 French francs, up from 6.0900; and 1,332.88 Italian
lire, up from 1,327.50.
   The New York rates are based on quotes before the Treasury
Department report was issued to Congress at 4 p.m. EDT. An hour
after that, the dollar was at 1.7930 West German marks, 126.97 yen
and 1.7485 British pounds.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7860 West German marks, down from 1.7875; 1.5145
Swiss francs, up from 1.5135; 6.1025 French francs, down from
6.1115; 2.0143 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0170; 1,330.85 Italian
lire, down from 1,332.50; and 1.1973 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2022.
   Bullion dealers said the slide in gold prices followed the
failure of eight member nations of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to reach any firm agreement on restraining
production during a meeting in Spain.
   They said a tip toward the bearish side on the technical charts
added to the downward pressure on gold.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at $408.20 a troy ounce bid, down from
$411.10 an ounce on Saturday. In London, gold fell to $405.15 an
ounce from $410.15 late Friday. In Zurich, it fell to $405.50 an
ounce from $409.40 late Friday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $405.80 a troy ounce from $408.40 an ounce Friday.
   Silver was quoted in London on Monday at a late bid of $6.23 a
troy ounce, down from Friday's $6.28. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $6.197 a troy ounce from
$6.223 Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
