<FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-SmithKline     10-24 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-SmithKline,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restructuring Charge Lowers SmithKline Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp. on Monday reported
it lost $195.5 million in the third quarter because of a one-time
charge associated with a major restructuring.
   The Philadelphia-based pharmaceutical giant, which has been
reeling from a plunge in sales of its two leading drugs, said it
would have made $97.1 million, or 79 cents per share, without the
$389.3 million charge.
   In the year-ago period, SmithKline reported profits of $149.6
million, or $1.18 a share.
   Sales during the quarter totaled $1.17 billion, up from $1.10
billion during the same 1987 period.
   The one-time charge against pretax earnings was announced Sept.
27 as payment for a corporate restructuring, which will combine
pharmaceutical units worldwide into Smith Kline & French
Laboratories, consolidate manufacturing capacity and eliminate
1,600 jobs.
   The charge includes the costs of closing facilities, severance
expenses, pension enhancements, write-downs of certain assets and
reserves for estimated liabilities.
   In a statement, Henry Wendt, chairman and chief executive
officer, said sales of the drug Tagamet dropped 18 percent
worldwide, with U.S. sales down 40 percent and international sales
up 9 percent. U.S. sales of Dyazide, the company's other leading
drug, also decreased, he said.
   ``Wholesalers and retailers of Tagamet and Dyazide continued to
work down the large inventory of product they had on hand,'' Wendt
said. ``We hope to return to more normal buying patterns in the
fourth quarter.''
   Profits for the first nine months of 1988 fell 84 percent to
$69.8 million, or 56 cents a share, from $428.1 million or $3.36 a
share in 1987. Sales rose to $3.47 billion from $3.13 billion.
</TEXT>
