<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-24 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0837</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Prices Dive On Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices took their sharpest dive in nearly four
months Monday on New York's Commodity Exchange as traders took
profits after bidding up prices to an all-time high last week.
   On other markets, precious metals futures declined as energy
prices tumbled; pork bellies rallied strongly; livestock futures
were mixed; grains and soybeans were mostly lower; and stock-index
futures retreated.
   The Comex spot copper price plunged 3.85 cents to $1.414 a pound
while the contract for delivery in December fell 3 cents to
$1.3325, the steepest drop in the copper market since July 1.
   Analysts said copper prices were due for a correction after
climbing by 60 percent since early August to a record $1.465 a
pound during Friday's trading. The spot price settled Friday below
the record level reached during the day.
   Monday's stronger dollar and weaker oil prices provided a
bearish backdrop for the entire metals complex.
   But the strongest sell signal for copper traders appeared to be
the London Metal Exchange's report of a 7,900-metric-ton decline
last week in its warehouse stocks of the metal. The market had been
expecting a steeper drop in LME stocks, said Fred Demler, metals
economist with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   Analyst James Steel of Refco Inc. in New York, said LME stocks
of copper have fallen as low as they were late last December, when
spot copper soared to $1.46 a pound.
   Although the spot copper price surpassed that level last week,
Steel noted the December contract had risen only as high as $1.382
compared with $1.41 last year.
   ``We're still a few cents under last year's high and that was
something of a signal for profit-taking,'' he said. ``But it's only
natural to be pullling back and taking some profits after the highs
of last week.''
   Steel said he expected copper prices to fall further, perhaps as
low as $1.30 for December delivery, before rising again.
   Fred Demler, metals economist with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said the December copper price could fall as low as $1.12 and still
not break the market's bullish momentum.
   Precious metals futures prices fell moderately on the Comex in
reaction to the sharp drop in oil prices, analysts said.
   Gold settled $2.60 to $3.10 lower with December at $408.80 a
troy ounce; silver was 2.6 cents to 3 cents lower with December at
$6.255 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures plummeted on the New York Mercantile Exchange in
reaction to the failure of eight OPEC oil ministers to reach an
agreement to curb crude-oil production at a meeting that ended
during the weekend.
   ``I think this is an example of unrealistic expectations in a
market ripe for disappointment,'' said Peter Beutel, an energy
analyst with Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 94 cents to $1.20
lower with December at $13.17 a barrel; heating oil was 1.84 cents
to 2.81 cents lower with November at 39.90 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.26 cents to 2 cents lower with November at 49.96
cents a gallon.
   Frozen pork belly futures prices soared in a technical rally
inspired by the market's refusal to fall sharply in reaction to
Friday's weekly cold-storage report from the Agriculture Department.
   The USDA reported about 1 million more pounds of pork bellies in
cold storage than the market had expected.
   Hog prices advanced with the bellies while cattle futures rose
in reaction to cash cattle prices as high as $74 per hundredweight,
the highest packer price paid since spring, analysts said.
   Live cattle settled unchanged to .47 cent higher with December
at 74.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .47 cent
higher with October at 81.95 cents a pound; hogs were .17 cent to
.55 cent higher with December at 42.25 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.60 cents to 1.75 cents higher with February at 51.25
cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mostly lower on the Chicago
Board ofTrade amid disappointment over slack export sales and
improved growing conditions for South American soybeans.
   Soybeans, corn and oats ended substantially lower but wheat
settled mixed due to a late rebound on news that China was seeking
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Wheat settled 3\ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with December at
$4.18} a bushel; corn was \ cent to 6 cents lower with December at
$2.77{ a bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 5{ cents lower with December
at $2.44} a bushel; soybeans were 10\ cents lower to 1 cent higher
with November at $7.65{ a bushel.
   Stock-index futures closed modestly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of
the Standard & Poor's 500 settled 1.35 points lower at 283.65.
</TEXT>
