<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Computer     10-24 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Computer,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Compaq Earnings Jump 58 Percent; Cray Off 37 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two stars of the computer industry reported diverging
third-quarter results Monday, as Compaq Computer Corp. recorded a
59 percent profit gain and Cray Research Inc. posted a 37 percent
decline.
   Compaq said its profit gain came on a 60 percent increase in
sales as the Houston-based personal computer maker continued to
benefit from strong demand for its powerful personal computers.
   Cray, the world's leading manufacturer of supercomputers, said
its profit drop came on a 21 percent decline in sales. It predicted
a bulge in sales in the fourth quarter, resulting in a roughly 10
percent revenue gain for the full year, but said the profit gain
for the year would be limited to 5 percent to 7 percent because of
unexpectedly high costs of research and development.
   Compaq said it earned $58 million, or $1.40 a share on a fully
diluted basis, up from $36 million, or 94 cents a share, a year
earlier. Revenue rose to $501.6 million from $313.5 million.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Compaq said its
earnings rose 87 percent to $163 million, or $4.06 a share on a
fully diluted basis, from $87 million, or $2.29 a share, a year
earlier. Revenue rose 76.4 percent to $1.40 billion from $792
million.
   The earnings per share are calculated on the basis of what they
would be assuming they are diluted by an increase in the number of
outstanding shares through conversion of all convertible securities
into common stock.
   Compaq is the leader in sales of personal computers based on
Intel Corp.'s 80386, the chip maker's fastest microprocessor.
   Cray Research, of Minneapolis, said its profit in the quarter
fell to $22.6 million, or 73 cents a share, down from $36.1
million, or $1.14 a share, a year earlier. Revenue fell to $145.2
million from $184.6 million.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Cray said its
profit fell 40 percent to $68.1 million, or $2.19 a share, from
$113.0 million, or $3.57 a share, a year earlier. Revenue fell 19
percent to $425.4 million from $523.7 million.
</TEXT>
