<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FortHoward     10-24 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fort Howard,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fort Howard Returns To Private Ownership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Management at Fort Howard Corp., with
help from a New York investment firm, on Monday completed a $3.55
billion buyout that returns the paper manufacturer to private
ownership.
   The buyout, first proposed in June by Morgan Stanley Group Inc,
was led by Fort Howard's chief executive and chairman Paul J.
Schierl, president Donald H. De Meuse and Kathleen J. Hempel,
executive vice president.
   About 150 people, most shareholders, attended a meeting at the
company's headquarters to observe the completion of the buyout.
   The meeting was a formality since those controlling nearly 80
percent of Fort Howard's stock accepted the $53-per-share offer.
Only a simple majority of the approximately 68 million shares was
required to complete the deal.
   Shareholders who have not tendered stock have been advised to do
so shortly to guarantee they will receive payment.
   The company was organized privately in 1919 by Austin Cofrin and
went public in 1971.
</TEXT>
