<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Farmers     10-24 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Farmers,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurer's Profit Up 6 Percent in 3rd Qtr.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Group Inc. said Monday that its
profit rose 6 percent in the third quarter, although it spent $8.2
million in an unsuccessful fight against a buyout by Batus Inc.
   Farmers said Monday it earned $65.9 million, or 96 cents a
share, up from $62.1 million, or 90 cents a share, in the third
quarter of 1987. Revenue in the quarter ended Sept. 30 was $302.1
million, up from $287.6 million a year earlier.
   After an acrimonious eight-month battle, Farmers agreed in
August to be bought by Batus, a Louisville, Ky.-based tobacco,
retailing and paper conglomerate, for $5.2 billion cash. The merger
awaits approval by regulators in three states, Ohio, Oregon and
Kansas.
   Farmers said Monday it spent $8.2 million in the third quarter
fighting the takeover, and a total of $15.8 million over the course
of the year.
   Farmers, the nation's third-biggest home and auto insurer and
seventh-largest property and casualty insurer, attributed its
higher revenue to higher premiums, more policies sold, cost control
and a lower tax rate.
   In the first nine months of 1988, Farmers reported a profit of
$205.9 million, or $3 a share, up 13 percent from the profit of
$181.5 million, or $2.62 a share, in the same period of 1987.
Revenue for the first three quarters was $888.7 million, up from
$830.6 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
